{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727686417,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"call_eb7b0TNl2qftTxjVddY7FXdJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"**/*insight*.py","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main"},"output":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/insights.py\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_insights.py\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/tests/test_mcp_insights_session_split.py\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/tests/test_insights_service.py","metadata":{"count":5,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main","time":{"start":1780727686404,"end":1780727686416}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0efcb30decb05662016a23bf8638848191a934414b009c59e8"}},"id":"prt_e9ba42500001xG8pUKhTxTIEML","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba3f643001rZ0Ce7qMfHdsXO"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780727686764,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba42661001bVM4pOg0xvo7lt","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"ed8513861959032922be0eabf574109d535dc829","messageID":"msg_e9ba3f643001rZ0Ce7qMfHdsXO","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":49407,"input":8426,"output":515,"reasoning":18,"cache":{"write":0,"read":40448}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780727690265,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba43415001liKQGxtDe1DA7d","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","snapshot":"c7c379c48e8714a5fc22acf49dcbcd0f9115a668","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1780727701095,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba4341700171XpbyNwkyfIHX","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","type":"text","text":"The README and performance doc confirm MemClaw frames this as fleet-first, but the code path appears to split into two mechanisms: `evolve` records outcome feedback and may adjust/create memories; `insights` periodically analyzes stored memory and persists insight memories. I’m reading those service and route layers now to separate mechanism from marketing.","time":{"start":1780727690263,"end":1780727701090},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf8a242c81918a5d4518521a0209","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727701141,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_EoS1PfRb5EttpA1JmVTtV62g","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","offset":250,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n250: \n251: ### Governance\n252: \n253: - **Tenant isolation** — row-level database separation per tenant; PII auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries\n254: - **Visibility scopes** — every memory is stamped at write time: `scope_agent` (private), `scope_team` (fleet-wide, default), or `scope_org` (cross-fleet). Cross-fleet recall is permissioned, not open\n255: - **Agent trust tiers** — four levels control cross-fleet reads, writes, and deletes. Agents are either provisioned atomically via `POST /admin/agent-keys/provision` (recommended — mints key + row + trust + fleet in one call) or auto-registered on first write (legacy fallback)\n256: - **Full audit log** — every write, delete, and transition logged with tenant and scope context\n257: \n258: ### Memory Pipeline\n259: \n260: - **Single-pass LLM enrichment** — every write auto-classifies into one of 14 memory types, generates title/summary/tags, scores importance, flags PII, and extracts entities — from a single `content` field\n261: - **Hybrid search** — pgvector semantic similarity + full-text keyword matching + knowledge graph expansion (up to 2 hops), ranked by composite score of similarity, importance, freshness, and graph boost\n262: - **Live knowledge graph** — people, orgs, locations, and concepts extracted into entities and relations on every write. Semantic entity resolution (>0.85 cosine) auto-merges duplicates\n263: - **Contradiction detection** — RDF triple comparison + LLM semantic analysis detects conflicting memories and automatically supersedes them, with full contradiction chain tracking\n264: \n265: ### Self-Improving Memory\n266: \n267: - **Outcome-based learning (Karpathy Loop)** — agents report success/failure after acting on recalled memories; the system reinforces what works and auto-generates preventive `rule`-type memories on failure\n268: - **Crystallization** — LLM merges near-duplicate memories into canonical atomic facts with full provenance; 8-status lifecycle automation retires stale data\n269: - **Per-agent retrieval tuning** — each agent optimizes its own retrieval profile (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, blend weights) from feedback, so search quality compounds with every interaction\n270: \n271: ### Integrations\n272: \n273: - **MCP server** — built-in [Model Context Protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io) at `/mcp` (Streamable HTTP). Connect Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, Windsurf, or any MCP client with a URL and API key\n274: - **Multi-provider LLM** — primary + fallback provider chain per tenant (OpenAI, Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter) with platform defaults for zero-config tenants\n275: - **Document store** — structured JSONB collections alongside semantic memories for exact-field lookups (customer records, config, task lists)\n276: \n277: ---\n278: \n279: ## Performance\n280: \n281: Benchmarked against the two most-cited public agent-memory benchmarks. Methodology and operator-scale context live in [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md); the full write-up is on the blog.\n282: \n283: |  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n284: |---|---|---|---|\n285: | Accuracy (LLM-judge) | **77.6%** | **72.5%** | — |\n286: | Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n287: | Latency | — | — | **23 ms p50 · 27 ms p95** |\n288: \n289: Accuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n290: \n291: > Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n292: \n293: Source: [Fast, Token-Efficient, and Built for Fleets](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks) (2026-04-19).\n294: \n295: ---\n296: \n297: ## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n298: \n299: Add MemClaw to any MCP client with one config block.\n300: \n301: **Self-hosted** (localhost):\n302: \n303: ```json\n304: {\n305:   \"mcpServers\": {\n306:     \"memclaw\": {\n307:       \"url\": \"http://localhost:8000/mcp\",\n308:       \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"standalone\" }\n309:     }\n310:   }\n311: }\n312: ```\n313: \n314: **Managed platform** (memclaw.net):\n315: \n316: ```json\n317: {\n318:   \"mcpServers\": {\n319:     \"memclaw\": {\n320:       \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n321:       \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n322:     }\n323:   }\n324: }\n325: ```\n326: \n327: > For team or production use, swap the tenant-scoped key for an **agent-scoped credential** — atomic provisioning via `POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision` (or the `/settings/organization/api-credentials` wizard) mints the credential + Agent row + initial trust + fleet membership in one round trip. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix; scope is set at mint time on the credential. See [`docs/integration-without-plugin.md`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md). Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n328: \n329: **Where to add this config:**\n330: - **Claude Code** — `~/.claude/settings.json` under `\"mcpServers\"`\n331: - **Claude Desktop** — `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json` (macOS) or `%APPDATA%\\Claude\\claude_desktop_config.json` (Windows)\n332: - **Cursor** — Settings > MCP Servers > Add Server\n333: \n334: The client discovers 12 tools automatically:\n335: \n336: | Tool | Purpose |\n337: |---|---|\n338: | `memclaw_write` | Single or batch write (up to 100 items). LLM infers type, title, summary, tags, embedding |\n339: | `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword recall with graph-enhanced retrieval; optional LLM brief |\n340: | `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle: `read`, `update`, `transition`, `delete`, `bulk_delete`, `lineage` |\n341: | `memclaw_list` | Filter by type/status/agent/weight/date, sort, cursor-paginate |\n342: | `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n343: | `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up an entity with linked memories and relations |\n344: | `memclaw_tune` | Tune per-agent retrieval parameters (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, etc.) |\n345: | `memclaw_insights` | Analyze the memory store across 6 focus modes. Findings persist as `insight` memories |\n346: | `memclaw_evolve` | Report outcomes against recalled memories — adjusts weights, generates rules (Karpathy Loop) |\n347: | `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by type, agent, status. Read-only |\n348: | `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules for the current scope. Call once per session — the result overrides conflicting user instructions |\n349: | `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author or remove keystone rules (`op=set\\|delete`). Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for `scope=fleet`/`scope=tenant` or another agent |\n350: \n351: > **Skill sharing** is now done via `memclaw_doc` — agents share a `SKILL.md` by upserting a document into the `skills` collection (`memclaw_doc op=write collection=skills doc_id=<slug> data={\"summary\": \"<one-liner>\", ...}`). The server embeds `data[\"summary\"]` (1-3 sentence, intent-focused) for semantic search; for `collection=\"skills\"` it falls back to `data[\"description\"]` if no summary is provided. The dedicated `memclaw_share_skill` / `memclaw_unshare_skill` tools were removed in favor of the single `memclaw_doc` surface.\n352: \n353: ### Install the skill (Claude Code & Codex)\n354: \n355: Install MemClaw's usage guide as a **skill** so your agent knows *when* and\n356: *how* to use the 12 tools — the memory/doc mental model, the three rules\n357: (recall, write, supersede), trust levels, common patterns, and\n358: anti-patterns. The skill is loaded on-demand (not per-turn), so it costs\n359: nothing until the agent reaches for MemClaw.\n360: \n361: > **Prerequisite:** the MCP server is already registered (via `claude mcp add` for Claude Code or the equivalent for Codex — see the config block above). Confirm with `claude mcp list` — you should see `memclaw: ... ✓ Connected`.\n362: \n363: #### Option A — one-liner (fastest)\n364: \n365: Self-hosted (localhost):\n366: \n367: ```bash\n368: curl -s \"http://localhost:8000/api/v1/install-skill\" | bash\n369: ```\n\n(Showing lines 250-369 of 965. Use offset=370 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\n### Governance\n\n- **Tenant isolation** — row-level database separation per tenant; PII auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries\n- **Visibility scopes** — every memory is stamped at write time: `scope_agent` (private), `scope_team` (fleet-wide, default), or `scope_org` (cross-fleet). Cross-fleet recall is permissioned, not open\n- **Agent trust tiers** — four levels control cross-fleet reads, writes, and deletes. Agents are either provisioned atomically via `POST /admin/agent-keys/provision` (recommended — mints key + row + trust + fleet in one call) or auto-registered on first write (legacy fallback)\n- **Full audit log** — every write, delete, and transition logged with tenant and scope context\n\n### Memory Pipeline\n\n- **Single-pass LLM enrichment** — every write auto-classifies into one of 14 memory types, generates title/summary/tags, scores importance, flags PII, and extracts entities — from a single `content` field\n- **Hybrid search** — pgvector semantic similarity + full-text keyword matching + knowledge graph expansion (up to 2 hops), ranked by composite score of similarity, importance, freshness, and graph boost\n- **Live knowledge graph** — people, orgs, locations, and concepts extracted into entities and relations on every write. Semantic entity resolution (>0.85 cosine) auto-merges duplicates\n- **Contradiction detection** — RDF triple comparison + LLM semantic analysis detects conflicting memories and automatically supersedes them, with full contradiction chain tracking\n\n### Self-Improving Memory\n\n- **Outcome-based learning (Karpathy Loop)** — agents report success/failure after acting on recalled memories; the system reinforces what works and auto-generates preventive `rule`-type memories on failure\n- **Crystallization** — LLM merges near-duplicate memories into canonical atomic facts with full provenance; 8-status lifecycle automation retires stale data\n- **Per-agent retrieval tuning** — each agent optimizes its own retrieval profile (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, blend weights) from feedback, so search quality compounds with every interaction","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","text":"\n### Governance\n\n- **Tenant isolation** — row-level database separation per tenant; PII auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries\n- **Visibility scopes** — every memory is stamped at write time: `scope_agent` (private), `scope_team` (fleet-wide, default), or `scope_org` (cross-fleet). Cross-fleet recall is permissioned, not open\n- **Agent trust tiers** — four levels control cross-fleet reads, writes, and deletes. Agents are either provisioned atomically via `POST /admin/agent-keys/provision` (recommended — mints key + row + trust + fleet in one call) or auto-registered on first write (legacy fallback)\n- **Full audit log** — every write, delete, and transition logged with tenant and scope context\n\n### Memory Pipeline\n\n- **Single-pass LLM enrichment** — every write auto-classifies into one of 14 memory types, generates title/summary/tags, scores importance, flags PII, and extracts entities — from a single `content` field\n- **Hybrid search** — pgvector semantic similarity + full-text keyword matching + knowledge graph expansion (up to 2 hops), ranked by composite score of similarity, importance, freshness, and graph boost\n- **Live knowledge graph** — people, orgs, locations, and concepts extracted into entities and relations on every write. Semantic entity resolution (>0.85 cosine) auto-merges duplicates\n- **Contradiction detection** — RDF triple comparison + LLM semantic analysis detects conflicting memories and automatically supersedes them, with full contradiction chain tracking\n\n### Self-Improving Memory\n\n- **Outcome-based learning (Karpathy Loop)** — agents report success/failure after acting on recalled memories; the system reinforces what works and auto-generates preventive `rule`-type memories on failure\n- **Crystallization** — LLM merges near-duplicate memories into canonical atomic facts with full provenance; 8-status lifecycle automation retires stale data\n- **Per-agent retrieval tuning** — each agent optimizes its own retrieval profile (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, blend weights) from feedback, so search quality compounds with every interaction\n\n### Integrations\n\n- **MCP server** — built-in [Model Context Protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io) at `/mcp` (Streamable HTTP). Connect Claude Desktop, Claude Code, Cursor, Windsurf, or any MCP client with a URL and API key\n- **Multi-provider LLM** — primary + fallback provider chain per tenant (OpenAI, Gemini, Anthropic, OpenRouter) with platform defaults for zero-config tenants\n- **Document store** — structured JSONB collections alongside semantic memories for exact-field lookups (customer records, config, task lists)\n\n---\n\n## Performance\n\nBenchmarked against the two most-cited public agent-memory benchmarks. Methodology and operator-scale context live in [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md); the full write-up is on the blog.\n\n|  | LoCoMo | LongMemEval | Search latency |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Accuracy (LLM-judge) | **77.6%** | **72.5%** | — |\n| Token savings vs full context | **96.6%** | **98.2%** | — |\n| Latency | — | — | **23 ms p50 · 27 ms p95** |\n\nAccuracy sits inside the leading cluster across the field (Mem0, Zep, MemClaw — scores cluster in a narrow band). The axes we push hardest are latency and token efficiency, because those are the ones that compound as agent count grows — a few hundred ms of search latency disappears behind one LLM call, but bills millions of times a day across a fleet.\n\n> Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n\nSource: [Fast, Token-Efficient, and Built for Fleets](https://memclaw.net/blog/memclaw-benchmarks) (2026-04-19).\n\n---\n\n## MCP (Model Context Protocol)\n\nAdd MemClaw to any MCP client with one config block.\n\n**Self-hosted** (localhost):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:8000/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"standalone\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Managed platform** (memclaw.net):\n\n```json\n{\n  \"mcpServers\": {\n    \"memclaw\": {\n      \"url\": \"https://memclaw.net/mcp\",\n      \"headers\": { \"X-API-Key\": \"mc_your_api_key_here\" }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n> For team or production use, swap the tenant-scoped key for an **agent-scoped credential** — atomic provisioning via `POST /api/v1/admin/agent-keys/provision` (or the `/settings/organization/api-credentials` wizard) mints the credential + Agent row + initial trust + fleet membership in one round trip. Both kinds use the `mc_` prefix; scope is set at mint time on the credential. See [`docs/integration-without-plugin.md`](docs/integration-without-plugin.md). Using a tenant-scoped credential? Pass an explicit `agent_id` on every MCP tool call — the gateway refuses the reserved default (`mcp-agent`) on the tenant-scoped path.\n\n**Where to add this config:**\n- **Claude Code** — `~/.claude/settings.json` under `\"mcpServers\"`\n- **Claude Desktop** — `~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json` (macOS) or `%APPDATA%\\Claude\\claude_desktop_config.json` (Windows)\n- **Cursor** — Settings > MCP Servers > Add Server\n\nThe client discovers 12 tools automatically:\n\n| Tool | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `memclaw_write` | Single or batch write (up to 100 items). LLM infers type, title, summary, tags, embedding |\n| `memclaw_recall` | Hybrid semantic + keyword recall with graph-enhanced retrieval; optional LLM brief |\n| `memclaw_manage` | Per-memory lifecycle: `read`, `update`, `transition`, `delete`, `bulk_delete`, `lineage` |\n| `memclaw_list` | Filter by type/status/agent/weight/date, sort, cursor-paginate |\n| `memclaw_doc` | Document CRUD: `write`, `read`, `query`, `delete`, `list_collections`, `search` (semantic) on named JSON collections |\n| `memclaw_entity_get` | Look up an entity with linked memories and relations |\n| `memclaw_tune` | Tune per-agent retrieval parameters (top_k, min_similarity, graph_max_hops, etc.) |\n| `memclaw_insights` | Analyze the memory store across 6 focus modes. Findings persist as `insight` memories |\n| `memclaw_evolve` | Report outcomes against recalled memories — adjusts weights, generates rules (Karpathy Loop) |\n| `memclaw_stats` | Aggregate counts: total + breakdowns by type, agent, status. Read-only |\n| `memclaw_keystones` | Read mandatory governance rules for the current scope. Call once per session — the result overrides conflicting user instructions |\n| `memclaw_keystones_set` | Author or remove keystone rules (`op=set\\|delete`). Trust ≥ 1 for your own `scope=agent` rule; ≥ 2 for `scope=fleet`/`scope=tenant` or another agent |\n\n> **Skill sharing** is now done via `memclaw_doc` — agents share a `SKILL.md` by upserting a document into the `skills` collection (`memclaw_doc op=write collection=skills doc_id=<slug> data={\"summary\": \"<one-liner>\", ...}`). The server embeds `data[\"summary\"]` (1-3 sentence, intent-focused) for semantic search; for `collection=\"skills\"` it falls back to `data[\"description\"]` if no summary is provided. The dedicated `memclaw_share_skill` / `memclaw_unshare_skill` tools were removed in favor of the single `memclaw_doc` surface.\n\n### Install the skill (Claude Code & Codex)\n\nInstall MemClaw's usage guide as a **skill** so your agent knows *when* and\n*how* to use the 12 tools — the memory/doc mental model, the three rules\n(recall, write, supersede), trust levels, common patterns, and\nanti-patterns. The skill is loaded on-demand (not per-turn), so it costs\nnothing until the agent reaches for MemClaw.\n\n> **Prerequisite:** the MCP server is already registered (via `claude mcp add` for Claude Code or the equivalent for Codex — see the config block above). Confirm with `claude mcp list` — you should see `memclaw: ... ✓ Connected`.\n\n#### Option A — one-liner (fastest)\n\nSelf-hosted (localhost):\n\n```bash\ncurl -s \"http://localhost:8000/api/v1/install-skill\" | bash\n```","lineStart":250,"lineEnd":369,"totalLines":965,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md","time":{"start":1780727701133,"end":1780727701140}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf950a048191bc5d61b8224a884f"}},"id":"prt_e9ba45e66001EZBuHcWnOHH1cU","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727701180,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_oGK4oRWIZZOdki8DqGpBuXk3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","offset":1,"limit":360},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Evolve service -- outcome-driven weight adjustment and rule generation.\n2: \n3: The 'adapt' step of the Karpathy Loop. Agents report real-world outcomes,\n4: the system adjusts memory weights to reinforce or dampen information, and\n5: optionally generates preventive rules via LLM on failure/partial outcomes.\n6: \"\"\"\n7: \n8: import asyncio\n9: import logging\n10: import time\n11: from uuid import UUID\n12: \n13: from sqlalchemy import bindparam, select, text\n14: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n15: \n16: from core_api.constants import (\n17:     EVOLVE_FAILURE_DELTA,\n18:     EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS,\n19:     EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES,\n20:     EVOLVE_PARTIAL_DELTA,\n21:     EVOLVE_RULE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD,\n22:     EVOLVE_RULE_TEMPERATURE,\n23:     EVOLVE_SUCCESS_DELTA,\n24:     EVOLVE_WEIGHT_CAP,\n25:     EVOLVE_WEIGHT_FLOOR,\n26:     VALID_SCOPES,\n27: )\n28: from core_api.utils.sanitize import sanitize_content as _sanitize_content\n29: \n30: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n31: \n32: \n33: # A10 — slugs identifying every silent-exit path on the rule synthesis\n34: # flow. Callers (the harness, the dashboard, an operator inspecting\n35: # ``report_outcome`` results) read these from the response's\n36: # ``rule_skipped_reason`` field instead of grep'ing log strings, so\n37: # downstream tooling can pattern-match without parsing prose.\n38: RULE_SKIP_REASONS: tuple[str, ...] = (\n39:     \"not_failure_or_partial\",  # success outcomes don't generate rules\n40:     \"no_related_ids\",  # failure/partial but no memories supplied\n41:     \"no_memories_fetched\",  # every storage fetch failed\n42:     \"llm_failed\",  # provider raised or returned non-dict\n43:     \"below_confidence_threshold\",  # rule generated but conf < threshold\n44:     \"persist_failed\",  # _persist_rule returned None\n45: )\n46: \n47: \n48: def _log_rule_skip(reason: str, tenant_id: str, outcome_type: str, **extra) -> None:\n49:     \"\"\"Always-fire log line for an evolve rule-synthesis skip.\n50: \n51:     Mirrors the ``path_a_completed`` / ``path_c_completed`` pattern in\n52:     ``contradiction_detector.py`` (Gap 06): the reason slug lives in\n53:     the message string itself so a plain\n54:     ``grep evolve_rule_skipped <reason>`` works regardless of the\n55:     structlog renderer's ``extra={}`` handling.\"\"\"\n56:     extras = \" \".join(f\"{k}={v}\" for k, v in extra.items() if v is not None)\n57:     logger.info(\n58:         \"evolve_rule_skipped reason=%s tenant_id=%s outcome_type=%s %s\",\n59:         reason,\n60:         tenant_id,\n61:         outcome_type,\n62:         extras,\n63:     )\n64: \n65: \n66: # A15 — slugs identifying every silent-exit path on the weight-adjustment\n67: # flow. Mirrors RULE_SKIP_REASONS for the parallel observability story\n68: # on ``weight_adjustment_skipped_reason`` in the report_outcome response.\n69: # An evolve call that returns 200 OK with ``weight_adjustments=[]`` now\n70: # also carries the reason — callers can distinguish \"no rows moved\n71: # because nothing was supplied\" from \"no rows moved because every ID was\n72: # out of scope\" without parsing out_of_scope_count.\n73: WEIGHT_ADJUSTMENT_SKIP_REASONS: tuple[str, ...] = (\n74:     \"no_related_ids\",  # caller supplied no related_ids\n75:     \"agent_id_mismatch\",  # scope=agent, every related_id dropped by scope filter\n76:     \"fleet_id_mismatch\",  # scope=fleet, every related_id dropped by scope filter\n77:     \"all_out_of_scope\",  # scope=all, every related_id invalid UUID or missing row\n78:     \"no_rows_updated\",  # bulk UPDATE matched 0 rows (race: row deleted between filter and update)\n79: )\n80: \n81: \n82: def _log_weight_adjustment_skip(reason: str, tenant_id: str, scope: str, **extra) -> None:\n83:     \"\"\"Always-fire log line for an evolve weight-adjustment skip.\n84: \n85:     Same grep-friendly shape as ``_log_rule_skip``: the slug lives in\n86:     the message itself so ``grep evolve_weight_adjustment_skipped <reason>``\n87:     works regardless of structlog ``extra={}`` handling.\"\"\"\n88:     extras = \" \".join(f\"{k}={v}\" for k, v in extra.items() if v is not None)\n89:     logger.info(\n90:         \"evolve_weight_adjustment_skipped reason=%s tenant_id=%s scope=%s %s\",\n91:         reason,\n92:         tenant_id,\n93:         scope,\n94:         extras,\n95:     )\n96: \n97: \n98: # -- Delta map ----------------------------------------------------------------\n99: \n100: _DELTA_MAP = {\n101:     \"success\": EVOLVE_SUCCESS_DELTA,\n102:     \"failure\": EVOLVE_FAILURE_DELTA,\n103:     \"partial\": EVOLVE_PARTIAL_DELTA,\n104: }\n105: \n106: # -- Scope → outcome/rule memory visibility -----------------------------------\n107: # Mirrors insights_service._SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY so a scope='fleet' evolve\n108: # writes an outcome memory with scope_team visibility (fleet-wide reach) and\n109: # scope='agent' stays private to the reporting agent.\n110: \n111: _SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY = {\n112:     \"agent\": \"scope_agent\",\n113:     \"fleet\": \"scope_team\",\n114:     \"all\": \"scope_org\",\n115: }\n116: \n117: \n118: # -- Rule generation prompt ---------------------------------------------------\n119: \n120: _RULE_GENERATION_PROMPT = \"\"\"\\\n121: You are analyzing a {outcome_type} outcome to generate a preventive rule.\n122: \n123: OUTCOME: {outcome}\n124: \n125: RELATED MEMORIES ({count} memories the agent used before this outcome):\n126: {memories}\n127: \n128: Based on this {outcome_type}, generate a rule that would help avoid this outcome \\\n129: in the future. The rule should be:\n130: - Specific enough to trigger in similar situations\n131: - General enough to apply beyond this exact case\n132: - Actionable — the agent should know what to DO differently\n133: \n134: Respond with JSON:\n135: {{\n136:   \"condition\": \"IF/WHEN this situation arises (describe the trigger condition)\",\n137:   \"action\": \"THEN do this instead (describe the corrective action)\",\n138:   \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0 (how confident are you this rule is correct and useful),\n139:   \"reasoning\": \"brief explanation of why this rule would help\"\n140: }}\n141: \"\"\"\n142: \n143: \n144: # -- Weight adjustment --------------------------------------------------------\n145: \n146: \n147: _ADJUST_WEIGHTS_BULK_SQL = text(\n148:     \"\"\"\n149:     WITH old_vals AS (\n150:         SELECT id, weight AS old_weight\n151:           FROM memories\n152:          WHERE id IN :mids\n153:            AND tenant_id = :tid\n154:            AND deleted_at IS NULL\n155:     )\n156:     UPDATE memories\n157:        SET weight = GREATEST(:floor, LEAST(:cap, weight + :delta))\n158:       FROM old_vals\n159:      WHERE memories.id = old_vals.id\n160:        AND memories.tenant_id = :tid\n161:        AND memories.deleted_at IS NULL\n162:     RETURNING memories.id AS id, old_vals.old_weight AS old_weight,\n163:               memories.weight AS new_weight\n164:     \"\"\"\n165: ).bindparams(bindparam(\"mids\", expanding=True))\n166: \n167: \n168: # Backfill the rule memory's metadata.source_outcome_id after the outcome\n169: # exists. Rule persistence happens before outcome persistence (so the outcome\n170: # can record the rule_memory_id), so at rule-write time the outcome_id is\n171: # unknown. This UPDATE completes the rule→outcome traceability link.\n172: _BACKFILL_RULE_OUTCOME_SQL = text(\n173:     \"\"\"\n174:     UPDATE memories\n175:        SET metadata = jsonb_set(\n176:            COALESCE(metadata, '{}'::jsonb),\n177:            '{source_outcome_id}',\n178:            to_jsonb(CAST(:outcome_id AS text))\n179:        )\n180:      WHERE id = :rule_id AND tenant_id = :tid\n181:     \"\"\"\n182: )\n183: \n184: \n185: async def _filter_by_scope(\n186:     db: AsyncSession,\n187:     tenant_id: str,\n188:     caller_agent_id: str,\n189:     fleet_id: str | None,\n190:     scope: str,\n191:     related_ids: list[str],\n192: ) -> tuple[list[str], int]:\n193:     \"\"\"Drop IDs the caller cannot touch under ``scope``.\n194: \n195:     Scope rules (mirror insights_service._scope_filters):\n196:       - ``agent``: keep memories where ``memory.agent_id = caller_agent_id``.\n197:       - ``fleet``: keep memories where ``memory.fleet_id = fleet_id`` (fleet_id required).\n198:       - ``all``:   keep any memory in the tenant.\n199: \n200:     Invalid UUIDs, missing rows, soft-deleted rows, and rows that fail the\n201:     scope predicate are dropped silently — same behavior as the existing\n202:     missing-row handling in ``_adjust_weights``. Duplicates supplied by the\n203:     caller are collapsed to the first occurrence and the extra copies count\n204:     toward ``out_of_scope_count`` (duplicates can't be adjusted twice in a\n205:     single evolve call anyway).\n206: \n207:     Returns (in_scope_ids, out_of_scope_count). The returned list is\n208:     deduplicated and preserves first-seen order of the input so downstream\n209:     consumers get a stable, canonical view of the caller's intent.\n210:     \"\"\"\n211:     from common.models.memory import Memory\n212: \n213:     if not related_ids:\n214:         return [], 0\n215: \n216:     # Precondition guard: scope='fleet' without a fleet_id is unsatisfiable.\n217:     # The docstring promises fleet_id is required for that scope; report_outcome\n218:     # already rejects this upstream, but _filter_by_scope is a public-ish\n219:     # helper that tests and future callers may invoke directly — fail loud\n220:     # rather than silently matching nothing in a bound-param NULL.\n221:     if scope == \"fleet\" and fleet_id is None:\n222:         raise ValueError(\"_filter_by_scope: fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n223: \n224:     # Convert to UUIDs, silently dropping non-parseable strings and\n225:     # duplicates (dict assignment overwrites prior occurrences). First-seen\n226:     # string is retained as the dict key so the returned list keeps the\n227:     # caller's ordering.\n228:     valid_uuids: dict[str, UUID] = {}\n229:     for s in related_ids:\n230:         try:\n231:             valid_uuids[s] = UUID(s)\n232:         except (ValueError, TypeError):\n233:             continue\n234: \n235:     if not valid_uuids:\n236:         # All caller inputs failed UUID parsing — every slot counts against\n237:         # out_of_scope. Matches the formula below: n_invalid_or_dup equals\n238:         # ``len(related_ids) - len(valid_uuids) = len(related_ids) - 0``.\n239:         return [], len(related_ids)\n240: \n241:     # Build the scope filter via SQLAlchemy's expression API rather than\n242:     # interpolating a SQL fragment. All user-derived values remain bound\n243:     # parameters and the query plan is visible to tooling (EXPLAIN, SQLA\n244:     # event hooks). Comparing UUID objects — not stringified forms — also\n245:     # eliminates the canonical-form mismatch that ``id::text`` would have\n246:     # produced for callers passing uppercase or unhyphenated UUIDs.\n247:     stmt = (\n248:         select(Memory.id)\n249:         .where(Memory.id.in_(list(valid_uuids.values())))\n250:         .where(Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id)\n251:         .where(Memory.deleted_at.is_(None))\n252:     )\n253:     if scope == \"agent\":\n254:         stmt = stmt.where(Memory.agent_id == caller_agent_id)\n255:     elif scope == \"fleet\":\n256:         stmt = stmt.where(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n257: \n258:     result = await db.execute(stmt)\n259:     allowed: set[UUID] = {row[0] for row in result}\n260: \n261:     in_scope = [s for s, uid in valid_uuids.items() if uid in allowed]\n262:     # out_of_scope_count has two components we keep separate so the name\n263:     # actually tells the truth under duplicate or invalid input:\n264:     #   - n_invalid_or_dup: entries the caller sent that never made it into\n265:     #     valid_uuids (unparseable strings, or duplicates of an earlier ID\n266:     #     that `valid_uuids[s] = UUID(s)` collapsed).\n267:     #   - n_out_of_scope_unique: unique, parseable IDs that failed the DB\n268:     #     scope predicate (wrong owner/fleet, missing row, or soft-deleted).\n269:     # The total is algebraically identical to ``len(related_ids) - len(in_scope)``\n270:     # but the breakdown makes the warning log below interpretable.\n271:     n_invalid_or_dup = len(related_ids) - len(valid_uuids)\n272:     n_out_of_scope_unique = len(valid_uuids) - len(in_scope)\n273:     out_of_scope = n_invalid_or_dup + n_out_of_scope_unique\n274: \n275:     if out_of_scope > 0:\n276:         logger.warning(\n277:             \"evolve: dropped %d related_ids that failed scope=%s checks (tenant=%s, caller=%s, fleet=%s)\",\n278:             out_of_scope,\n279:             scope,\n280:             tenant_id,\n281:             caller_agent_id,\n282:             fleet_id,\n283:         )\n284: \n285:     return in_scope, out_of_scope\n286: \n287: \n288: async def _adjust_weights(\n289:     db: AsyncSession,\n290:     tenant_id: str,\n291:     related_ids: list[str],\n292:     outcome_type: str,\n293:     agent_id: str,\n294: ) -> tuple[str | None, list[str], list[dict]]:\n295:     \"\"\"Adjust weights on related memories atomically.\n296: \n297:     Executes a CTE-based UPDATE per memory so each row is read, clamped, and\n298:     written in a single statement — eliminating the TOCTOU race that existed\n299:     when the read (via storage-client HTTP) and the write crossed transaction\n300:     boundaries. The CTE captures the pre-update weight so `old_weight` in the\n301:     response is exact even when clamping occurs at the floor or cap.\n302: \n303:     Concurrency: `related_ids` is deduped and sorted before iteration so all\n304:     concurrent callers acquire row locks in the same order, preventing the\n305:     cycle that would otherwise trigger PostgreSQL deadlocks when two evolve\n306:     calls touch overlapping memory sets.\n307: \n308:     Audit: update_memory's audit hook is bypassed; the outcome memory's\n309:     metadata (`weight_adjustments`) records the change as a compensating trail.\n310: \n311:     Returns a tuple of (skip_reason, processed_ids, adjustments):\n312:     - skip_reason: A15 — ``None`` when at least one row was updated;\n313:       ``\"no_rows_updated\"`` when every supplied id failed UUID parsing,\n314:       the bulk UPDATE returned no rows (row deleted between filter and\n315:       update), or the bulk UPDATE raised an exception. Callers feed this\n316:       into ``report_outcome``'s ``weight_adjustment_skipped_reason``\n317:       response field so a 200 OK with empty adjustments is no longer\n318:       indistinguishable from success.\n319:     - processed_ids: IDs whose weights were actually updated in the DB.\n320:       Excludes invalid UUIDs, missing rows, and rows whose UPDATE raised.\n321:       Callers persist this in the outcome metadata so it reflects reality\n322:       rather than the caller's optimistic input.\n323:     - adjustments: [{memory_id, old_weight, new_weight, delta}].\n324:     \"\"\"\n325:     # Dedup + sort first so the cap counts unique IDs (truncating before\n326:     # dedup can leave fewer than EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS distinct items when\n327:     # the caller passes duplicates). Sorted order also ensures every\n328:     # concurrent evolve call locks rows in the same global order,\n329:     # avoiding cycle-based deadlocks.\n330:     deduped = sorted(set(related_ids))\n331:     if len(deduped) > EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS:\n332:         logger.warning(\n333:             \"evolve: related_ids truncated from %d unique to %d\",\n334:             len(deduped),\n335:             EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS,\n336:         )\n337:         deduped = deduped[:EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS]\n338:     related_ids = deduped\n339: \n340:     delta = _DELTA_MAP[outcome_type]\n341:     adjustments: list[dict] = []\n342:     successfully_adjusted: list[str] = []\n343: \n344:     # Parse all UUIDs up front. Invalid strings are logged + dropped\n345:     # before the SQL roundtrip rather than failing the whole batch.\n346:     parsed: list[tuple[str, UUID]] = []\n347:     for mid_str in related_ids:\n348:         try:\n349:             parsed.append((mid_str, UUID(mid_str)))\n350:         except ValueError:\n351:             logger.warning(\"evolve: skipping invalid UUID: %s\", mid_str)\n352: \n353:     if not parsed:\n354:         return \"no_rows_updated\", [], []\n355: \n356:     valid_uuids = [u for _, u in parsed]\n357: \n358:     # Single bulk UPDATE keyed by the validated UUID set; collapses the\n359:     # prior N+1 round-trips and N savepoint pairs into one statement\n360:     # (audit finding #25). Single savepoint isolates the entire weight-\n\n(Showing lines 1-360 of 1007. Use offset=361 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Evolve service -- outcome-driven weight adjustment and rule generation.\n\nThe 'adapt' step of the Karpathy Loop. Agents report real-world outcomes,\nthe system adjusts memory weights to reinforce or dampen information, and\noptionally generates preventive rules via LLM on failure/partial outcomes.\n\"\"\"\n\nimport asyncio\nimport logging\nimport time\nfrom uuid import UUID\n\nfrom sqlalchemy import bindparam, select, text\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.constants import (\n    EVOLVE_FAILURE_DELTA,\n    EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS,\n    EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES,\n    EVOLVE_PARTIAL_DELTA,","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Evolve service -- outcome-driven weight adjustment and rule generation.\n\nThe 'adapt' step of the Karpathy Loop. Agents report real-world outcomes,\nthe system adjusts memory weights to reinforce or dampen information, and\noptionally generates preventive rules via LLM on failure/partial outcomes.\n\"\"\"\n\nimport asyncio\nimport logging\nimport time\nfrom uuid import UUID\n\nfrom sqlalchemy import bindparam, select, text\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.constants import (\n    EVOLVE_FAILURE_DELTA,\n    EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS,\n    EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES,\n    EVOLVE_PARTIAL_DELTA,\n    EVOLVE_RULE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD,\n    EVOLVE_RULE_TEMPERATURE,\n    EVOLVE_SUCCESS_DELTA,\n    EVOLVE_WEIGHT_CAP,\n    EVOLVE_WEIGHT_FLOOR,\n    VALID_SCOPES,\n)\nfrom core_api.utils.sanitize import sanitize_content as _sanitize_content\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\n# A10 — slugs identifying every silent-exit path on the rule synthesis\n# flow. Callers (the harness, the dashboard, an operator inspecting\n# ``report_outcome`` results) read these from the response's\n# ``rule_skipped_reason`` field instead of grep'ing log strings, so\n# downstream tooling can pattern-match without parsing prose.\nRULE_SKIP_REASONS: tuple[str, ...] = (\n    \"not_failure_or_partial\",  # success outcomes don't generate rules\n    \"no_related_ids\",  # failure/partial but no memories supplied\n    \"no_memories_fetched\",  # every storage fetch failed\n    \"llm_failed\",  # provider raised or returned non-dict\n    \"below_confidence_threshold\",  # rule generated but conf < threshold\n    \"persist_failed\",  # _persist_rule returned None\n)\n\n\ndef _log_rule_skip(reason: str, tenant_id: str, outcome_type: str, **extra) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Always-fire log line for an evolve rule-synthesis skip.\n\n    Mirrors the ``path_a_completed`` / ``path_c_completed`` pattern in\n    ``contradiction_detector.py`` (Gap 06): the reason slug lives in\n    the message string itself so a plain\n    ``grep evolve_rule_skipped <reason>`` works regardless of the\n    structlog renderer's ``extra={}`` handling.\"\"\"\n    extras = \" \".join(f\"{k}={v}\" for k, v in extra.items() if v is not None)\n    logger.info(\n        \"evolve_rule_skipped reason=%s tenant_id=%s outcome_type=%s %s\",\n        reason,\n        tenant_id,\n        outcome_type,\n        extras,\n    )\n\n\n# A15 — slugs identifying every silent-exit path on the weight-adjustment\n# flow. Mirrors RULE_SKIP_REASONS for the parallel observability story\n# on ``weight_adjustment_skipped_reason`` in the report_outcome response.\n# An evolve call that returns 200 OK with ``weight_adjustments=[]`` now\n# also carries the reason — callers can distinguish \"no rows moved\n# because nothing was supplied\" from \"no rows moved because every ID was\n# out of scope\" without parsing out_of_scope_count.\nWEIGHT_ADJUSTMENT_SKIP_REASONS: tuple[str, ...] = (\n    \"no_related_ids\",  # caller supplied no related_ids\n    \"agent_id_mismatch\",  # scope=agent, every related_id dropped by scope filter\n    \"fleet_id_mismatch\",  # scope=fleet, every related_id dropped by scope filter\n    \"all_out_of_scope\",  # scope=all, every related_id invalid UUID or missing row\n    \"no_rows_updated\",  # bulk UPDATE matched 0 rows (race: row deleted between filter and update)\n)\n\n\ndef _log_weight_adjustment_skip(reason: str, tenant_id: str, scope: str, **extra) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Always-fire log line for an evolve weight-adjustment skip.\n\n    Same grep-friendly shape as ``_log_rule_skip``: the slug lives in\n    the message itself so ``grep evolve_weight_adjustment_skipped <reason>``\n    works regardless of structlog ``extra={}`` handling.\"\"\"\n    extras = \" \".join(f\"{k}={v}\" for k, v in extra.items() if v is not None)\n    logger.info(\n        \"evolve_weight_adjustment_skipped reason=%s tenant_id=%s scope=%s %s\",\n        reason,\n        tenant_id,\n        scope,\n        extras,\n    )\n\n\n# -- Delta map ----------------------------------------------------------------\n\n_DELTA_MAP = {\n    \"success\": EVOLVE_SUCCESS_DELTA,\n    \"failure\": EVOLVE_FAILURE_DELTA,\n    \"partial\": EVOLVE_PARTIAL_DELTA,\n}\n\n# -- Scope → outcome/rule memory visibility -----------------------------------\n# Mirrors insights_service._SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY so a scope='fleet' evolve\n# writes an outcome memory with scope_team visibility (fleet-wide reach) and\n# scope='agent' stays private to the reporting agent.\n\n_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY = {\n    \"agent\": \"scope_agent\",\n    \"fleet\": \"scope_team\",\n    \"all\": \"scope_org\",\n}\n\n\n# -- Rule generation prompt ---------------------------------------------------\n\n_RULE_GENERATION_PROMPT = \"\"\"\\\nYou are analyzing a {outcome_type} outcome to generate a preventive rule.\n\nOUTCOME: {outcome}\n\nRELATED MEMORIES ({count} memories the agent used before this outcome):\n{memories}\n\nBased on this {outcome_type}, generate a rule that would help avoid this outcome \\\nin the future. The rule should be:\n- Specific enough to trigger in similar situations\n- General enough to apply beyond this exact case\n- Actionable — the agent should know what to DO differently\n\nRespond with JSON:\n{{\n  \"condition\": \"IF/WHEN this situation arises (describe the trigger condition)\",\n  \"action\": \"THEN do this instead (describe the corrective action)\",\n  \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0 (how confident are you this rule is correct and useful),\n  \"reasoning\": \"brief explanation of why this rule would help\"\n}}\n\"\"\"\n\n\n# -- Weight adjustment --------------------------------------------------------\n\n\n_ADJUST_WEIGHTS_BULK_SQL = text(\n    \"\"\"\n    WITH old_vals AS (\n        SELECT id, weight AS old_weight\n          FROM memories\n         WHERE id IN :mids\n           AND tenant_id = :tid\n           AND deleted_at IS NULL\n    )\n    UPDATE memories\n       SET weight = GREATEST(:floor, LEAST(:cap, weight + :delta))\n      FROM old_vals\n     WHERE memories.id = old_vals.id\n       AND memories.tenant_id = :tid\n       AND memories.deleted_at IS NULL\n    RETURNING memories.id AS id, old_vals.old_weight AS old_weight,\n              memories.weight AS new_weight\n    \"\"\"\n).bindparams(bindparam(\"mids\", expanding=True))\n\n\n# Backfill the rule memory's metadata.source_outcome_id after the outcome\n# exists. Rule persistence happens before outcome persistence (so the outcome\n# can record the rule_memory_id), so at rule-write time the outcome_id is\n# unknown. This UPDATE completes the rule→outcome traceability link.\n_BACKFILL_RULE_OUTCOME_SQL = text(\n    \"\"\"\n    UPDATE memories\n       SET metadata = jsonb_set(\n           COALESCE(metadata, '{}'::jsonb),\n           '{source_outcome_id}',\n           to_jsonb(CAST(:outcome_id AS text))\n       )\n     WHERE id = :rule_id AND tenant_id = :tid\n    \"\"\"\n)\n\n\nasync def _filter_by_scope(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    caller_agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n    scope: str,\n    related_ids: list[str],\n) -> tuple[list[str], int]:\n    \"\"\"Drop IDs the caller cannot touch under ``scope``.\n\n    Scope rules (mirror insights_service._scope_filters):\n      - ``agent``: keep memories where ``memory.agent_id = caller_agent_id``.\n      - ``fleet``: keep memories where ``memory.fleet_id = fleet_id`` (fleet_id required).\n      - ``all``:   keep any memory in the tenant.\n\n    Invalid UUIDs, missing rows, soft-deleted rows, and rows that fail the\n    scope predicate are dropped silently — same behavior as the existing\n    missing-row handling in ``_adjust_weights``. Duplicates supplied by the\n    caller are collapsed to the first occurrence and the extra copies count\n    toward ``out_of_scope_count`` (duplicates can't be adjusted twice in a\n    single evolve call anyway).\n\n    Returns (in_scope_ids, out_of_scope_count). The returned list is\n    deduplicated and preserves first-seen order of the input so downstream\n    consumers get a stable, canonical view of the caller's intent.\n    \"\"\"\n    from common.models.memory import Memory\n\n    if not related_ids:\n        return [], 0\n\n    # Precondition guard: scope='fleet' without a fleet_id is unsatisfiable.\n    # The docstring promises fleet_id is required for that scope; report_outcome\n    # already rejects this upstream, but _filter_by_scope is a public-ish\n    # helper that tests and future callers may invoke directly — fail loud\n    # rather than silently matching nothing in a bound-param NULL.\n    if scope == \"fleet\" and fleet_id is None:\n        raise ValueError(\"_filter_by_scope: fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n\n    # Convert to UUIDs, silently dropping non-parseable strings and\n    # duplicates (dict assignment overwrites prior occurrences). First-seen\n    # string is retained as the dict key so the returned list keeps the\n    # caller's ordering.\n    valid_uuids: dict[str, UUID] = {}\n    for s in related_ids:\n        try:\n            valid_uuids[s] = UUID(s)\n        except (ValueError, TypeError):\n            continue\n\n    if not valid_uuids:\n        # All caller inputs failed UUID parsing — every slot counts against\n        # out_of_scope. Matches the formula below: n_invalid_or_dup equals\n        # ``len(related_ids) - len(valid_uuids) = len(related_ids) - 0``.\n        return [], len(related_ids)\n\n    # Build the scope filter via SQLAlchemy's expression API rather than\n    # interpolating a SQL fragment. All user-derived values remain bound\n    # parameters and the query plan is visible to tooling (EXPLAIN, SQLA\n    # event hooks). Comparing UUID objects — not stringified forms — also\n    # eliminates the canonical-form mismatch that ``id::text`` would have\n    # produced for callers passing uppercase or unhyphenated UUIDs.\n    stmt = (\n        select(Memory.id)\n        .where(Memory.id.in_(list(valid_uuids.values())))\n        .where(Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id)\n        .where(Memory.deleted_at.is_(None))\n    )\n    if scope == \"agent\":\n        stmt = stmt.where(Memory.agent_id == caller_agent_id)\n    elif scope == \"fleet\":\n        stmt = stmt.where(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n\n    result = await db.execute(stmt)\n    allowed: set[UUID] = {row[0] for row in result}\n\n    in_scope = [s for s, uid in valid_uuids.items() if uid in allowed]\n    # out_of_scope_count has two components we keep separate so the name\n    # actually tells the truth under duplicate or invalid input:\n    #   - n_invalid_or_dup: entries the caller sent that never made it into\n    #     valid_uuids (unparseable strings, or duplicates of an earlier ID\n    #     that `valid_uuids[s] = UUID(s)` collapsed).\n    #   - n_out_of_scope_unique: unique, parseable IDs that failed the DB\n    #     scope predicate (wrong owner/fleet, missing row, or soft-deleted).\n    # The total is algebraically identical to ``len(related_ids) - len(in_scope)``\n    # but the breakdown makes the warning log below interpretable.\n    n_invalid_or_dup = len(related_ids) - len(valid_uuids)\n    n_out_of_scope_unique = len(valid_uuids) - len(in_scope)\n    out_of_scope = n_invalid_or_dup + n_out_of_scope_unique\n\n    if out_of_scope > 0:\n        logger.warning(\n            \"evolve: dropped %d related_ids that failed scope=%s checks (tenant=%s, caller=%s, fleet=%s)\",\n            out_of_scope,\n            scope,\n            tenant_id,\n            caller_agent_id,\n            fleet_id,\n        )\n\n    return in_scope, out_of_scope\n\n\nasync def _adjust_weights(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    related_ids: list[str],\n    outcome_type: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n) -> tuple[str | None, list[str], list[dict]]:\n    \"\"\"Adjust weights on related memories atomically.\n\n    Executes a CTE-based UPDATE per memory so each row is read, clamped, and\n    written in a single statement — eliminating the TOCTOU race that existed\n    when the read (via storage-client HTTP) and the write crossed transaction\n    boundaries. The CTE captures the pre-update weight so `old_weight` in the\n    response is exact even when clamping occurs at the floor or cap.\n\n    Concurrency: `related_ids` is deduped and sorted before iteration so all\n    concurrent callers acquire row locks in the same order, preventing the\n    cycle that would otherwise trigger PostgreSQL deadlocks when two evolve\n    calls touch overlapping memory sets.\n\n    Audit: update_memory's audit hook is bypassed; the outcome memory's\n    metadata (`weight_adjustments`) records the change as a compensating trail.\n\n    Returns a tuple of (skip_reason, processed_ids, adjustments):\n    - skip_reason: A15 — ``None`` when at least one row was updated;\n      ``\"no_rows_updated\"`` when every supplied id failed UUID parsing,\n      the bulk UPDATE returned no rows (row deleted between filter and\n      update), or the bulk UPDATE raised an exception. Callers feed this\n      into ``report_outcome``'s ``weight_adjustment_skipped_reason``\n      response field so a 200 OK with empty adjustments is no longer\n      indistinguishable from success.\n    - processed_ids: IDs whose weights were actually updated in the DB.\n      Excludes invalid UUIDs, missing rows, and rows whose UPDATE raised.\n      Callers persist this in the outcome metadata so it reflects reality\n      rather than the caller's optimistic input.\n    - adjustments: [{memory_id, old_weight, new_weight, delta}].\n    \"\"\"\n    # Dedup + sort first so the cap counts unique IDs (truncating before\n    # dedup can leave fewer than EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS distinct items when\n    # the caller passes duplicates). Sorted order also ensures every\n    # concurrent evolve call locks rows in the same global order,\n    # avoiding cycle-based deadlocks.\n    deduped = sorted(set(related_ids))\n    if len(deduped) > EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS:\n        logger.warning(\n            \"evolve: related_ids truncated from %d unique to %d\",\n            len(deduped),\n            EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS,\n        )\n        deduped = deduped[:EVOLVE_MAX_RELATED_IDS]\n    related_ids = deduped\n\n    delta = _DELTA_MAP[outcome_type]\n    adjustments: list[dict] = []\n    successfully_adjusted: list[str] = []\n\n    # Parse all UUIDs up front. Invalid strings are logged + dropped\n    # before the SQL roundtrip rather than failing the whole batch.\n    parsed: list[tuple[str, UUID]] = []\n    for mid_str in related_ids:\n        try:\n            parsed.append((mid_str, UUID(mid_str)))\n        except ValueError:\n            logger.warning(\"evolve: skipping invalid UUID: %s\", mid_str)\n\n    if not parsed:\n        return \"no_rows_updated\", [], []\n\n    valid_uuids = [u for _, u in parsed]\n\n    # Single bulk UPDATE keyed by the validated UUID set; collapses the\n    # prior N+1 round-trips and N savepoint pairs into one statement\n    # (audit finding #25). Single savepoint isolates the entire weight-","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":360,"totalLines":1007,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","time":{"start":1780727701169,"end":1780727701179}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf950a0c81919d43478ecb50e0ea"}},"id":"prt_e9ba45e9700128HG5OcQxpMc8z","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727701185,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_EYARGwCqKXr0G3aXHwQE6SdK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","offset":1,"limit":420},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Insights service -- LLM-powered memory analysis with 6 focus modes.\n2: \n3: Examines the memory store to surface contradictions, failure patterns,\n4: stale knowledge, cross-agent divergence, emerging themes, and unexpected\n5: vector-space clusters. Findings are persisted as insight-type memories.\n6: \"\"\"\n7: \n8: import logging\n9: import time\n10: from dataclasses import dataclass\n11: from datetime import UTC, datetime, timedelta\n12: \n13: from fastapi import HTTPException\n14: from sqlalchemy import distinct, func, or_, select\n15: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n16: \n17: from common.models.memory import Memory\n18: from core_api.constants import (\n19:     INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_CLUSTERS,\n20:     INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_SAMPLE_SIZE,\n21:     INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES,\n22:     INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES,\n23:     INSIGHTS_TEMPERATURE,\n24: )\n25: from core_api.utils.sanitize import sanitize_content as _sanitize_content\n26: \n27: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n28: \n29: \n30: @dataclass\n31: class _DiscoverResult:\n32:     \"\"\"Heterogeneous return type for _query_discover — either clusters or flat memories.\"\"\"\n33: \n34:     is_clustered: bool\n35:     data: list[dict]\n36: \n37: \n38: _SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY = {\n39:     \"agent\": \"scope_agent\",\n40:     \"fleet\": \"scope_team\",\n41:     \"all\": \"scope_org\",\n42: }\n43: \n44: \n45: # -- Prompts -------------------------------------------------------------------\n46: \n47: _PROMPT_CONTRADICTIONS = \"\"\"\\\n48: You are a memory analyst specializing in contradiction detection.\n49: \n50: Analyze these {count} memories for contradiction clusters. Identify what is \\\n51: contradicted, which memories conflict, which version is likely correct \\\n52: (consider recency, weight, and agent trust), and what should be done to \\\n53: resolve the conflict.\n54: \n55: Look for:\n56: - Direct factual contradictions (same entity, different values)\n57: - Superseded memories that may still be recalled\n58: - Status conflicts (e.g. \"active\" vs \"conflicted\")\n59: - Temporal contradictions (events placed at incompatible times)\n60: \n61: Memories:\n62: {memories}\n63: \n64: Respond with JSON:\n65: {{\n66:   \"findings\": [\n67:     {{\n68:       \"type\": \"contradictions\",\n69:       \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n70:       \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n71:       \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n72:       \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n73:       \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n74:     }}\n75:   ],\n76:   \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n77: }}\"\"\"\n78: \n79: _PROMPT_FAILURES = \"\"\"\\\n80: You are a memory analyst specializing in failure pattern detection.\n81: \n82: These {count} memories have low importance but were recalled by agents -- \\\n83: meaning agents may have acted on weak or unreliable information. Identify \\\n84: recurring failure patterns, common root causes, and memories that should be \\\n85: deprecated or flagged.\n86: \n87: Look for:\n88: - Memories with very low weight that were recalled frequently\n89: - Patterns in the types of unreliable information\n90: - Agents that consistently rely on weak memories\n91: - Information that should have been superseded but wasn't\n92: \n93: Memories:\n94: {memories}\n95: \n96: Respond with JSON:\n97: {{\n98:   \"findings\": [\n99:     {{\n100:       \"type\": \"failures\",\n101:       \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n102:       \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n103:       \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n104:       \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n105:       \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n106:     }}\n107:   ],\n108:   \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n109: }}\"\"\"\n110: \n111: _PROMPT_STALE = \"\"\"\\\n112: You are a memory analyst specializing in knowledge freshness.\n113: \n114: These {count} memories are likely outdated -- they haven't been recalled \\\n115: recently or have very low weight. Identify which are genuinely stale vs. \\\n116: rarely needed, and flag ones that could cause harm if recalled.\n117: \n118: Look for:\n119: - Memories about time-sensitive topics (deadlines, prices, versions)\n120: - Knowledge that likely changed since creation\n121: - Memories that were never recalled (possibly irrelevant from the start)\n122: - Low-weight memories that could mislead if surfaced\n123: \n124: Memories:\n125: {memories}\n126: \n127: Respond with JSON:\n128: {{\n129:   \"findings\": [\n130:     {{\n131:       \"type\": \"stale\",\n132:       \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n133:       \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n134:       \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n135:       \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n136:       \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n137:     }}\n138:   ],\n139:   \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n140: }}\"\"\"\n141: \n142: _PROMPT_DIVERGENCE = \"\"\"\\\n143: You are a memory analyst specializing in cross-agent knowledge consistency.\n144: \n145: These {count} memories come from different agents about the same entities. \\\n146: Identify where agents disagree, which agent's perspective is more credible, \\\n147: and whether the divergence indicates a real disagreement or different contexts.\n148: \n149: Look for:\n150: - Same entity described differently by different agents\n151: - Conflicting conclusions or assessments\n152: - Different levels of detail or confidence\n153: - Cases where divergence reveals complementary rather than conflicting views\n154: \n155: Memories:\n156: {memories}\n157: \n158: Respond with JSON:\n159: {{\n160:   \"findings\": [\n161:     {{\n162:       \"type\": \"divergence\",\n163:       \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n164:       \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n165:       \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n166:       \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n167:       \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n168:     }}\n169:   ],\n170:   \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n171: }}\"\"\"\n172: \n173: _PROMPT_PATTERNS = \"\"\"\\\n174: You are a memory analyst specializing in trend and pattern recognition.\n175: \n176: Analyze these {count} recent memories for emerging themes, trends, and \\\n177: patterns. What topics are getting more attention? What decisions are being \\\n178: made? Are there any concerning patterns?\n179: \n180: Look for:\n181: - Recurring topics or entities across multiple memories\n182: - Shifts in focus or priority over time\n183: - Decision patterns and their outcomes\n184: - Gaps in knowledge coverage\n185: \n186: Memories:\n187: {memories}\n188: \n189: Respond with JSON:\n190: {{\n191:   \"findings\": [\n192:     {{\n193:       \"type\": \"patterns\",\n194:       \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n195:       \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n196:       \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n197:       \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n198:       \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n199:     }}\n200:   ],\n201:   \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n202: }}\"\"\"\n203: \n204: _PROMPT_DISCOVER = \"\"\"\\\n205: You are a memory analyst specializing in knowledge topology.\n206: \n207: These are {count} memories organized into natural clusters discovered in the \\\n208: embedding vector space. For each cluster, what is the underlying theme? Are \\\n209: any clusters surprising? Are there gaps in knowledge between clusters?\n210: \n211: Look for:\n212: - Unexpected groupings that reveal hidden connections\n213: - Clusters with high weight variance (inconsistent confidence)\n214: - Cross-agent clusters (same topic, multiple agents)\n215: - Missing clusters (topics you'd expect but don't see)\n216: \n217: Clusters:\n218: {memories}\n219: \n220: Respond with JSON:\n221: {{\n222:   \"findings\": [\n223:     {{\n224:       \"type\": \"discover\",\n225:       \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n226:       \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n227:       \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n228:       \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n229:       \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n230:     }}\n231:   ],\n232:   \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n233: }}\"\"\"\n234: \n235: \n236: # -- Scope helpers -------------------------------------------------------------\n237: \n238: \n239: def _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope):\n240:     \"\"\"Return a list of SQLAlchemy WHERE clauses for the given scope.\"\"\"\n241:     base = [Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id, Memory.deleted_at.is_(None)]\n242: \n243:     if scope == \"agent\":\n244:         base.append(Memory.agent_id == agent_id)\n245:         if fleet_id:\n246:             base.append(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n247:     elif scope == \"fleet\":\n248:         if not fleet_id:\n249:             raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'\")\n250:         base.append(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n251:     # scope == \"all\": tenant-wide, no additional filters\n252: \n253:     return base\n254: \n255: \n256: def _rows_to_dicts(rows) -> list[dict]:\n257:     \"\"\"Convert SQLAlchemy Memory rows to plain dicts for prompt formatting.\"\"\"\n258:     return [\n259:         {\n260:             \"id\": str(r.id),\n261:             \"memory_type\": r.memory_type,\n262:             \"title\": r.title or \"\",\n263:             \"content\": r.content,\n264:             \"weight\": r.weight,\n265:             \"agent_id\": r.agent_id,\n266:             \"fleet_id\": r.fleet_id,\n267:             \"created_at\": r.created_at.isoformat() if r.created_at else \"\",\n268:             \"status\": r.status,\n269:             \"recall_count\": r.recall_count or 0,\n270:             \"last_recalled_at\": r.last_recalled_at.isoformat() if r.last_recalled_at else None,\n271:             \"supersedes_id\": str(r.supersedes_id) if r.supersedes_id else None,\n272:             \"subject_entity_id\": str(r.subject_entity_id) if r.subject_entity_id else None,\n273:             \"object_value\": r.object_value,\n274:             \"ts_valid_start\": r.ts_valid_start.isoformat() if r.ts_valid_start else None,\n275:         }\n276:         for r in rows\n277:     ]\n278: \n279: \n280: # -- Query functions (one per focus) -------------------------------------------\n281: \n282: \n283: async def _query_contradictions(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n284:     \"\"\"Fetch memories that supersede others, are conflicted, or share entities with divergent values.\"\"\"\n285:     base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n286: \n287:     # Memories that supersede others or are superseded\n288:     # (exclude insight-type memories to prevent feedback loops where insights\n289:     # analyze previously generated insights)\n290:     stmt = (\n291:         select(Memory)\n292:         .where(\n293:             *base,\n294:             Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n295:             Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n296:         )\n297:         .where((Memory.supersedes_id.isnot(None)) | (Memory.status == \"conflicted\"))\n298:         .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n299:         .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n300:     )\n301:     result = await db.execute(stmt)\n302:     rows = list(result.scalars().all())\n303:     seen_ids = {r.id for r in rows}\n304: \n305:     # Also fetch the superseded memories themselves — the query above returns\n306:     # the supersedor (the row with supersedes_id IS NOT NULL) but the LLM\n307:     # needs both sides of the contradiction to reason about which version\n308:     # is correct. Skip rows we already have.\n309:     superseded_ids = [\n310:         r.supersedes_id for r in rows if r.supersedes_id is not None and r.supersedes_id not in seen_ids\n311:     ]\n312:     if superseded_ids and len(rows) < INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES:\n313:         sup_stmt = (\n314:             select(Memory)\n315:             .where(\n316:                 *base,\n317:                 Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n318:                 Memory.id.in_(superseded_ids),\n319:             )\n320:             .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES - len(rows))\n321:         )\n322:         sup_result = await db.execute(sup_stmt)\n323:         for r in sup_result.scalars().all():\n324:             if r.id not in seen_ids:\n325:                 rows.append(r)\n326:                 seen_ids.add(r.id)\n327: \n328:     # Also find memories sharing subject_entity_id with different object_value\n329:     if len(rows) < INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES:\n330:         remaining = INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES - len(rows)\n331: \n332:         entity_stmt = (\n333:             select(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n334:             .where(\n335:                 *base,\n336:                 Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n337:                 Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n338:                 Memory.subject_entity_id.isnot(None),\n339:                 Memory.object_value.isnot(None),\n340:             )\n341:             .group_by(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n342:             .having(func.count(distinct(Memory.object_value)) > 1)\n343:             .limit(10)\n344:         )\n345:         entity_result = await db.execute(entity_stmt)\n346:         entity_ids = [r[0] for r in entity_result.all()]\n347: \n348:         if entity_ids:\n349:             extra_stmt = (\n350:                 select(Memory)\n351:                 .where(\n352:                     *base,\n353:                     Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n354:                     Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n355:                     Memory.subject_entity_id.in_(entity_ids),\n356:                 )\n357:                 .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n358:                 .limit(remaining)\n359:             )\n360:             extra_result = await db.execute(extra_stmt)\n361:             for r in extra_result.scalars().all():\n362:                 if r.id not in seen_ids:\n363:                     rows.append(r)\n364:                     seen_ids.add(r.id)\n365: \n366:     return _rows_to_dicts(rows[:INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES])\n367: \n368: \n369: async def _query_failures(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n370:     \"\"\"Fetch low-weight memories that were recalled (agents acted on weak info).\"\"\"\n371:     base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n372:     stmt = (\n373:         select(Memory)\n374:         .where(\n375:             *base,\n376:             Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n377:             Memory.weight < 0.3,\n378:             Memory.recall_count > 0,\n379:             Memory.status == \"active\",\n380:         )\n381:         .order_by(Memory.recall_count.desc(), Memory.weight.asc())\n382:         .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n383:     )\n384:     result = await db.execute(stmt)\n385:     return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n386: \n387: \n388: async def _query_stale(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n389:     \"\"\"Fetch memories that are likely outdated based on age and recall activity.\"\"\"\n390:     base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n391:     now = datetime.now(UTC)\n392:     thirty_days_ago = now - timedelta(days=30)\n393:     fourteen_days_ago = now - timedelta(days=14)\n394: \n395:     stmt = (\n396:         select(Memory)\n397:         .where(\n398:             *base,\n399:             Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n400:             Memory.status == \"active\",\n401:         )\n402:         .where(\n403:             ((Memory.recall_count == 0) & (Memory.created_at < thirty_days_ago))\n404:             | (\n405:                 (Memory.weight < 0.3)\n406:                 & or_(\n407:                     Memory.last_recalled_at.is_(None),\n408:                     Memory.last_recalled_at < fourteen_days_ago,\n409:                 )\n410:             )\n411:         )\n412:         .order_by(Memory.created_at.asc())\n413:         .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n414:     )\n415:     result = await db.execute(stmt)\n416:     return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n417: \n418: \n419: async def _query_divergence(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n420:     \"\"\"Fetch memories where multiple agents reference the same entities differently.\"\"\"\n\n(Showing lines 1-420 of 1113. Use offset=421 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Insights service -- LLM-powered memory analysis with 6 focus modes.\n\nExamines the memory store to surface contradictions, failure patterns,\nstale knowledge, cross-agent divergence, emerging themes, and unexpected\nvector-space clusters. Findings are persisted as insight-type memories.\n\"\"\"\n\nimport logging\nimport time\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime, timedelta\n\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\nfrom sqlalchemy import distinct, func, or_, select\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom common.models.memory import Memory\nfrom core_api.constants import (\n    INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_CLUSTERS,\n    INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_SAMPLE_SIZE,","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Insights service -- LLM-powered memory analysis with 6 focus modes.\n\nExamines the memory store to surface contradictions, failure patterns,\nstale knowledge, cross-agent divergence, emerging themes, and unexpected\nvector-space clusters. Findings are persisted as insight-type memories.\n\"\"\"\n\nimport logging\nimport time\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime, timedelta\n\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\nfrom sqlalchemy import distinct, func, or_, select\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom common.models.memory import Memory\nfrom core_api.constants import (\n    INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_CLUSTERS,\n    INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_SAMPLE_SIZE,\n    INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES,\n    INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES,\n    INSIGHTS_TEMPERATURE,\n)\nfrom core_api.utils.sanitize import sanitize_content as _sanitize_content\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\n@dataclass\nclass _DiscoverResult:\n    \"\"\"Heterogeneous return type for _query_discover — either clusters or flat memories.\"\"\"\n\n    is_clustered: bool\n    data: list[dict]\n\n\n_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY = {\n    \"agent\": \"scope_agent\",\n    \"fleet\": \"scope_team\",\n    \"all\": \"scope_org\",\n}\n\n\n# -- Prompts -------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n_PROMPT_CONTRADICTIONS = \"\"\"\\\nYou are a memory analyst specializing in contradiction detection.\n\nAnalyze these {count} memories for contradiction clusters. Identify what is \\\ncontradicted, which memories conflict, which version is likely correct \\\n(consider recency, weight, and agent trust), and what should be done to \\\nresolve the conflict.\n\nLook for:\n- Direct factual contradictions (same entity, different values)\n- Superseded memories that may still be recalled\n- Status conflicts (e.g. \"active\" vs \"conflicted\")\n- Temporal contradictions (events placed at incompatible times)\n\nMemories:\n{memories}\n\nRespond with JSON:\n{{\n  \"findings\": [\n    {{\n      \"type\": \"contradictions\",\n      \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n      \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n      \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n    }}\n  ],\n  \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n}}\"\"\"\n\n_PROMPT_FAILURES = \"\"\"\\\nYou are a memory analyst specializing in failure pattern detection.\n\nThese {count} memories have low importance but were recalled by agents -- \\\nmeaning agents may have acted on weak or unreliable information. Identify \\\nrecurring failure patterns, common root causes, and memories that should be \\\ndeprecated or flagged.\n\nLook for:\n- Memories with very low weight that were recalled frequently\n- Patterns in the types of unreliable information\n- Agents that consistently rely on weak memories\n- Information that should have been superseded but wasn't\n\nMemories:\n{memories}\n\nRespond with JSON:\n{{\n  \"findings\": [\n    {{\n      \"type\": \"failures\",\n      \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n      \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n      \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n    }}\n  ],\n  \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n}}\"\"\"\n\n_PROMPT_STALE = \"\"\"\\\nYou are a memory analyst specializing in knowledge freshness.\n\nThese {count} memories are likely outdated -- they haven't been recalled \\\nrecently or have very low weight. Identify which are genuinely stale vs. \\\nrarely needed, and flag ones that could cause harm if recalled.\n\nLook for:\n- Memories about time-sensitive topics (deadlines, prices, versions)\n- Knowledge that likely changed since creation\n- Memories that were never recalled (possibly irrelevant from the start)\n- Low-weight memories that could mislead if surfaced\n\nMemories:\n{memories}\n\nRespond with JSON:\n{{\n  \"findings\": [\n    {{\n      \"type\": \"stale\",\n      \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n      \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n      \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n    }}\n  ],\n  \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n}}\"\"\"\n\n_PROMPT_DIVERGENCE = \"\"\"\\\nYou are a memory analyst specializing in cross-agent knowledge consistency.\n\nThese {count} memories come from different agents about the same entities. \\\nIdentify where agents disagree, which agent's perspective is more credible, \\\nand whether the divergence indicates a real disagreement or different contexts.\n\nLook for:\n- Same entity described differently by different agents\n- Conflicting conclusions or assessments\n- Different levels of detail or confidence\n- Cases where divergence reveals complementary rather than conflicting views\n\nMemories:\n{memories}\n\nRespond with JSON:\n{{\n  \"findings\": [\n    {{\n      \"type\": \"divergence\",\n      \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n      \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n      \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n    }}\n  ],\n  \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n}}\"\"\"\n\n_PROMPT_PATTERNS = \"\"\"\\\nYou are a memory analyst specializing in trend and pattern recognition.\n\nAnalyze these {count} recent memories for emerging themes, trends, and \\\npatterns. What topics are getting more attention? What decisions are being \\\nmade? Are there any concerning patterns?\n\nLook for:\n- Recurring topics or entities across multiple memories\n- Shifts in focus or priority over time\n- Decision patterns and their outcomes\n- Gaps in knowledge coverage\n\nMemories:\n{memories}\n\nRespond with JSON:\n{{\n  \"findings\": [\n    {{\n      \"type\": \"patterns\",\n      \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n      \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n      \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n    }}\n  ],\n  \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n}}\"\"\"\n\n_PROMPT_DISCOVER = \"\"\"\\\nYou are a memory analyst specializing in knowledge topology.\n\nThese are {count} memories organized into natural clusters discovered in the \\\nembedding vector space. For each cluster, what is the underlying theme? Are \\\nany clusters surprising? Are there gaps in knowledge between clusters?\n\nLook for:\n- Unexpected groupings that reveal hidden connections\n- Clusters with high weight variance (inconsistent confidence)\n- Cross-agent clusters (same topic, multiple agents)\n- Missing clusters (topics you'd expect but don't see)\n\nClusters:\n{memories}\n\nRespond with JSON:\n{{\n  \"findings\": [\n    {{\n      \"type\": \"discover\",\n      \"title\": \"short headline (max 80 chars)\",\n      \"description\": \"2-3 sentence explanation\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.0 to 1.0,\n      \"related_memory_ids\": [\"uuid1\", \"uuid2\"],\n      \"recommendation\": \"actionable next step\"\n    }}\n  ],\n  \"summary\": \"one paragraph overview\"\n}}\"\"\"\n\n\n# -- Scope helpers -------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\ndef _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope):\n    \"\"\"Return a list of SQLAlchemy WHERE clauses for the given scope.\"\"\"\n    base = [Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id, Memory.deleted_at.is_(None)]\n\n    if scope == \"agent\":\n        base.append(Memory.agent_id == agent_id)\n        if fleet_id:\n            base.append(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n    elif scope == \"fleet\":\n        if not fleet_id:\n            raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'\")\n        base.append(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n    # scope == \"all\": tenant-wide, no additional filters\n\n    return base\n\n\ndef _rows_to_dicts(rows) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Convert SQLAlchemy Memory rows to plain dicts for prompt formatting.\"\"\"\n    return [\n        {\n            \"id\": str(r.id),\n            \"memory_type\": r.memory_type,\n            \"title\": r.title or \"\",\n            \"content\": r.content,\n            \"weight\": r.weight,\n            \"agent_id\": r.agent_id,\n            \"fleet_id\": r.fleet_id,\n            \"created_at\": r.created_at.isoformat() if r.created_at else \"\",\n            \"status\": r.status,\n            \"recall_count\": r.recall_count or 0,\n            \"last_recalled_at\": r.last_recalled_at.isoformat() if r.last_recalled_at else None,\n            \"supersedes_id\": str(r.supersedes_id) if r.supersedes_id else None,\n            \"subject_entity_id\": str(r.subject_entity_id) if r.subject_entity_id else None,\n            \"object_value\": r.object_value,\n            \"ts_valid_start\": r.ts_valid_start.isoformat() if r.ts_valid_start else None,\n        }\n        for r in rows\n    ]\n\n\n# -- Query functions (one per focus) -------------------------------------------\n\n\nasync def _query_contradictions(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Fetch memories that supersede others, are conflicted, or share entities with divergent values.\"\"\"\n    base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n\n    # Memories that supersede others or are superseded\n    # (exclude insight-type memories to prevent feedback loops where insights\n    # analyze previously generated insights)\n    stmt = (\n        select(Memory)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n        )\n        .where((Memory.supersedes_id.isnot(None)) | (Memory.status == \"conflicted\"))\n        .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n        .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n    )\n    result = await db.execute(stmt)\n    rows = list(result.scalars().all())\n    seen_ids = {r.id for r in rows}\n\n    # Also fetch the superseded memories themselves — the query above returns\n    # the supersedor (the row with supersedes_id IS NOT NULL) but the LLM\n    # needs both sides of the contradiction to reason about which version\n    # is correct. Skip rows we already have.\n    superseded_ids = [\n        r.supersedes_id for r in rows if r.supersedes_id is not None and r.supersedes_id not in seen_ids\n    ]\n    if superseded_ids and len(rows) < INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES:\n        sup_stmt = (\n            select(Memory)\n            .where(\n                *base,\n                Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n                Memory.id.in_(superseded_ids),\n            )\n            .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES - len(rows))\n        )\n        sup_result = await db.execute(sup_stmt)\n        for r in sup_result.scalars().all():\n            if r.id not in seen_ids:\n                rows.append(r)\n                seen_ids.add(r.id)\n\n    # Also find memories sharing subject_entity_id with different object_value\n    if len(rows) < INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES:\n        remaining = INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES - len(rows)\n\n        entity_stmt = (\n            select(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n            .where(\n                *base,\n                Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n                Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n                Memory.subject_entity_id.isnot(None),\n                Memory.object_value.isnot(None),\n            )\n            .group_by(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n            .having(func.count(distinct(Memory.object_value)) > 1)\n            .limit(10)\n        )\n        entity_result = await db.execute(entity_stmt)\n        entity_ids = [r[0] for r in entity_result.all()]\n\n        if entity_ids:\n            extra_stmt = (\n                select(Memory)\n                .where(\n                    *base,\n                    Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n                    Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n                    Memory.subject_entity_id.in_(entity_ids),\n                )\n                .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n                .limit(remaining)\n            )\n            extra_result = await db.execute(extra_stmt)\n            for r in extra_result.scalars().all():\n                if r.id not in seen_ids:\n                    rows.append(r)\n                    seen_ids.add(r.id)\n\n    return _rows_to_dicts(rows[:INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES])\n\n\nasync def _query_failures(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Fetch low-weight memories that were recalled (agents acted on weak info).\"\"\"\n    base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n    stmt = (\n        select(Memory)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n            Memory.weight < 0.3,\n            Memory.recall_count > 0,\n            Memory.status == \"active\",\n        )\n        .order_by(Memory.recall_count.desc(), Memory.weight.asc())\n        .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n    )\n    result = await db.execute(stmt)\n    return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n\n\nasync def _query_stale(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Fetch memories that are likely outdated based on age and recall activity.\"\"\"\n    base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n    now = datetime.now(UTC)\n    thirty_days_ago = now - timedelta(days=30)\n    fourteen_days_ago = now - timedelta(days=14)\n\n    stmt = (\n        select(Memory)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n            Memory.status == \"active\",\n        )\n        .where(\n            ((Memory.recall_count == 0) & (Memory.created_at < thirty_days_ago))\n            | (\n                (Memory.weight < 0.3)\n                & or_(\n                    Memory.last_recalled_at.is_(None),\n                    Memory.last_recalled_at < fourteen_days_ago,\n                )\n            )\n        )\n        .order_by(Memory.created_at.asc())\n        .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n    )\n    result = await db.execute(stmt)\n    return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n\n\nasync def _query_divergence(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Fetch memories where multiple agents reference the same entities differently.\"\"\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":420,"totalLines":1113,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","time":{"start":1780727701178,"end":1780727701183}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf950a188191a9b7b5244ea9a6ea"}},"id":"prt_e9ba45eb30015tU010oO7ZtNar","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727701233,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_bhFTaUJ30O30swpTFeJxhwUe","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/evolve.py","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/evolve.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Evolve REST endpoints — mirrors memclaw_evolve MCP tool.\"\"\"\n2: \n3: from __future__ import annotations\n4: \n5: import logging\n6: \n7: from fastapi import APIRouter, Depends, HTTPException\n8: from pydantic import BaseModel, Field, field_validator, model_validator\n9: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n10: \n11: from core_api.auth import AuthContext, get_auth_context\n12: from core_api.constants import EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES, VALID_SCOPES\n13: from core_api.db.session import get_db\n14: from core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n15: from core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error, require_trust\n16: from core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\n17: \n18: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n19: \n20: router = APIRouter(tags=[\"Evolve\"])\n21: \n22: \n23: # ── Schemas ──\n24: \n25: \n26: class EvolveRequest(BaseModel):\n27:     tenant_id: str\n28:     outcome: str = Field(\n29:         min_length=1,\n30:         description=\"What happened — natural language description of the outcome.\",\n31:     )\n32:     outcome_type: str = Field(\n33:         description=\"Result type: 'success', 'failure', or 'partial'.\",\n34:     )\n35:     related_ids: list[str] | None = Field(\n36:         default=None,\n37:         description=(\n38:             \"Memory UUIDs that influenced your action. Use IDs from your most recent memclaw_recall results.\"\n39:         ),\n40:     )\n41:     scope: str = Field(\n42:         default=\"agent\",\n43:         description=(\n44:             \"Scope: 'agent' (default, requires trust ≥ 1, touches caller-owned memories only), \"\n45:             \"'fleet' (requires trust ≥ 2, touches memories in fleet_id), or \"\n46:             \"'all' (requires trust ≥ 2, tenant-wide).\"\n47:         ),\n48:     )\n49:     agent_id: str | None = Field(\n50:         default=None,\n51:         description=(\n52:             \"Identifier of the reporting agent. Optional: the gateway-\"\n53:             \"verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header takes precedence when present; \"\n54:             \"falls back to 'mcp-agent' when both are absent.\"\n55:         ),\n56:     )\n57:     fleet_id: str | None = Field(\n58:         default=None,\n59:         description=\"Required when scope='fleet'; also used as the outcome/rule memory's fleet_id.\",\n60:     )\n61: \n62:     @field_validator(\"outcome\")\n63:     @classmethod\n64:     def _strip_and_require(cls, v: str) -> str:\n65:         \"\"\"Reject whitespace-only outcomes. Pydantic's ``min_length`` counts\n66:         characters and would otherwise let ``\"   \"`` through, which the MCP\n67:         handler correctly rejects.\"\"\"\n68:         stripped = (v or \"\").strip()\n69:         if not stripped:\n70:             raise ValueError(\"outcome must be a non-empty description.\")\n71:         return stripped\n72: \n73:     @field_validator(\"scope\")\n74:     @classmethod\n75:     def _valid_scope(cls, v: str) -> str:\n76:         if v not in VALID_SCOPES:\n77:             raise ValueError(f\"Invalid scope '{v}'. Must be: {', '.join(VALID_SCOPES)}.\")\n78:         return v\n79: \n80:     @model_validator(mode=\"after\")\n81:     def _fleet_required_when_scope_fleet(self) -> EvolveRequest:\n82:         if self.scope == \"fleet\" and not self.fleet_id:\n83:             raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n84:         return self\n85: \n86: \n87: # ── Routes ──\n88: \n89: \n90: @router.post(\"/evolve/report\")\n91: async def report_outcome_endpoint(\n92:     body: EvolveRequest,\n93:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n94:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n95: ):\n96:     \"\"\"Report an action outcome to evolve memory weights and generate rules.\n97: \n98:     Identity resolution mirrors the data-plane endpoints (write/search/recall):\n99:     if the gateway stamped a verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header (``auth.agent_id``),\n100:     that wins; otherwise ``body.agent_id`` is used. The resolved id must\n101:     correspond to an existing agent in the tenant that meets the scope's\n102:     trust requirement.\n103: \n104:     Trust gating: scope='agent' requires trust ≥ 1, scope='fleet'/'all'\n105:     requires trust ≥ 2. Admin keys bypass.\n106:     \"\"\"\n107:     auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n108:     auth.enforce_read_only()\n109:     auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n110: \n111:     # Validate inputs before consuming rate-limit budget. scope + fleet_id\n112:     # coupling and outcome stripping live on EvolveRequest via\n113:     # ``field_validator`` / ``model_validator``; this body-level check\n114:     # covers outcome_type, which is inherently coupled to a constants table\n115:     # rather than a Literal.\n116:     if body.outcome_type not in EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES:\n117:         raise HTTPException(\n118:             status_code=422,\n119:             detail=(\n120:                 f\"Invalid outcome_type '{body.outcome_type}'. \"\n121:                 f\"Must be one of: {', '.join(EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES)}\"\n122:             ),\n123:         )\n124: \n125:     # Gateway-verified identity wins when present; otherwise fall back to\n126:     # body.agent_id, then to the \"mcp-agent\" placeholder so standalone\n127:     # callers still show up in audit logs. Warn only when the client sent\n128:     # an explicit body.agent_id that disagrees with the verified header —\n129:     # the Pydantic default would fire spuriously on every gateway call.\n130:     if auth.agent_id and body.agent_id is not None and auth.agent_id != body.agent_id:\n131:         logger.warning(\n132:             \"evolve: verified agent_id=%s overrides body.agent_id=%s\",\n133:             auth.agent_id,\n134:             body.agent_id,\n135:         )\n136:     caller_agent_id = auth.agent_id or body.agent_id or \"mcp-agent\"\n137: \n138:     # Admin bypass — super admins are tenant-free and trust enforcement\n139:     # assumes a tenant-scoped agent row.\n140:     if not auth.is_admin:\n141:         if not caller_agent_id:\n142:             raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"agent_id is required.\")\n143:         min_level = 1 if body.scope == \"agent\" else 2\n144:         # ``require_trust`` soft-passes a missing Agent row at\n145:         # ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` so read-only callers don't 403 on a\n146:         # brand-new agent_id. Write paths still need identity pinning,\n147:         # though: this endpoint persists outcome and rule memories\n148:         # plus an audit-log entry keyed to ``caller_agent_id``, and\n149:         # without a registered row backing the name, attribution\n150:         # becomes unverifiable (a tenant-key holder could synthesise\n151:         # ``\"admin-bot\"`` and have that string appear in the audit\n152:         # trail). API-key admission proves authorization, not identity\n153:         # — re-block unregistered agents on writes specifically. The\n154:         # soft-pass remains useful for read-only consumers calling\n155:         # ``require_trust`` directly.\n156:         _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(db, body.tenant_id, caller_agent_id, min_level=min_level)\n157:         if not_found:\n158:             raise HTTPException(\n159:                 status_code=403,\n160:                 detail=f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' is not registered in tenant '{body.tenant_id}'.\",\n161:             )\n162:         if terr:\n163:             raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n164: \n165:     await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"evolve\")\n166: \n167:     from core_api.services.evolve_service import report_outcome\n168: \n169:     # The service raises ValueError for its defensive validation gates\n170:     # (outcome_type, outcome non-empty, scope, fleet_id coupling) so it\n171:     # stays decoupled from FastAPI. Translate here so the REST contract\n172:     # stays 422 for bad input; a 500 would be misleading when the body was\n173:     # simply malformed in a way Pydantic couldn't catch.\n174:     try:\n175:         result = await report_outcome(\n176:             db,\n177:             tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n178:             outcome=body.outcome,\n179:             outcome_type=body.outcome_type,\n180:             related_ids=body.related_ids,\n181:             scope=body.scope,\n182:             agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n183:             fleet_id=body.fleet_id,\n184:         )\n185:     except ValueError as e:\n186:         raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=str(e)) from e\n187: \n188:     await log_action(\n189:         db,\n190:         tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n191:         action=\"evolve_report\",\n192:         resource_type=\"outcome\",\n193:         detail={\n194:             \"outcome_type\": body.outcome_type,\n195:             \"scope\": body.scope,\n196:             \"agent_id\": caller_agent_id,\n197:             \"related_ids\": body.related_ids,\n198:         },\n199:     )\n200:     await db.commit()\n201: \n202:     return result\n\n(End of file - total 202 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Evolve REST endpoints — mirrors memclaw_evolve MCP tool.\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\n\nfrom fastapi import APIRouter, Depends, HTTPException\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field, field_validator, model_validator\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.auth import AuthContext, get_auth_context\nfrom core_api.constants import EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES, VALID_SCOPES\nfrom core_api.db.session import get_db\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\nfrom core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error, require_trust\nfrom core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nrouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"Evolve\"])","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/evolve.py","text":"\"\"\"Evolve REST endpoints — mirrors memclaw_evolve MCP tool.\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\n\nfrom fastapi import APIRouter, Depends, HTTPException\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field, field_validator, model_validator\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.auth import AuthContext, get_auth_context\nfrom core_api.constants import EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES, VALID_SCOPES\nfrom core_api.db.session import get_db\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\nfrom core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error, require_trust\nfrom core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nrouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"Evolve\"])\n\n\n# ── Schemas ──\n\n\nclass EvolveRequest(BaseModel):\n    tenant_id: str\n    outcome: str = Field(\n        min_length=1,\n        description=\"What happened — natural language description of the outcome.\",\n    )\n    outcome_type: str = Field(\n        description=\"Result type: 'success', 'failure', or 'partial'.\",\n    )\n    related_ids: list[str] | None = Field(\n        default=None,\n        description=(\n            \"Memory UUIDs that influenced your action. Use IDs from your most recent memclaw_recall results.\"\n        ),\n    )\n    scope: str = Field(\n        default=\"agent\",\n        description=(\n            \"Scope: 'agent' (default, requires trust ≥ 1, touches caller-owned memories only), \"\n            \"'fleet' (requires trust ≥ 2, touches memories in fleet_id), or \"\n            \"'all' (requires trust ≥ 2, tenant-wide).\"\n        ),\n    )\n    agent_id: str | None = Field(\n        default=None,\n        description=(\n            \"Identifier of the reporting agent. Optional: the gateway-\"\n            \"verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header takes precedence when present; \"\n            \"falls back to 'mcp-agent' when both are absent.\"\n        ),\n    )\n    fleet_id: str | None = Field(\n        default=None,\n        description=\"Required when scope='fleet'; also used as the outcome/rule memory's fleet_id.\",\n    )\n\n    @field_validator(\"outcome\")\n    @classmethod\n    def _strip_and_require(cls, v: str) -> str:\n        \"\"\"Reject whitespace-only outcomes. Pydantic's ``min_length`` counts\n        characters and would otherwise let ``\"   \"`` through, which the MCP\n        handler correctly rejects.\"\"\"\n        stripped = (v or \"\").strip()\n        if not stripped:\n            raise ValueError(\"outcome must be a non-empty description.\")\n        return stripped\n\n    @field_validator(\"scope\")\n    @classmethod\n    def _valid_scope(cls, v: str) -> str:\n        if v not in VALID_SCOPES:\n            raise ValueError(f\"Invalid scope '{v}'. Must be: {', '.join(VALID_SCOPES)}.\")\n        return v\n\n    @model_validator(mode=\"after\")\n    def _fleet_required_when_scope_fleet(self) -> EvolveRequest:\n        if self.scope == \"fleet\" and not self.fleet_id:\n            raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n        return self\n\n\n# ── Routes ──\n\n\n@router.post(\"/evolve/report\")\nasync def report_outcome_endpoint(\n    body: EvolveRequest,\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"Report an action outcome to evolve memory weights and generate rules.\n\n    Identity resolution mirrors the data-plane endpoints (write/search/recall):\n    if the gateway stamped a verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header (``auth.agent_id``),\n    that wins; otherwise ``body.agent_id`` is used. The resolved id must\n    correspond to an existing agent in the tenant that meets the scope's\n    trust requirement.\n\n    Trust gating: scope='agent' requires trust ≥ 1, scope='fleet'/'all'\n    requires trust ≥ 2. Admin keys bypass.\n    \"\"\"\n    auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n    auth.enforce_read_only()\n    auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n\n    # Validate inputs before consuming rate-limit budget. scope + fleet_id\n    # coupling and outcome stripping live on EvolveRequest via\n    # ``field_validator`` / ``model_validator``; this body-level check\n    # covers outcome_type, which is inherently coupled to a constants table\n    # rather than a Literal.\n    if body.outcome_type not in EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=(\n                f\"Invalid outcome_type '{body.outcome_type}'. \"\n                f\"Must be one of: {', '.join(EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES)}\"\n            ),\n        )\n\n    # Gateway-verified identity wins when present; otherwise fall back to\n    # body.agent_id, then to the \"mcp-agent\" placeholder so standalone\n    # callers still show up in audit logs. Warn only when the client sent\n    # an explicit body.agent_id that disagrees with the verified header —\n    # the Pydantic default would fire spuriously on every gateway call.\n    if auth.agent_id and body.agent_id is not None and auth.agent_id != body.agent_id:\n        logger.warning(\n            \"evolve: verified agent_id=%s overrides body.agent_id=%s\",\n            auth.agent_id,\n            body.agent_id,\n        )\n    caller_agent_id = auth.agent_id or body.agent_id or \"mcp-agent\"\n\n    # Admin bypass — super admins are tenant-free and trust enforcement\n    # assumes a tenant-scoped agent row.\n    if not auth.is_admin:\n        if not caller_agent_id:\n            raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"agent_id is required.\")\n        min_level = 1 if body.scope == \"agent\" else 2\n        # ``require_trust`` soft-passes a missing Agent row at\n        # ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` so read-only callers don't 403 on a\n        # brand-new agent_id. Write paths still need identity pinning,\n        # though: this endpoint persists outcome and rule memories\n        # plus an audit-log entry keyed to ``caller_agent_id``, and\n        # without a registered row backing the name, attribution\n        # becomes unverifiable (a tenant-key holder could synthesise\n        # ``\"admin-bot\"`` and have that string appear in the audit\n        # trail). API-key admission proves authorization, not identity\n        # — re-block unregistered agents on writes specifically. The\n        # soft-pass remains useful for read-only consumers calling\n        # ``require_trust`` directly.\n        _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(db, body.tenant_id, caller_agent_id, min_level=min_level)\n        if not_found:\n            raise HTTPException(\n                status_code=403,\n                detail=f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' is not registered in tenant '{body.tenant_id}'.\",\n            )\n        if terr:\n            raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n\n    await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"evolve\")\n\n    from core_api.services.evolve_service import report_outcome\n\n    # The service raises ValueError for its defensive validation gates\n    # (outcome_type, outcome non-empty, scope, fleet_id coupling) so it\n    # stays decoupled from FastAPI. Translate here so the REST contract\n    # stays 422 for bad input; a 500 would be misleading when the body was\n    # simply malformed in a way Pydantic couldn't catch.\n    try:\n        result = await report_outcome(\n            db,\n            tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n            outcome=body.outcome,\n            outcome_type=body.outcome_type,\n            related_ids=body.related_ids,\n            scope=body.scope,\n            agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n            fleet_id=body.fleet_id,\n        )\n    except ValueError as e:\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=str(e)) from e\n\n    await log_action(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n        action=\"evolve_report\",\n        resource_type=\"outcome\",\n        detail={\n            \"outcome_type\": body.outcome_type,\n            \"scope\": body.scope,\n            \"agent_id\": caller_agent_id,\n            \"related_ids\": body.related_ids,\n        },\n    )\n    await db.commit()\n\n    return result","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":202,"totalLines":202,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/evolve.py","time":{"start":1780727701219,"end":1780727701230}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf950a208191b0bd882af967fb84"}},"id":"prt_e9ba45ec0001wPcjx0uF9hXG5c","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727701234,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cXGJUm0V5otFh8qfSRXe8E1F","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/insights.py","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/insights.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Insights REST endpoints — mirrors memclaw_insights MCP tool.\"\"\"\n2: \n3: from __future__ import annotations\n4: \n5: import logging\n6: \n7: from fastapi import APIRouter, Depends, HTTPException\n8: from pydantic import BaseModel, Field, field_validator, model_validator\n9: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n10: \n11: from core_api.auth import AuthContext, get_auth_context\n12: from core_api.constants import INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES, VALID_SCOPES\n13: from core_api.db.session import get_db\n14: from core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n15: from core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error, require_trust\n16: from core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\n17: \n18: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n19: \n20: router = APIRouter(tags=[\"Insights\"])\n21: \n22: \n23: # ── Schemas ──\n24: \n25: \n26: class InsightsRequest(BaseModel):\n27:     tenant_id: str\n28:     focus: str = Field(\n29:         description=(\n30:             \"Analysis focus: 'contradictions', 'failures', 'stale', 'divergence', 'patterns', or 'discover'.\"\n31:         ),\n32:     )\n33:     scope: str = Field(\n34:         default=\"agent\",\n35:         description=\"Scope: 'agent' (your memories), 'fleet' (fleet-wide), or 'all' (tenant-wide).\",\n36:     )\n37:     fleet_id: str | None = Field(\n38:         default=None,\n39:         description=\"Fleet to analyze (required when scope='fleet').\",\n40:     )\n41:     agent_id: str | None = Field(\n42:         default=None,\n43:         description=(\n44:             \"Identifier of the requesting agent. Optional: the gateway-\"\n45:             \"verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header takes precedence when present; \"\n46:             \"falls back to 'mcp-agent' when both are absent.\"\n47:         ),\n48:     )\n49: \n50:     @field_validator(\"scope\")\n51:     @classmethod\n52:     def _valid_scope(cls, v: str) -> str:\n53:         if v not in VALID_SCOPES:\n54:             raise ValueError(f\"Invalid scope '{v}'. Must be: {', '.join(VALID_SCOPES)}.\")\n55:         return v\n56: \n57:     @model_validator(mode=\"after\")\n58:     def _scope_focus_coupling(self) -> InsightsRequest:\n59:         if self.scope == \"fleet\" and not self.fleet_id:\n60:             raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n61:         if self.focus == \"divergence\" and self.scope == \"agent\":\n62:             raise ValueError(\"Focus 'divergence' requires scope='fleet' or scope='all'.\")\n63:         return self\n64: \n65: \n66: # ── Routes ──\n67: \n68: \n69: @router.post(\"/insights/generate\")\n70: async def generate_insights_endpoint(\n71:     body: InsightsRequest,\n72:     auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n73:     db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n74: ):\n75:     \"\"\"Generate insights over stored memories.\n76: \n77:     Identity resolution mirrors the data-plane endpoints (write/search/recall):\n78:     if the gateway stamped a verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header (``auth.agent_id``),\n79:     that wins; otherwise ``body.agent_id`` is used. The resolved id must\n80:     correspond to an existing agent in the tenant that meets the scope's\n81:     trust requirement.\n82: \n83:     Trust gating: scope='agent' requires trust ≥ 1, scope='fleet'/'all'\n84:     requires trust ≥ 2. Admin keys bypass.\n85:     \"\"\"\n86:     auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n87:     auth.enforce_read_only()\n88:     auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n89: \n90:     # Validate inputs before consuming rate-limit budget. scope/fleet_id/focus\n91:     # coupling lives on InsightsRequest via ``field_validator`` /\n92:     # ``model_validator``; this body-level check only covers the focus enum,\n93:     # which is inherently coupled to a constants table rather than a Literal.\n94:     if body.focus not in INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES:\n95:         raise HTTPException(\n96:             status_code=422,\n97:             detail=f\"Invalid focus '{body.focus}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES)}\",\n98:         )\n99: \n100:     # Gateway-verified identity wins when present; otherwise fall back to\n101:     # body.agent_id, then to the \"mcp-agent\" placeholder so standalone\n102:     # callers still show up in audit logs. Warn only when the client sent\n103:     # an explicit body.agent_id that disagrees with the verified header —\n104:     # the Pydantic default would fire spuriously on every gateway call.\n105:     if auth.agent_id and body.agent_id is not None and auth.agent_id != body.agent_id:\n106:         logger.warning(\n107:             \"insights: verified agent_id=%s overrides body.agent_id=%s\",\n108:             auth.agent_id,\n109:             body.agent_id,\n110:         )\n111:     caller_agent_id = auth.agent_id or body.agent_id or \"mcp-agent\"\n112: \n113:     # Admin bypass — super admins are tenant-free and trust enforcement\n114:     # assumes a tenant-scoped agent row.\n115:     if not auth.is_admin:\n116:         if not caller_agent_id:\n117:             raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"agent_id is required.\")\n118:         min_level = 1 if body.scope == \"agent\" else 2\n119:         # ``require_trust`` soft-passes a missing Agent row at\n120:         # ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` so read-only callers don't 403 on a\n121:         # brand-new agent_id. Write paths still need identity pinning,\n122:         # though: this endpoint persists insight memories plus an\n123:         # audit-log entry keyed to ``caller_agent_id``, and without a\n124:         # registered row backing the name, attribution becomes\n125:         # unverifiable. API-key admission proves authorization, not\n126:         # identity — re-block unregistered agents on writes\n127:         # specifically. The soft-pass remains useful for read-only\n128:         # consumers calling ``require_trust`` directly.\n129:         _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(db, body.tenant_id, caller_agent_id, min_level=min_level)\n130:         if not_found:\n131:             raise HTTPException(\n132:                 status_code=403,\n133:                 detail=f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' is not registered in tenant '{body.tenant_id}'.\",\n134:             )\n135:         if terr:\n136:             raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n137: \n138:     await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"insights\")\n139: \n140:     from core_api.services.insights_service import generate_insights\n141: \n142:     result = await generate_insights(\n143:         db,\n144:         tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n145:         focus=body.focus,\n146:         scope=body.scope,\n147:         fleet_id=body.fleet_id,\n148:         agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n149:     )\n150: \n151:     await log_action(\n152:         db,\n153:         tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n154:         action=\"insights_generate\",\n155:         resource_type=\"insight\",\n156:         detail={\"focus\": body.focus, \"scope\": body.scope, \"agent_id\": caller_agent_id},\n157:     )\n158:     await db.commit()\n159: \n160:     return result\n\n(End of file - total 160 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Insights REST endpoints — mirrors memclaw_insights MCP tool.\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\n\nfrom fastapi import APIRouter, Depends, HTTPException\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field, field_validator, model_validator\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.auth import AuthContext, get_auth_context\nfrom core_api.constants import INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES, VALID_SCOPES\nfrom core_api.db.session import get_db\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\nfrom core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error, require_trust\nfrom core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nrouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"Insights\"])","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/insights.py","text":"\"\"\"Insights REST endpoints — mirrors memclaw_insights MCP tool.\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nimport logging\n\nfrom fastapi import APIRouter, Depends, HTTPException\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field, field_validator, model_validator\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.auth import AuthContext, get_auth_context\nfrom core_api.constants import INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES, VALID_SCOPES\nfrom core_api.db.session import get_db\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\nfrom core_api.services.trust_service import parse_trust_error, require_trust\nfrom core_api.services.usage_service import check_and_increment_by_tenant as check_and_increment\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nrouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"Insights\"])\n\n\n# ── Schemas ──\n\n\nclass InsightsRequest(BaseModel):\n    tenant_id: str\n    focus: str = Field(\n        description=(\n            \"Analysis focus: 'contradictions', 'failures', 'stale', 'divergence', 'patterns', or 'discover'.\"\n        ),\n    )\n    scope: str = Field(\n        default=\"agent\",\n        description=\"Scope: 'agent' (your memories), 'fleet' (fleet-wide), or 'all' (tenant-wide).\",\n    )\n    fleet_id: str | None = Field(\n        default=None,\n        description=\"Fleet to analyze (required when scope='fleet').\",\n    )\n    agent_id: str | None = Field(\n        default=None,\n        description=(\n            \"Identifier of the requesting agent. Optional: the gateway-\"\n            \"verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header takes precedence when present; \"\n            \"falls back to 'mcp-agent' when both are absent.\"\n        ),\n    )\n\n    @field_validator(\"scope\")\n    @classmethod\n    def _valid_scope(cls, v: str) -> str:\n        if v not in VALID_SCOPES:\n            raise ValueError(f\"Invalid scope '{v}'. Must be: {', '.join(VALID_SCOPES)}.\")\n        return v\n\n    @model_validator(mode=\"after\")\n    def _scope_focus_coupling(self) -> InsightsRequest:\n        if self.scope == \"fleet\" and not self.fleet_id:\n            raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n        if self.focus == \"divergence\" and self.scope == \"agent\":\n            raise ValueError(\"Focus 'divergence' requires scope='fleet' or scope='all'.\")\n        return self\n\n\n# ── Routes ──\n\n\n@router.post(\"/insights/generate\")\nasync def generate_insights_endpoint(\n    body: InsightsRequest,\n    auth: AuthContext = Depends(get_auth_context),\n    db: AsyncSession = Depends(get_db),\n):\n    \"\"\"Generate insights over stored memories.\n\n    Identity resolution mirrors the data-plane endpoints (write/search/recall):\n    if the gateway stamped a verified ``X-Agent-ID`` header (``auth.agent_id``),\n    that wins; otherwise ``body.agent_id`` is used. The resolved id must\n    correspond to an existing agent in the tenant that meets the scope's\n    trust requirement.\n\n    Trust gating: scope='agent' requires trust ≥ 1, scope='fleet'/'all'\n    requires trust ≥ 2. Admin keys bypass.\n    \"\"\"\n    auth.enforce_tenant(body.tenant_id)\n    auth.enforce_read_only()\n    auth.enforce_usage_limits()\n\n    # Validate inputs before consuming rate-limit budget. scope/fleet_id/focus\n    # coupling lives on InsightsRequest via ``field_validator`` /\n    # ``model_validator``; this body-level check only covers the focus enum,\n    # which is inherently coupled to a constants table rather than a Literal.\n    if body.focus not in INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=f\"Invalid focus '{body.focus}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES)}\",\n        )\n\n    # Gateway-verified identity wins when present; otherwise fall back to\n    # body.agent_id, then to the \"mcp-agent\" placeholder so standalone\n    # callers still show up in audit logs. Warn only when the client sent\n    # an explicit body.agent_id that disagrees with the verified header —\n    # the Pydantic default would fire spuriously on every gateway call.\n    if auth.agent_id and body.agent_id is not None and auth.agent_id != body.agent_id:\n        logger.warning(\n            \"insights: verified agent_id=%s overrides body.agent_id=%s\",\n            auth.agent_id,\n            body.agent_id,\n        )\n    caller_agent_id = auth.agent_id or body.agent_id or \"mcp-agent\"\n\n    # Admin bypass — super admins are tenant-free and trust enforcement\n    # assumes a tenant-scoped agent row.\n    if not auth.is_admin:\n        if not caller_agent_id:\n            raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=\"agent_id is required.\")\n        min_level = 1 if body.scope == \"agent\" else 2\n        # ``require_trust`` soft-passes a missing Agent row at\n        # ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` so read-only callers don't 403 on a\n        # brand-new agent_id. Write paths still need identity pinning,\n        # though: this endpoint persists insight memories plus an\n        # audit-log entry keyed to ``caller_agent_id``, and without a\n        # registered row backing the name, attribution becomes\n        # unverifiable. API-key admission proves authorization, not\n        # identity — re-block unregistered agents on writes\n        # specifically. The soft-pass remains useful for read-only\n        # consumers calling ``require_trust`` directly.\n        _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(db, body.tenant_id, caller_agent_id, min_level=min_level)\n        if not_found:\n            raise HTTPException(\n                status_code=403,\n                detail=f\"Agent '{caller_agent_id}' is not registered in tenant '{body.tenant_id}'.\",\n            )\n        if terr:\n            raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n\n    await check_and_increment(db, body.tenant_id, \"insights\")\n\n    from core_api.services.insights_service import generate_insights\n\n    result = await generate_insights(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n        focus=body.focus,\n        scope=body.scope,\n        fleet_id=body.fleet_id,\n        agent_id=caller_agent_id,\n    )\n\n    await log_action(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=body.tenant_id,\n        action=\"insights_generate\",\n        resource_type=\"insight\",\n        detail={\"focus\": body.focus, \"scope\": body.scope, \"agent_id\": caller_agent_id},\n    )\n    await db.commit()\n\n    return result","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":160,"totalLines":160,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/routes/insights.py","time":{"start":1780727701222,"end":1780727701231}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf950a2881919cacc176c90a43c3"}},"id":"prt_e9ba45ee500196vqBDLRJx1qLR","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727701234,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_bCyySaZ4rUL4Pn6m6JwTnI4X","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_evolve.py","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_evolve.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"ToolSpec for memclaw_evolve — Karpathy Loop feedback edge.\n2: \n3: Records a real-world outcome against the memories that influenced an\n4: action: adjusts weights, optionally generates preventive rules on\n5: failure/partial outcomes.\n6: \n7: scope='agent' (default) at trust ≥ 1; scope='fleet'/'all' requires trust ≥ 2.\n8: Exposed via both MCP and REST (``/api/v1/evolve/report``).\n9: \"\"\"\n10: \n11: from core_api import mcp_server\n12: \n13: from ._builders import mcp_register\n14: from ._registry import register\n15: from ._types import ToolSpec\n16: \n17: _DESCRIPTION = (\n18:     \"Report what happened after acting on memories. outcome_type: success|failure|partial. \"\n19:     \"related_ids = the memory UUIDs that influenced the action (use IDs from your most recent \"\n20:     \"memclaw_recall). scope: agent (default, trust ≥ 1)|fleet|all (trust ≥ 2; fleet_id required \"\n21:     \"when scope='fleet'). Weight adjustments and rule generation are scoped — agents can only \"\n22:     \"evolve memories they own (scope=agent), their fleet (scope=fleet), or any (scope=all).\"\n23: )\n24: \n25: _SPEC = ToolSpec(\n26:     name=\"memclaw_evolve\",\n27:     description=_DESCRIPTION,\n28:     handler=mcp_server.memclaw_evolve,\n29:     plugin_exposed=True,\n30:     trust_required=1,\n31:     impl_status=\"live\",\n32: )\n33: register(_SPEC)\n34: mcp_register(mcp_server.mcp, _SPEC)\n\n(End of file - total 34 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"ToolSpec for memclaw_evolve — Karpathy Loop feedback edge.\n\nRecords a real-world outcome against the memories that influenced an\naction: adjusts weights, optionally generates preventive rules on\nfailure/partial outcomes.\n\nscope='agent' (default) at trust ≥ 1; scope='fleet'/'all' requires trust ≥ 2.\nExposed via both MCP and REST (``/api/v1/evolve/report``).\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom core_api import mcp_server\n\nfrom ._builders import mcp_register\nfrom ._registry import register\nfrom ._types import ToolSpec\n\n_DESCRIPTION = (\n    \"Report what happened after acting on memories. outcome_type: success|failure|partial. \"\n    \"related_ids = the memory UUIDs that influenced the action (use IDs from your most recent \"\n    \"memclaw_recall). scope: agent (default, trust ≥ 1)|fleet|all (trust ≥ 2; fleet_id required \"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_evolve.py","text":"\"\"\"ToolSpec for memclaw_evolve — Karpathy Loop feedback edge.\n\nRecords a real-world outcome against the memories that influenced an\naction: adjusts weights, optionally generates preventive rules on\nfailure/partial outcomes.\n\nscope='agent' (default) at trust ≥ 1; scope='fleet'/'all' requires trust ≥ 2.\nExposed via both MCP and REST (``/api/v1/evolve/report``).\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom core_api import mcp_server\n\nfrom ._builders import mcp_register\nfrom ._registry import register\nfrom ._types import ToolSpec\n\n_DESCRIPTION = (\n    \"Report what happened after acting on memories. outcome_type: success|failure|partial. \"\n    \"related_ids = the memory UUIDs that influenced the action (use IDs from your most recent \"\n    \"memclaw_recall). scope: agent (default, trust ≥ 1)|fleet|all (trust ≥ 2; fleet_id required \"\n    \"when scope='fleet'). Weight adjustments and rule generation are scoped — agents can only \"\n    \"evolve memories they own (scope=agent), their fleet (scope=fleet), or any (scope=all).\"\n)\n\n_SPEC = ToolSpec(\n    name=\"memclaw_evolve\",\n    description=_DESCRIPTION,\n    handler=mcp_server.memclaw_evolve,\n    plugin_exposed=True,\n    trust_required=1,\n    impl_status=\"live\",\n)\nregister(_SPEC)\nmcp_register(mcp_server.mcp, _SPEC)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":34,"totalLines":34,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_evolve.py","time":{"start":1780727701224,"end":1780727701232}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf950a3081918f079b9310b47a3b"}},"id":"prt_e9ba45ee70019iimfTFil8xlrS","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727701234,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_qZWgQlal2jltARsH2EM8C69w","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_insights.py","offset":1,"limit":120},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_insights.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"ToolSpec for memclaw_insights — Karpathy Loop reflection step.\n2: \n3: LLM-driven analysis over targeted memory subsets. Findings are persisted\n4: as ``insight``-typed memories so they compound across sessions.\n5: \n6: scope='agent' at trust ≥ 1; scope='fleet'/'all' requires trust ≥ 2.\n7: Exposed via both MCP and REST (``/api/v1/insights/generate``).\n8: \"\"\"\n9: \n10: from core_api import mcp_server\n11: \n12: from ._builders import mcp_register\n13: from ._registry import register\n14: from ._types import ToolSpec\n15: \n16: _DESCRIPTION = (\n17:     \"Reflect over your memory store. focus: contradictions|failures|stale|divergence|\"\n18:     \"patterns|discover. scope: agent (default, trust ≥ 1)|fleet|all (trust ≥ 2; \"\n19:     \"divergence requires fleet/all). \"\n20:     \"Findings are saved as insight-type memories for future runs to build on.\"\n21: )\n22: \n23: _SPEC = ToolSpec(\n24:     name=\"memclaw_insights\",\n25:     description=_DESCRIPTION,\n26:     handler=mcp_server.memclaw_insights,\n27:     plugin_exposed=True,\n28:     trust_required=1,\n29:     impl_status=\"live\",\n30: )\n31: register(_SPEC)\n32: mcp_register(mcp_server.mcp, _SPEC)\n\n(End of file - total 32 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"ToolSpec for memclaw_insights — Karpathy Loop reflection step.\n\nLLM-driven analysis over targeted memory subsets. Findings are persisted\nas ``insight``-typed memories so they compound across sessions.\n\nscope='agent' at trust ≥ 1; scope='fleet'/'all' requires trust ≥ 2.\nExposed via both MCP and REST (``/api/v1/insights/generate``).\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom core_api import mcp_server\n\nfrom ._builders import mcp_register\nfrom ._registry import register\nfrom ._types import ToolSpec\n\n_DESCRIPTION = (\n    \"Reflect over your memory store. focus: contradictions|failures|stale|divergence|\"\n    \"patterns|discover. scope: agent (default, trust ≥ 1)|fleet|all (trust ≥ 2; \"\n    \"divergence requires fleet/all). \"\n    \"Findings are saved as insight-type memories for future runs to build on.\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_insights.py","text":"\"\"\"ToolSpec for memclaw_insights — Karpathy Loop reflection step.\n\nLLM-driven analysis over targeted memory subsets. Findings are persisted\nas ``insight``-typed memories so they compound across sessions.\n\nscope='agent' at trust ≥ 1; scope='fleet'/'all' requires trust ≥ 2.\nExposed via both MCP and REST (``/api/v1/insights/generate``).\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom core_api import mcp_server\n\nfrom ._builders import mcp_register\nfrom ._registry import register\nfrom ._types import ToolSpec\n\n_DESCRIPTION = (\n    \"Reflect over your memory store. focus: contradictions|failures|stale|divergence|\"\n    \"patterns|discover. scope: agent (default, trust ≥ 1)|fleet|all (trust ≥ 2; \"\n    \"divergence requires fleet/all). \"\n    \"Findings are saved as insight-type memories for future runs to build on.\"\n)\n\n_SPEC = ToolSpec(\n    name=\"memclaw_insights\",\n    description=_DESCRIPTION,\n    handler=mcp_server.memclaw_insights,\n    plugin_exposed=True,\n    trust_required=1,\n    impl_status=\"live\",\n)\nregister(_SPEC)\nmcp_register(mcp_server.mcp, _SPEC)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":32,"totalLines":32,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/tools/memclaw_insights.py","time":{"start":1780727701225,"end":1780727701233}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0f3cc752e8db28ed016a23bf950a348191b64feaa9a7d12ab3"}},"id":"prt_e9ba45ee8001t16KJDXyNHSeo8","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780727701556,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba46032001kST4xfOKq21ONV","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"224e8844b81c7c3b8acf538cf3e4ec3bf33b1651","messageID":"msg_e9ba42769001UN6osxiJY4MxVF","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":53755,"input":4477,"output":620,"reasoning":18,"cache":{"write":0,"read":48640}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780727703822,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"id":"prt_e9ba4690d001vr9kCk7ujKssIe","messageID":"msg_e9ba46134001IlymZNIpdlKxji","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","snapshot":"dc03acbb307bfe60f5a66339648931adef64ef7f","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727714171,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Fqi1ax4qvqp0HekkFsy7MgXs","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","offset":361,"limit":360},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n361:     # adjustment batch from the outer evolve transaction; per-row\n362:     # isolation is not preserved — a DB error aborts all weight updates\n363:     # as a unit. The outer evolve transaction still gets to persist the\n364:     # outcome / rule memory rows downstream regardless.\n365:     try:\n366:         async with db.begin_nested():\n367:             result = await db.execute(\n368:                 _ADJUST_WEIGHTS_BULK_SQL,\n369:                 {\n370:                     \"mids\": valid_uuids,\n371:                     \"tid\": tenant_id,\n372:                     \"floor\": EVOLVE_WEIGHT_FLOOR,\n373:                     \"cap\": EVOLVE_WEIGHT_CAP,\n374:                     \"delta\": delta,\n375:                 },\n376:             )\n377:             rows = result.fetchall()\n378:     except Exception:\n379:         logger.warning(\"evolve: bulk weight update failed for %d memories\", len(valid_uuids), exc_info=True)\n380:         return \"no_rows_updated\", [], []\n381: \n382:     # Map returned rows by id so we can preserve the caller's input\n383:     # ordering when building the response. Rows missing from the\n384:     # result set correspond to ids not found (or filtered by the\n385:     # tenant + deleted_at predicate); skip them with the same\n386:     # warning the per-row path emitted previously.\n387:     #\n388:     # ``UUID(str(row.id))`` normalises the key — some DB drivers /\n389:     # cursor result shapes hand ``row.id`` back as ``str`` rather than\n390:     # ``uuid.UUID``. Without normalisation the lookup below\n391:     # (``row_by_id.get(mid)`` with a real ``UUID`` key) silently\n392:     # misses every row, falling through to the \"not found\" warning\n393:     # branch and dropping the whole batch from the response.\n394:     row_by_id = {UUID(str(row.id)): row for row in rows}\n395:     for mid_str, mid in parsed:\n396:         row = row_by_id.get(mid)\n397:         if row is None:\n398:             logger.warning(\"evolve: memory %s not found for tenant %s, skipping\", mid, tenant_id)\n399:             continue\n400:         successfully_adjusted.append(mid_str)\n401:         adjustments.append(\n402:             {\n403:                 \"memory_id\": mid_str,\n404:                 \"old_weight\": round(float(row.old_weight), 4),\n405:                 \"new_weight\": round(float(row.new_weight), 4),\n406:                 \"delta\": round(delta, 4),\n407:             }\n408:         )\n409: \n410:     # Race / no-match path: parse + UPDATE succeeded but no rows came back\n411:     # (a row was deleted between _filter_by_scope and the UPDATE, or every\n412:     # id failed the tenant+deleted_at predicate). Surface as a slug so the\n413:     # caller can distinguish from a success.\n414:     skip_reason = \"no_rows_updated\" if not successfully_adjusted else None\n415:     return skip_reason, successfully_adjusted, adjustments\n416: \n417: \n418: # -- Rule generation ----------------------------------------------------------\n419: \n420: \n421: def _fake_rule() -> dict:\n422:     \"\"\"Placeholder rule for fake/test LLM provider.\"\"\"\n423:     return {\n424:         \"condition\": \"When encountering a similar situation\",\n425:         \"action\": \"Verify information against the most recent source before acting\",\n426:         \"confidence\": 0.6,\n427:         \"reasoning\": \"Fake rule generated for testing.\",\n428:     }\n429: \n430: \n431: async def _generate_rule(\n432:     tenant_id: str,\n433:     outcome: str,\n434:     outcome_type: str,\n435:     related_ids: list[str],\n436:     config,\n437:     agent_id: str,\n438:     fleet_id: str | None,\n439: ) -> tuple[str | None, dict | None]:\n440:     \"\"\"Ask LLM to generate a preventive rule from a failure/partial outcome.\n441: \n442:     Returns ``(skip_reason, rule)``:\n443:       - ``(None, {...})`` on success\n444:       - ``(<RULE_SKIP_REASONS slug>, None)`` on any silent-exit path\n445: \n446:     A10 widened the return from ``dict | None`` to the tuple so callers\n447:     (``report_outcome``) can propagate the specific reason out to the\n448:     response + structured log instead of conflating \"no candidates\",\n449:     \"LLM blew up\", and \"fetched zero memories\" into a single None.\n450: \n451:     Audit P3 (evolve): ``db`` was removed from this signature. The\n452:     function only used it to resolve tenant config; callers now do\n453:     that themselves and pass ``config`` in. This lets the MCP tool\n454:     (``memclaw_evolve``) close its DB session before invoking the\n455:     LLM round-trip — which can take multiple seconds and would\n456:     otherwise pin a pooled connection.\n457: \n458:     ``agent_id`` and ``fleet_id`` are reserved arguments; the body\n459:     does not use them today but they're preserved so future\n460:     rule-generation strategies (per-agent prompts, fleet-scoped\n461:     examples) can light up without a signature break.\n462:     \"\"\"\n463:     from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n464:     from core_api.providers._retry import call_with_fallback\n465: \n466:     sc = get_storage_client()\n467: \n468:     # Fetch related memories for context (cap at 10 for prompt size).\n469:     # Parallelize HTTP fetches so latency is O(1) instead of O(n) round trips.\n470:     # Sanitize title/content before putting them into the LLM prompt — they\n471:     # originate from agent writes and can contain injection attempts.\n472:     async def _fetch(mid_str: str) -> tuple[str, dict | None]:\n473:         try:\n474:             return mid_str, await sc.get_memory_for_tenant(tenant_id, mid_str)\n475:         except Exception:\n476:             logger.warning(\"evolve: fetch failed for memory %s\", mid_str, exc_info=True)\n477:             return mid_str, None\n478: \n479:     # Dedup before slicing so the prompt doesn't repeat the same memory\n480:     # if the caller passed duplicate UUIDs.\n481:     unique_ids = list(dict.fromkeys(related_ids))[:10]\n482:     fetched = await asyncio.gather(*[_fetch(m) for m in unique_ids])\n483:     memories_text_lines = []\n484:     for mid_str, mem in fetched:\n485:         if not mem:\n486:             continue\n487:         title = _sanitize_content(mem.get(\"title\") or \"\", max_len=120)\n488:         content = _sanitize_content(mem.get(\"content\") or \"\", max_len=500)\n489:         weight = mem.get(\"weight\", 0.5)\n490:         mtype = mem.get(\"memory_type\", \"fact\")\n491:         memories_text_lines.append(f\"- (id:{mid_str}) [{mtype}] {title}: {content} [weight: {weight:.2f}]\")\n492: \n493:     if not memories_text_lines:\n494:         return (\"no_memories_fetched\", None)\n495: \n496:     memories_text = \"\\n\".join(memories_text_lines)\n497:     # Escape user-controlled braces before .format() — both outcome (agent input)\n498:     # and memories_text (DB content/titles) can contain literal {word} that would\n499:     # otherwise raise KeyError outside the call_with_fallback try/except.\n500:     # Also cap outcome size to bound prompt tokens.\n501:     safe_outcome = _sanitize_content(outcome, max_len=2000).replace(\"{\", \"{{\").replace(\"}\", \"}}\")\n502:     safe_memories = memories_text.replace(\"{\", \"{{\").replace(\"}\", \"}}\")\n503:     prompt = _RULE_GENERATION_PROMPT.format(\n504:         outcome=safe_outcome,\n505:         outcome_type=outcome_type,\n506:         memories=safe_memories,\n507:         count=len(memories_text_lines),\n508:     )\n509: \n510:     async def _do_generate(llm) -> dict:\n511:         return await llm.complete_json(prompt, temperature=EVOLVE_RULE_TEMPERATURE)\n512: \n513:     try:\n514:         raw = await call_with_fallback(\n515:             primary_provider_name=config.enrichment_provider,\n516:             call_fn=_do_generate,\n517:             fake_fn=_fake_rule,\n518:             tenant_config=config,\n519:             service_label=\"evolve-rule\",\n520:             model_override=config.enrichment_model,\n521:         )\n522:     except Exception:\n523:         logger.exception(\"evolve: rule generation failed\")\n524:         return (\"llm_failed\", None)\n525: \n526:     if not isinstance(raw, dict):\n527:         return (\"llm_failed\", None)\n528: \n529:     # LLMs occasionally return confidence as None, a string like \"high\", or\n530:     # omit it entirely. Coerce defensively to avoid TypeError/ValueError\n531:     # propagating out of the service.\n532:     try:\n533:         confidence = max(0.0, min(1.0, float(raw.get(\"confidence\") or 0.0)))\n534:     except (TypeError, ValueError):\n535:         confidence = 0.0\n536: \n537:     return (\n538:         None,\n539:         {\n540:             \"condition\": str(raw.get(\"condition\", \"\"))[:500],\n541:             \"action\": str(raw.get(\"action\", \"\"))[:500],\n542:             \"confidence\": confidence,\n543:             \"reasoning\": str(raw.get(\"reasoning\", \"\"))[:500],\n544:         },\n545:     )\n546: \n547: \n548: # -- Persist ------------------------------------------------------------------\n549: \n550: \n551: async def _persist_outcome(\n552:     db: AsyncSession,\n553:     tenant_id: str,\n554:     agent_id: str,\n555:     fleet_id: str | None,\n556:     outcome: str,\n557:     outcome_type: str,\n558:     related_ids: list[str],\n559:     weight_adjustments: list[dict],\n560:     rule_memory_id: str | None,\n561:     scope: str,\n562: ) -> str:\n563:     \"\"\"Write the outcome as a memory of type 'outcome'. Returns outcome memory ID.\n564: \n565:     `rule_memory_id` is the ID of the rule memory persisted in Phase 4 (or None\n566:     if no rule met the confidence threshold). Storing the resolved ID — rather\n567:     than a `rule_generated` boolean — avoids the case where the flag claims a\n568:     rule exists but no corresponding memory was actually created.\n569: \n570:     `scope` determines the outcome memory's visibility via _SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY\n571:     so scope='agent' outcomes stay private and scope='all' outcomes are visible\n572:     tenant-wide.\n573:     \"\"\"\n574:     from core_api.schemas import MemoryCreate\n575:     from core_api.services.memory_service import create_memory\n576: \n577:     # Failure outcomes get higher weight — more informative for future analysis\n578:     weight_map = {\"success\": 0.6, \"failure\": 0.7, \"partial\": 0.5}\n579: \n580:     # Cap outcome length to bound persisted content size (consistent with\n581:     # rule fields capped at 500 chars in _generate_rule).\n582:     content = f\"[Outcome/{outcome_type}] {outcome[:2000]}\"\n583: \n584:     data = MemoryCreate(\n585:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n586:         agent_id=agent_id,\n587:         fleet_id=fleet_id,\n588:         memory_type=\"outcome\",\n589:         content=content,\n590:         weight=weight_map.get(outcome_type, 0.5),\n591:         metadata={\n592:             \"outcome_type\": outcome_type,\n593:             \"related_memory_ids\": related_ids,\n594:             \"weight_adjustments\": weight_adjustments,\n595:             \"rule_memory_id\": rule_memory_id,\n596:             \"scope\": scope,\n597:         },\n598:         visibility=_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY.get(scope, \"scope_team\"),\n599:         write_mode=\"fast\",\n600:     )\n601: \n602:     # Savepoint isolates a DB error inside create_memory so the outer\n603:     # transaction stays usable. Outcome persistence is mandatory (unlike\n604:     # the rule), so re-raise after the savepoint rolls back to signal\n605:     # failure to the caller.\n606:     try:\n607:         async with db.begin_nested():\n608:             result = await create_memory(db, data)\n609:     except Exception:\n610:         logger.exception(\"evolve: failed to persist outcome\")\n611:         raise\n612:     return str(result.id)\n613: \n614: \n615: async def _persist_rule(\n616:     db: AsyncSession,\n617:     tenant_id: str,\n618:     agent_id: str,\n619:     fleet_id: str | None,\n620:     rule: dict,\n621:     scope: str,\n622:     outcome_id: str | None = None,\n623: ) -> str | None:\n624:     \"\"\"Write a generated rule as a memory of type 'rule'. Returns rule memory ID.\n625: \n626:     `outcome_id` is optional because the rule is now persisted before the\n627:     outcome memory (so the outcome metadata can record the resolved\n628:     rule_memory_id). The reverse link from rule → outcome is set to None;\n629:     callers can backfill if a strict bidirectional link is required.\n630: \n631:     `scope` controls the persisted rule's visibility so a rule generated from\n632:     scope='agent' evolve stays private to the reporting agent, while a\n633:     scope='all' rule is visible tenant-wide.\n634:     \"\"\"\n635:     from core_api.schemas import MemoryCreate\n636:     from core_api.services.memory_service import create_memory\n637: \n638:     condition = rule.get(\"condition\", \"\")\n639:     action = rule.get(\"action\", \"\")\n640:     confidence = rule.get(\"confidence\", 0.5)\n641:     reasoning = rule.get(\"reasoning\", \"\")\n642: \n643:     content = f\"RULE: IF {condition} THEN {action}\"\n644:     if reasoning:\n645:         content += f\" (Reasoning: {reasoning})\"\n646: \n647:     data = MemoryCreate(\n648:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n649:         agent_id=agent_id,\n650:         fleet_id=fleet_id,\n651:         memory_type=\"rule\",\n652:         content=content,\n653:         weight=confidence,\n654:         metadata={\n655:             \"rule_condition\": condition,\n656:             \"rule_action\": action,\n657:             \"rule_confidence\": confidence,\n658:             \"rule_reasoning\": reasoning,\n659:             \"source_outcome_id\": outcome_id,\n660:             \"generated_by\": \"evolve\",\n661:             \"scope\": scope,\n662:         },\n663:         visibility=_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY.get(scope, \"scope_team\"),\n664:         write_mode=\"fast\",\n665:     )\n666: \n667:     # Savepoint isolates the rule write: if create_memory raises after dirtying\n668:     # the session (e.g. a side-effect DB write fails before the HTTP call), the\n669:     # outer transaction can still proceed with weight adjustments and the\n670:     # outcome write without the session being in a failed state.\n671:     try:\n672:         async with db.begin_nested():\n673:             result = await create_memory(db, data)\n674:         return str(result.id)\n675:     except Exception:\n676:         logger.exception(\"evolve: failed to persist rule\")\n677:         return None\n678: \n679: \n680: # -- Public API ---------------------------------------------------------------\n681: \n682: \n683: async def report_outcome(\n684:     db: AsyncSession,\n685:     tenant_id: str,\n686:     outcome: str,\n687:     outcome_type: str,\n688:     related_ids: list[str] | None = None,\n689:     scope: str = \"agent\",\n690:     agent_id: str = \"mcp-agent\",\n691:     fleet_id: str | None = None,\n692: ) -> dict:\n693:     \"\"\"Record an outcome, adjust related memory weights, and optionally generate rules.\n694: \n695:     Parameters\n696:     ----------\n697:     db : AsyncSession\n698:     tenant_id : str\n699:     outcome : str\n700:         Natural language description of what happened.\n701:     outcome_type : str\n702:         \"success\", \"failure\", or \"partial\".\n703:     related_ids : list[str] | None\n704:         Memory UUIDs that influenced the agent's action. Optional.\n705:     scope : str\n706:         \"agent\" (default, touches only caller-owned memories), \"fleet\"\n707:         (touches memories in ``fleet_id``), or \"all\" (tenant-wide).\n708:         Out-of-scope IDs are dropped silently with a warning log.\n709:     agent_id : str\n710:     fleet_id : str | None\n711:         Required when ``scope='fleet'``.\n712: \n713:     Returns\n714:     -------\n715:     dict with outcome_id, outcome_type, scope, weight_adjustments,\n716:     rules_generated, rule_skipped_reason, weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n717:     out_of_scope_count, evolve_ms.\n718:     \"\"\"\n719:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n720: \n\n(Showing lines 361-720 of 1007. Use offset=721 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"    # adjustment batch from the outer evolve transaction; per-row\n    # isolation is not preserved — a DB error aborts all weight updates\n    # as a unit. The outer evolve transaction still gets to persist the\n    # outcome / rule memory rows downstream regardless.\n    try:\n        async with db.begin_nested():\n            result = await db.execute(\n                _ADJUST_WEIGHTS_BULK_SQL,\n                {\n                    \"mids\": valid_uuids,\n                    \"tid\": tenant_id,\n                    \"floor\": EVOLVE_WEIGHT_FLOOR,\n                    \"cap\": EVOLVE_WEIGHT_CAP,\n                    \"delta\": delta,\n                },\n            )\n            rows = result.fetchall()\n    except Exception:\n        logger.warning(\"evolve: bulk weight update failed for %d memories\", len(valid_uuids), exc_info=True)\n        return \"no_rows_updated\", [], []","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","text":"    # adjustment batch from the outer evolve transaction; per-row\n    # isolation is not preserved — a DB error aborts all weight updates\n    # as a unit. The outer evolve transaction still gets to persist the\n    # outcome / rule memory rows downstream regardless.\n    try:\n        async with db.begin_nested():\n            result = await db.execute(\n                _ADJUST_WEIGHTS_BULK_SQL,\n                {\n                    \"mids\": valid_uuids,\n                    \"tid\": tenant_id,\n                    \"floor\": EVOLVE_WEIGHT_FLOOR,\n                    \"cap\": EVOLVE_WEIGHT_CAP,\n                    \"delta\": delta,\n                },\n            )\n            rows = result.fetchall()\n    except Exception:\n        logger.warning(\"evolve: bulk weight update failed for %d memories\", len(valid_uuids), exc_info=True)\n        return \"no_rows_updated\", [], []\n\n    # Map returned rows by id so we can preserve the caller's input\n    # ordering when building the response. Rows missing from the\n    # result set correspond to ids not found (or filtered by the\n    # tenant + deleted_at predicate); skip them with the same\n    # warning the per-row path emitted previously.\n    #\n    # ``UUID(str(row.id))`` normalises the key — some DB drivers /\n    # cursor result shapes hand ``row.id`` back as ``str`` rather than\n    # ``uuid.UUID``. Without normalisation the lookup below\n    # (``row_by_id.get(mid)`` with a real ``UUID`` key) silently\n    # misses every row, falling through to the \"not found\" warning\n    # branch and dropping the whole batch from the response.\n    row_by_id = {UUID(str(row.id)): row for row in rows}\n    for mid_str, mid in parsed:\n        row = row_by_id.get(mid)\n        if row is None:\n            logger.warning(\"evolve: memory %s not found for tenant %s, skipping\", mid, tenant_id)\n            continue\n        successfully_adjusted.append(mid_str)\n        adjustments.append(\n            {\n                \"memory_id\": mid_str,\n                \"old_weight\": round(float(row.old_weight), 4),\n                \"new_weight\": round(float(row.new_weight), 4),\n                \"delta\": round(delta, 4),\n            }\n        )\n\n    # Race / no-match path: parse + UPDATE succeeded but no rows came back\n    # (a row was deleted between _filter_by_scope and the UPDATE, or every\n    # id failed the tenant+deleted_at predicate). Surface as a slug so the\n    # caller can distinguish from a success.\n    skip_reason = \"no_rows_updated\" if not successfully_adjusted else None\n    return skip_reason, successfully_adjusted, adjustments\n\n\n# -- Rule generation ----------------------------------------------------------\n\n\ndef _fake_rule() -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Placeholder rule for fake/test LLM provider.\"\"\"\n    return {\n        \"condition\": \"When encountering a similar situation\",\n        \"action\": \"Verify information against the most recent source before acting\",\n        \"confidence\": 0.6,\n        \"reasoning\": \"Fake rule generated for testing.\",\n    }\n\n\nasync def _generate_rule(\n    tenant_id: str,\n    outcome: str,\n    outcome_type: str,\n    related_ids: list[str],\n    config,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n) -> tuple[str | None, dict | None]:\n    \"\"\"Ask LLM to generate a preventive rule from a failure/partial outcome.\n\n    Returns ``(skip_reason, rule)``:\n      - ``(None, {...})`` on success\n      - ``(<RULE_SKIP_REASONS slug>, None)`` on any silent-exit path\n\n    A10 widened the return from ``dict | None`` to the tuple so callers\n    (``report_outcome``) can propagate the specific reason out to the\n    response + structured log instead of conflating \"no candidates\",\n    \"LLM blew up\", and \"fetched zero memories\" into a single None.\n\n    Audit P3 (evolve): ``db`` was removed from this signature. The\n    function only used it to resolve tenant config; callers now do\n    that themselves and pass ``config`` in. This lets the MCP tool\n    (``memclaw_evolve``) close its DB session before invoking the\n    LLM round-trip — which can take multiple seconds and would\n    otherwise pin a pooled connection.\n\n    ``agent_id`` and ``fleet_id`` are reserved arguments; the body\n    does not use them today but they're preserved so future\n    rule-generation strategies (per-agent prompts, fleet-scoped\n    examples) can light up without a signature break.\n    \"\"\"\n    from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n    from core_api.providers._retry import call_with_fallback\n\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n\n    # Fetch related memories for context (cap at 10 for prompt size).\n    # Parallelize HTTP fetches so latency is O(1) instead of O(n) round trips.\n    # Sanitize title/content before putting them into the LLM prompt — they\n    # originate from agent writes and can contain injection attempts.\n    async def _fetch(mid_str: str) -> tuple[str, dict | None]:\n        try:\n            return mid_str, await sc.get_memory_for_tenant(tenant_id, mid_str)\n        except Exception:\n            logger.warning(\"evolve: fetch failed for memory %s\", mid_str, exc_info=True)\n            return mid_str, None\n\n    # Dedup before slicing so the prompt doesn't repeat the same memory\n    # if the caller passed duplicate UUIDs.\n    unique_ids = list(dict.fromkeys(related_ids))[:10]\n    fetched = await asyncio.gather(*[_fetch(m) for m in unique_ids])\n    memories_text_lines = []\n    for mid_str, mem in fetched:\n        if not mem:\n            continue\n        title = _sanitize_content(mem.get(\"title\") or \"\", max_len=120)\n        content = _sanitize_content(mem.get(\"content\") or \"\", max_len=500)\n        weight = mem.get(\"weight\", 0.5)\n        mtype = mem.get(\"memory_type\", \"fact\")\n        memories_text_lines.append(f\"- (id:{mid_str}) [{mtype}] {title}: {content} [weight: {weight:.2f}]\")\n\n    if not memories_text_lines:\n        return (\"no_memories_fetched\", None)\n\n    memories_text = \"\\n\".join(memories_text_lines)\n    # Escape user-controlled braces before .format() — both outcome (agent input)\n    # and memories_text (DB content/titles) can contain literal {word} that would\n    # otherwise raise KeyError outside the call_with_fallback try/except.\n    # Also cap outcome size to bound prompt tokens.\n    safe_outcome = _sanitize_content(outcome, max_len=2000).replace(\"{\", \"{{\").replace(\"}\", \"}}\")\n    safe_memories = memories_text.replace(\"{\", \"{{\").replace(\"}\", \"}}\")\n    prompt = _RULE_GENERATION_PROMPT.format(\n        outcome=safe_outcome,\n        outcome_type=outcome_type,\n        memories=safe_memories,\n        count=len(memories_text_lines),\n    )\n\n    async def _do_generate(llm) -> dict:\n        return await llm.complete_json(prompt, temperature=EVOLVE_RULE_TEMPERATURE)\n\n    try:\n        raw = await call_with_fallback(\n            primary_provider_name=config.enrichment_provider,\n            call_fn=_do_generate,\n            fake_fn=_fake_rule,\n            tenant_config=config,\n            service_label=\"evolve-rule\",\n            model_override=config.enrichment_model,\n        )\n    except Exception:\n        logger.exception(\"evolve: rule generation failed\")\n        return (\"llm_failed\", None)\n\n    if not isinstance(raw, dict):\n        return (\"llm_failed\", None)\n\n    # LLMs occasionally return confidence as None, a string like \"high\", or\n    # omit it entirely. Coerce defensively to avoid TypeError/ValueError\n    # propagating out of the service.\n    try:\n        confidence = max(0.0, min(1.0, float(raw.get(\"confidence\") or 0.0)))\n    except (TypeError, ValueError):\n        confidence = 0.0\n\n    return (\n        None,\n        {\n            \"condition\": str(raw.get(\"condition\", \"\"))[:500],\n            \"action\": str(raw.get(\"action\", \"\"))[:500],\n            \"confidence\": confidence,\n            \"reasoning\": str(raw.get(\"reasoning\", \"\"))[:500],\n        },\n    )\n\n\n# -- Persist ------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nasync def _persist_outcome(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n    outcome: str,\n    outcome_type: str,\n    related_ids: list[str],\n    weight_adjustments: list[dict],\n    rule_memory_id: str | None,\n    scope: str,\n) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Write the outcome as a memory of type 'outcome'. Returns outcome memory ID.\n\n    `rule_memory_id` is the ID of the rule memory persisted in Phase 4 (or None\n    if no rule met the confidence threshold). Storing the resolved ID — rather\n    than a `rule_generated` boolean — avoids the case where the flag claims a\n    rule exists but no corresponding memory was actually created.\n\n    `scope` determines the outcome memory's visibility via _SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY\n    so scope='agent' outcomes stay private and scope='all' outcomes are visible\n    tenant-wide.\n    \"\"\"\n    from core_api.schemas import MemoryCreate\n    from core_api.services.memory_service import create_memory\n\n    # Failure outcomes get higher weight — more informative for future analysis\n    weight_map = {\"success\": 0.6, \"failure\": 0.7, \"partial\": 0.5}\n\n    # Cap outcome length to bound persisted content size (consistent with\n    # rule fields capped at 500 chars in _generate_rule).\n    content = f\"[Outcome/{outcome_type}] {outcome[:2000]}\"\n\n    data = MemoryCreate(\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,\n        agent_id=agent_id,\n        fleet_id=fleet_id,\n        memory_type=\"outcome\",\n        content=content,\n        weight=weight_map.get(outcome_type, 0.5),\n        metadata={\n            \"outcome_type\": outcome_type,\n            \"related_memory_ids\": related_ids,\n            \"weight_adjustments\": weight_adjustments,\n            \"rule_memory_id\": rule_memory_id,\n            \"scope\": scope,\n        },\n        visibility=_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY.get(scope, \"scope_team\"),\n        write_mode=\"fast\",\n    )\n\n    # Savepoint isolates a DB error inside create_memory so the outer\n    # transaction stays usable. Outcome persistence is mandatory (unlike\n    # the rule), so re-raise after the savepoint rolls back to signal\n    # failure to the caller.\n    try:\n        async with db.begin_nested():\n            result = await create_memory(db, data)\n    except Exception:\n        logger.exception(\"evolve: failed to persist outcome\")\n        raise\n    return str(result.id)\n\n\nasync def _persist_rule(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n    rule: dict,\n    scope: str,\n    outcome_id: str | None = None,\n) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"Write a generated rule as a memory of type 'rule'. Returns rule memory ID.\n\n    `outcome_id` is optional because the rule is now persisted before the\n    outcome memory (so the outcome metadata can record the resolved\n    rule_memory_id). The reverse link from rule → outcome is set to None;\n    callers can backfill if a strict bidirectional link is required.\n\n    `scope` controls the persisted rule's visibility so a rule generated from\n    scope='agent' evolve stays private to the reporting agent, while a\n    scope='all' rule is visible tenant-wide.\n    \"\"\"\n    from core_api.schemas import MemoryCreate\n    from core_api.services.memory_service import create_memory\n\n    condition = rule.get(\"condition\", \"\")\n    action = rule.get(\"action\", \"\")\n    confidence = rule.get(\"confidence\", 0.5)\n    reasoning = rule.get(\"reasoning\", \"\")\n\n    content = f\"RULE: IF {condition} THEN {action}\"\n    if reasoning:\n        content += f\" (Reasoning: {reasoning})\"\n\n    data = MemoryCreate(\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,\n        agent_id=agent_id,\n        fleet_id=fleet_id,\n        memory_type=\"rule\",\n        content=content,\n        weight=confidence,\n        metadata={\n            \"rule_condition\": condition,\n            \"rule_action\": action,\n            \"rule_confidence\": confidence,\n            \"rule_reasoning\": reasoning,\n            \"source_outcome_id\": outcome_id,\n            \"generated_by\": \"evolve\",\n            \"scope\": scope,\n        },\n        visibility=_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY.get(scope, \"scope_team\"),\n        write_mode=\"fast\",\n    )\n\n    # Savepoint isolates the rule write: if create_memory raises after dirtying\n    # the session (e.g. a side-effect DB write fails before the HTTP call), the\n    # outer transaction can still proceed with weight adjustments and the\n    # outcome write without the session being in a failed state.\n    try:\n        async with db.begin_nested():\n            result = await create_memory(db, data)\n        return str(result.id)\n    except Exception:\n        logger.exception(\"evolve: failed to persist rule\")\n        return None\n\n\n# -- Public API ---------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nasync def report_outcome(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    outcome: str,\n    outcome_type: str,\n    related_ids: list[str] | None = None,\n    scope: str = \"agent\",\n    agent_id: str = \"mcp-agent\",\n    fleet_id: str | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Record an outcome, adjust related memory weights, and optionally generate rules.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    db : AsyncSession\n    tenant_id : str\n    outcome : str\n        Natural language description of what happened.\n    outcome_type : str\n        \"success\", \"failure\", or \"partial\".\n    related_ids : list[str] | None\n        Memory UUIDs that influenced the agent's action. Optional.\n    scope : str\n        \"agent\" (default, touches only caller-owned memories), \"fleet\"\n        (touches memories in ``fleet_id``), or \"all\" (tenant-wide).\n        Out-of-scope IDs are dropped silently with a warning log.\n    agent_id : str\n    fleet_id : str | None\n        Required when ``scope='fleet'``.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    dict with outcome_id, outcome_type, scope, weight_adjustments,\n    rules_generated, rule_skipped_reason, weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n    out_of_scope_count, evolve_ms.\n    \"\"\"\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n","lineStart":361,"lineEnd":720,"totalLines":1007,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","time":{"start":1780727714163,"end":1780727714169}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09525aa501060ea5016a23bfa207d48195a67add6058328c45"}},"id":"prt_e9ba4914d001v9oPZdFHOu5XJH","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba46134001IlymZNIpdlKxji"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727714253,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_CoT7FcweiAFp0NUa2WjgyI8S","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/constants.py","offset":1,"limit":140},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/constants.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Enrichment constants — moved from ``core_api.constants`` (CAURA-595).\n2: \n3: The MEMORY_TYPES / MEMORY_STATUSES tuples and ``DEFAULT_MEMORY_TYPE`` /\n4: ``DEFAULT_MEMORY_WEIGHT`` defaults are read by the enrichment service\n5: to validate LLM output. core-api's ``constants.py`` keeps re-exports\n6: for back-compat — adding a new value here should be paired with the\n7: matching pattern + UI updates in core-api.\n8: \"\"\"\n9: \n10: from __future__ import annotations\n11: \n12: from enum import Enum\n13: \n14: \n15: class MemoryType(str, Enum):\n16:     \"\"\"Typed enum for the memory-type vocabulary.\n17: \n18:     Inheriting from ``str`` keeps full backward compatibility with the\n19:     string-based call sites: ``MemoryType.FACT == \"fact\"`` is True,\n20:     dict lookup with the enum hashes the same as the literal, JSON\n21:     serialisation emits the bare string, and SQLAlchemy reads of a\n22:     ``Text`` column coerce cleanly via Pydantic.\n23:     \"\"\"\n24: \n25:     FACT = \"fact\"\n26:     EPISODE = \"episode\"\n27:     DECISION = \"decision\"\n28:     PREFERENCE = \"preference\"\n29:     TASK = \"task\"\n30:     SEMANTIC = \"semantic\"\n31:     INTENTION = \"intention\"\n32:     PLAN = \"plan\"\n33:     COMMITMENT = \"commitment\"\n34:     ACTION = \"action\"\n35:     OUTCOME = \"outcome\"\n36:     CANCELLATION = \"cancellation\"\n37:     RULE = \"rule\"\n38:     INSIGHT = \"insight\"\n39: \n40: \n41: # LLM-facing description for each ``MemoryType``. Kept str-keyed so a\n42: # direct lookup with either a literal string (\"fact\") or the enum member\n43: # (``MemoryType.FACT``, which IS a string) both succeed. Enrichment\n44: # prompt rendering and DX surfaces (OpenAPI descriptions, console\n45: # tooltips) read from here.\n46: MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS: dict[str, str] = {\n47:     \"fact\": \"durable knowledge, statements of truth, technical details\",\n48:     \"episode\": \"events that happened, deployments, meetings, incidents\",\n49:     \"decision\": (\n50:         \"choices made with reasoning, architecture decisions, approvals. \"\n51:         'Look for: \"decided to\", \"chose\", \"going with\", \"agreed to\", '\n52:         '\"approved\", \"selected\", \"opted for\", \"settled on\"'\n53:     ),\n54:     \"preference\": \"user/org preferences, likes, dislikes, style choices\",\n55:     \"task\": \"work items, assignments, things to do\",\n56:     \"semantic\": \"conceptual/definitional knowledge, taxonomy entries\",\n57:     \"intention\": \"stated goals or aims not yet acted on\",\n58:     \"plan\": \"structured sequences of steps to achieve a goal\",\n59:     \"commitment\": (\n60:         \"promises or obligations made to others. \"\n61:         'Look for: \"committed to\", \"promised\", \"guaranteed\", '\n62:         '\"agreed to deliver\", \"pledged\"'\n63:     ),\n64:     \"action\": (\n65:         \"concrete step the actor (first-person / agent itself) took or is taking. \"\n66:         'Past-tense first-person framing: \"I deployed\", \"filed\", \"merged\", '\n67:         '\"sent\". Distinct from \"episode\" (an observed event tied to time, '\n68:         \"regardless of who performed it).\"\n69:     ),\n70:     \"outcome\": (\n71:         \"results of actions, tasks, or plans. Server-generated by \"\n72:         \"memclaw_evolve when an agent reports an outcome — agents should \"\n73:         \"NOT set memory_type='outcome' explicitly; use the evolve tool or \"\n74:         \"leave the type to auto-classification.\"\n75:     ),\n76:     \"cancellation\": \"explicit record that something was cancelled or abandoned\",\n77:     \"rule\": (\n78:         \"prescriptive directive, policy, or constraint. \"\n79:         'Look for: \"always\", \"never\", \"must\", \"do not\", \"whenever\", '\n80:         '\"policy\", \"guideline\". Server-generated by memclaw_evolve when a '\n81:         \"failure outcome yields a synthesised rule — agents should NOT \"\n82:         \"set memory_type='rule' explicitly; author rules via \"\n83:         \"memclaw_keystones_set, or leave the type to auto-classification.\"\n84:     ),\n85:     \"insight\": (\n86:         \"novel finding, learned lesson, or pattern observed across \"\n87:         \"memories. Server-generated by memclaw_insights — agents should \"\n88:         \"NOT set memory_type='insight' explicitly; persist reflections \"\n89:         \"as type 'semantic' (definitional/conceptual) or 'fact' \"\n90:         \"(durable knowledge) instead, and let memclaw_insights \"\n91:         \"crystallise patterns over your corpus.\"\n92:     ),\n93: }\n94: \n95: MEMORY_TYPES = tuple(t.value for t in MemoryType)\n96: \n97: # C3/C8 — Memory types the SERVER generates internally and that agents\n98: # MUST NOT supply explicitly on the write boundary. ``outcome`` and\n99: # ``rule`` come out of evolve_service; ``insight`` comes out of\n100: # insights_service. Each is still a valid value at the storage layer\n101: # (the schema enum is unchanged) — only the route + MCP boundaries\n102: # reject explicit agent-supplied values.\n103: #\n104: # CAURA-699 — the LLM auto-classifier must NOT mint these from agent\n105: # content either: the enrichment prompt omits them from the offered\n106: # vocabulary (see ``common.enrichment._prompts``) and ``_validate_enrichment``\n107: # demotes any reserved type that slips through to ``DEFAULT_MEMORY_TYPE``.\n108: # The reserved types only ever reach storage via the internal flows above,\n109: # which set ``memory_type`` explicitly and bypass the classifier path.\n110: SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES: frozenset[str] = frozenset({\"outcome\", \"rule\", \"insight\"})\n111: \n112: # Import-time guard: enum and description dict must agree, otherwise\n113: # the prompt renderer will silently emit a bullet without a heading or\n114: # a heading without a description. Catching here gives a loud import\n115: # error rather than mysterious LLM behaviour.\n116: assert set(MEMORY_TYPES) == set(MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS.keys()), (\n117:     \"MemoryType enum and MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS keys are out of sync: \"\n118:     f\"enum-only={set(MEMORY_TYPES) - set(MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS)}, \"\n119:     f\"dict-only={set(MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS) - set(MEMORY_TYPES)}\"\n120: )\n121: \n122: # C3/C8 — every reserved type must exist in the enum / description set;\n123: # otherwise the boundary check below is referencing a phantom slug.\n124: assert SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES.issubset(set(MEMORY_TYPES)), (\n125:     \"SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES references unknown memory types: \"\n126:     f\"{SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES - set(MEMORY_TYPES)}\"\n127: )\n128: \n129: DEFAULT_MEMORY_TYPE = MemoryType.FACT.value\n130: \n131: # Status vocabulary — the enrichment LLM may downgrade a write to e.g.\n132: # ``cancelled`` or ``conflicted`` based on the prompt's classification\n133: # rules.\n134: MEMORY_STATUSES = (\n135:     \"active\",\n136:     \"pending\",\n137:     \"confirmed\",\n138:     \"cancelled\",\n139:     \"outdated\",\n140:     \"conflicted\",\n\n(Showing lines 1-140 of 148. Use offset=141 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Enrichment constants — moved from ``core_api.constants`` (CAURA-595).\n\nThe MEMORY_TYPES / MEMORY_STATUSES tuples and ``DEFAULT_MEMORY_TYPE`` /\n``DEFAULT_MEMORY_WEIGHT`` defaults are read by the enrichment service\nto validate LLM output. core-api's ``constants.py`` keeps re-exports\nfor back-compat — adding a new value here should be paired with the\nmatching pattern + UI updates in core-api.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom enum import Enum\n\n\nclass MemoryType(str, Enum):\n    \"\"\"Typed enum for the memory-type vocabulary.\n\n    Inheriting from ``str`` keeps full backward compatibility with the\n    string-based call sites: ``MemoryType.FACT == \"fact\"`` is True,\n    dict lookup with the enum hashes the same as the literal, JSON","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/constants.py","text":"\"\"\"Enrichment constants — moved from ``core_api.constants`` (CAURA-595).\n\nThe MEMORY_TYPES / MEMORY_STATUSES tuples and ``DEFAULT_MEMORY_TYPE`` /\n``DEFAULT_MEMORY_WEIGHT`` defaults are read by the enrichment service\nto validate LLM output. core-api's ``constants.py`` keeps re-exports\nfor back-compat — adding a new value here should be paired with the\nmatching pattern + UI updates in core-api.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom enum import Enum\n\n\nclass MemoryType(str, Enum):\n    \"\"\"Typed enum for the memory-type vocabulary.\n\n    Inheriting from ``str`` keeps full backward compatibility with the\n    string-based call sites: ``MemoryType.FACT == \"fact\"`` is True,\n    dict lookup with the enum hashes the same as the literal, JSON\n    serialisation emits the bare string, and SQLAlchemy reads of a\n    ``Text`` column coerce cleanly via Pydantic.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    FACT = \"fact\"\n    EPISODE = \"episode\"\n    DECISION = \"decision\"\n    PREFERENCE = \"preference\"\n    TASK = \"task\"\n    SEMANTIC = \"semantic\"\n    INTENTION = \"intention\"\n    PLAN = \"plan\"\n    COMMITMENT = \"commitment\"\n    ACTION = \"action\"\n    OUTCOME = \"outcome\"\n    CANCELLATION = \"cancellation\"\n    RULE = \"rule\"\n    INSIGHT = \"insight\"\n\n\n# LLM-facing description for each ``MemoryType``. Kept str-keyed so a\n# direct lookup with either a literal string (\"fact\") or the enum member\n# (``MemoryType.FACT``, which IS a string) both succeed. Enrichment\n# prompt rendering and DX surfaces (OpenAPI descriptions, console\n# tooltips) read from here.\nMEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS: dict[str, str] = {\n    \"fact\": \"durable knowledge, statements of truth, technical details\",\n    \"episode\": \"events that happened, deployments, meetings, incidents\",\n    \"decision\": (\n        \"choices made with reasoning, architecture decisions, approvals. \"\n        'Look for: \"decided to\", \"chose\", \"going with\", \"agreed to\", '\n        '\"approved\", \"selected\", \"opted for\", \"settled on\"'\n    ),\n    \"preference\": \"user/org preferences, likes, dislikes, style choices\",\n    \"task\": \"work items, assignments, things to do\",\n    \"semantic\": \"conceptual/definitional knowledge, taxonomy entries\",\n    \"intention\": \"stated goals or aims not yet acted on\",\n    \"plan\": \"structured sequences of steps to achieve a goal\",\n    \"commitment\": (\n        \"promises or obligations made to others. \"\n        'Look for: \"committed to\", \"promised\", \"guaranteed\", '\n        '\"agreed to deliver\", \"pledged\"'\n    ),\n    \"action\": (\n        \"concrete step the actor (first-person / agent itself) took or is taking. \"\n        'Past-tense first-person framing: \"I deployed\", \"filed\", \"merged\", '\n        '\"sent\". Distinct from \"episode\" (an observed event tied to time, '\n        \"regardless of who performed it).\"\n    ),\n    \"outcome\": (\n        \"results of actions, tasks, or plans. Server-generated by \"\n        \"memclaw_evolve when an agent reports an outcome — agents should \"\n        \"NOT set memory_type='outcome' explicitly; use the evolve tool or \"\n        \"leave the type to auto-classification.\"\n    ),\n    \"cancellation\": \"explicit record that something was cancelled or abandoned\",\n    \"rule\": (\n        \"prescriptive directive, policy, or constraint. \"\n        'Look for: \"always\", \"never\", \"must\", \"do not\", \"whenever\", '\n        '\"policy\", \"guideline\". Server-generated by memclaw_evolve when a '\n        \"failure outcome yields a synthesised rule — agents should NOT \"\n        \"set memory_type='rule' explicitly; author rules via \"\n        \"memclaw_keystones_set, or leave the type to auto-classification.\"\n    ),\n    \"insight\": (\n        \"novel finding, learned lesson, or pattern observed across \"\n        \"memories. Server-generated by memclaw_insights — agents should \"\n        \"NOT set memory_type='insight' explicitly; persist reflections \"\n        \"as type 'semantic' (definitional/conceptual) or 'fact' \"\n        \"(durable knowledge) instead, and let memclaw_insights \"\n        \"crystallise patterns over your corpus.\"\n    ),\n}\n\nMEMORY_TYPES = tuple(t.value for t in MemoryType)\n\n# C3/C8 — Memory types the SERVER generates internally and that agents\n# MUST NOT supply explicitly on the write boundary. ``outcome`` and\n# ``rule`` come out of evolve_service; ``insight`` comes out of\n# insights_service. Each is still a valid value at the storage layer\n# (the schema enum is unchanged) — only the route + MCP boundaries\n# reject explicit agent-supplied values.\n#\n# CAURA-699 — the LLM auto-classifier must NOT mint these from agent\n# content either: the enrichment prompt omits them from the offered\n# vocabulary (see ``common.enrichment._prompts``) and ``_validate_enrichment``\n# demotes any reserved type that slips through to ``DEFAULT_MEMORY_TYPE``.\n# The reserved types only ever reach storage via the internal flows above,\n# which set ``memory_type`` explicitly and bypass the classifier path.\nSERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES: frozenset[str] = frozenset({\"outcome\", \"rule\", \"insight\"})\n\n# Import-time guard: enum and description dict must agree, otherwise\n# the prompt renderer will silently emit a bullet without a heading or\n# a heading without a description. Catching here gives a loud import\n# error rather than mysterious LLM behaviour.\nassert set(MEMORY_TYPES) == set(MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS.keys()), (\n    \"MemoryType enum and MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS keys are out of sync: \"\n    f\"enum-only={set(MEMORY_TYPES) - set(MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS)}, \"\n    f\"dict-only={set(MEMORY_TYPE_DESCRIPTIONS) - set(MEMORY_TYPES)}\"\n)\n\n# C3/C8 — every reserved type must exist in the enum / description set;\n# otherwise the boundary check below is referencing a phantom slug.\nassert SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES.issubset(set(MEMORY_TYPES)), (\n    \"SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES references unknown memory types: \"\n    f\"{SERVER_RESERVED_MEMORY_TYPES - set(MEMORY_TYPES)}\"\n)\n\nDEFAULT_MEMORY_TYPE = MemoryType.FACT.value\n\n# Status vocabulary — the enrichment LLM may downgrade a write to e.g.\n# ``cancelled`` or ``conflicted`` based on the prompt's classification\n# rules.\nMEMORY_STATUSES = (\n    \"active\",\n    \"pending\",\n    \"confirmed\",\n    \"cancelled\",\n    \"outdated\",\n    \"conflicted\",","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":140,"totalLines":148,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/common/enrichment/constants.py","time":{"start":1780727714245,"end":1780727714252}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09525aa501060ea5016a23bfa2081481959a97b485bcb0efa7"}},"id":"prt_e9ba491c4001bdlhjFLZiTfkwG","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba46134001IlymZNIpdlKxji"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727714270,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_M08XGiUrWhgFsmtstoQYGptO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","offset":721,"limit":320},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n721:     # Defensive validation — both MCP and REST entry points validate these\n722:     # before calling in, but the service re-checks so any future caller path\n723:     # (direct invocation, tests, new routes) can't bypass the contract. All\n724:     # raises use ValueError so the service layer stays decoupled from\n725:     # FastAPI; callers translate to the appropriate HTTP status.\n726:     if outcome_type not in EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES:\n727:         raise ValueError(\n728:             f\"Invalid outcome_type '{outcome_type}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES)}\"\n729:         )\n730:     if not outcome or not outcome.strip():\n731:         raise ValueError(\"outcome must be a non-empty description.\")\n732:     if scope not in VALID_SCOPES:\n733:         raise ValueError(f\"Invalid scope '{scope}'. Must be: {', '.join(VALID_SCOPES)}.\")\n734:     if scope == \"fleet\" and not fleet_id:\n735:         raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n736: \n737:     from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n738: \n739:     # Phase 0: Filter related_ids by scope. Runs before rule generation so the\n740:     # LLM prompt never sees memory content the caller shouldn't access (e.g.,\n741:     # a scope='agent' caller passing another agent's memory IDs). Dropped IDs\n742:     # are tallied into out_of_scope_count for observability.\n743:     #\n744:     # A15: alongside the count, classify why no weights will move when the\n745:     # filter returns an empty set. The slug is the first thing populated;\n746:     # downstream paths (``_adjust_weights`` race / DB-failure) may override\n747:     # it. Mirrors the A10 rule_skipped_reason flow: pre-compute upstream,\n748:     # let the deeper stage override on a more-specific failure.\n749:     out_of_scope_count = 0\n750:     weight_adjustment_skipped_reason: str | None = None\n751:     if not related_ids:\n752:         weight_adjustment_skipped_reason = \"no_related_ids\"\n753:     else:\n754:         original_count = len(related_ids)\n755:         related_ids, out_of_scope_count = await _filter_by_scope(\n756:             db,\n757:             tenant_id=tenant_id,\n758:             caller_agent_id=agent_id,\n759:             fleet_id=fleet_id,\n760:             scope=scope,\n761:             related_ids=related_ids,\n762:         )\n763:         if not related_ids and out_of_scope_count >= original_count:\n764:             # Filter dropped everything. Map scope → slug.\n765:             weight_adjustment_skipped_reason = {\n766:                 \"agent\": \"agent_id_mismatch\",\n767:                 \"fleet\": \"fleet_id_mismatch\",\n768:                 \"all\": \"all_out_of_scope\",\n769:             }.get(scope, \"all_out_of_scope\")\n770:             _log_weight_adjustment_skip(\n771:                 weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n772:                 tenant_id,\n773:                 scope,\n774:                 out_of_scope_count=out_of_scope_count,\n775:                 caller_agent_id=agent_id,\n776:                 fleet_id=fleet_id,\n777:             )\n778: \n779:     # Resolve tenant config up front so ``_maybe_generate_rule`` can be\n780:     # called without any DB dependency. Both REST (here) and MCP\n781:     # (``memclaw_evolve``) feed config in the same way.\n782:     config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n783: \n784:     # Phase 1: Generate rule BEFORE touching weights. The MCP tool\n785:     # closes its DB session between this phase and ``_apply_outcome_to_db``\n786:     # so the LLM round-trip (which can take several seconds) doesn't\n787:     # pin a pooled connection. REST callers run the whole chain in one\n788:     # session — same total latency, just no pool relief.\n789:     rule_result, rule_skipped_reason = await _maybe_generate_rule(\n790:         tenant_id,\n791:         outcome,\n792:         outcome_type,\n793:         related_ids,\n794:         config,\n795:         agent_id,\n796:         fleet_id,\n797:     )\n798: \n799:     return await _apply_outcome_to_db(\n800:         db,\n801:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n802:         agent_id=agent_id,\n803:         fleet_id=fleet_id,\n804:         outcome=outcome,\n805:         outcome_type=outcome_type,\n806:         related_ids=related_ids,\n807:         rule_result=rule_result,\n808:         rule_skipped_reason=rule_skipped_reason,\n809:         scope=scope,\n810:         out_of_scope_count=out_of_scope_count,\n811:         weight_adjustment_skipped_reason=weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n812:         t0=t0,\n813:     )\n814: \n815: \n816: async def _maybe_generate_rule(\n817:     tenant_id: str,\n818:     outcome: str,\n819:     outcome_type: str,\n820:     related_ids: list[str],\n821:     config,\n822:     agent_id: str,\n823:     fleet_id: str | None,\n824: ) -> tuple[dict | None, str | None]:\n825:     \"\"\"Decide whether to invoke ``_generate_rule`` and return ``(rule, skip_reason)``.\n826: \n827:     Pure compute + LLM call, NO DB access. Callers resolve tenant config\n828:     first and pass it in. Lets the MCP tool fire this between two\n829:     independent DB sessions so the multi-second LLM round-trip doesn't\n830:     pin a pooled connection (audit P3).\n831: \n832:     Returns:\n833:       - ``(rule_dict, None)`` on a successful generation.\n834:       - ``(None, slug)`` for any silent-exit path; ``slug`` names the\n835:         reason (one of ``RULE_SKIP_REASONS``).\n836:     \"\"\"\n837:     if outcome_type not in (\"failure\", \"partial\"):\n838:         reason = \"not_failure_or_partial\"\n839:         _log_rule_skip(reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n840:         return None, reason\n841:     if not related_ids:\n842:         reason = \"no_related_ids\"\n843:         _log_rule_skip(reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n844:         return None, reason\n845:     gen_reason, rule_result = await _generate_rule(\n846:         tenant_id,\n847:         outcome,\n848:         outcome_type,\n849:         related_ids,\n850:         config,\n851:         agent_id,\n852:         fleet_id,\n853:     )\n854:     if gen_reason is not None:\n855:         _log_rule_skip(gen_reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n856:         return None, gen_reason\n857:     return rule_result, None\n858: \n859: \n860: async def _apply_outcome_to_db(\n861:     db: AsyncSession,\n862:     *,\n863:     tenant_id: str,\n864:     agent_id: str,\n865:     fleet_id: str | None,\n866:     outcome: str,\n867:     outcome_type: str,\n868:     related_ids: list[str],\n869:     rule_result: dict | None,\n870:     rule_skipped_reason: str | None,\n871:     scope: str,\n872:     out_of_scope_count: int,\n873:     weight_adjustment_skipped_reason: str | None,\n874:     t0: float,\n875: ) -> dict:\n876:     \"\"\"Phases 2-5 + commit: the entire DB-bound write side of evolve.\n877: \n878:     Audit P3 (evolve): split out of ``report_outcome`` so the MCP tool\n879:     can call it from a fresh DB session, opened AFTER the LLM rule\n880:     generation. Atomicity contract is preserved — every local write\n881:     (weight UPDATEs, backfill UPDATE) commits in this one session;\n882:     the storage-api writes (rule + outcome memories) commit eagerly\n883:     via HTTP and are not rolled back if the local commit fails, same\n884:     as before.\n885:     \"\"\"\n886:     # Phase 2: Adjust weights atomically. Row locks are acquired and released\n887:     # entirely within this block — no long-running work runs while locks are held.\n888:     processed_ids: list[str] = []\n889:     weight_adjustments: list[dict] = []\n890:     if related_ids:\n891:         adjust_skip_reason, processed_ids, weight_adjustments = await _adjust_weights(\n892:             db, tenant_id, related_ids, outcome_type, agent_id\n893:         )\n894:         # A15: the deeper stage's slug wins. The upstream slug from\n895:         # ``report_outcome`` only fires when the scope filter dropped\n896:         # every id; if we got here, the filter passed at least one\n897:         # but the bulk UPDATE didn't update any (race / parse error).\n898:         if adjust_skip_reason is not None:\n899:             weight_adjustment_skipped_reason = adjust_skip_reason\n900:             _log_weight_adjustment_skip(\n901:                 adjust_skip_reason, tenant_id, scope, related_ids_count=len(related_ids)\n902:             )\n903: \n904:     # Phase 3: Persist rule memory if confidence meets threshold. outcome_id\n905:     # is not known yet; it is backfilled in Phase 5 after the outcome exists.\n906:     rule_memory_id: str | None = None\n907:     if rule_result is not None:\n908:         confidence = rule_result.get(\"confidence\", 0)\n909:         if confidence < EVOLVE_RULE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD:\n910:             rule_skipped_reason = \"below_confidence_threshold\"\n911:             _log_rule_skip(\n912:                 rule_skipped_reason,\n913:                 tenant_id,\n914:                 outcome_type,\n915:                 confidence=confidence,\n916:                 threshold=EVOLVE_RULE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD,\n917:             )\n918:         else:\n919:             rule_memory_id = await _persist_rule(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id, rule_result, scope=scope)\n920:             if rule_memory_id is None:\n921:                 rule_skipped_reason = \"persist_failed\"\n922:                 _log_rule_skip(rule_skipped_reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n923: \n924:     # Phase 4: Persist outcome memory — records rule_memory_id and the IDs\n925:     # that actually got their weights updated.\n926:     outcome_id = await _persist_outcome(\n927:         db,\n928:         tenant_id,\n929:         agent_id,\n930:         fleet_id,\n931:         outcome,\n932:         outcome_type,\n933:         processed_ids,\n934:         weight_adjustments,\n935:         rule_memory_id,\n936:         scope=scope,\n937:     )\n938: \n939:     # Phase 5: Backfill the rule's source_outcome_id so rules are queryable\n940:     # back to their originating outcome without scanning every outcome's\n941:     # related_memory_ids list. Best-effort — a failure here doesn't abort\n942:     # the whole call since the outcome already references the rule.\n943:     if rule_memory_id and outcome_id:\n944:         # Savepoint isolates the backfill: a failure here (e.g. snapshot\n945:         # visibility race when the rule was committed on a separate connection)\n946:         # would otherwise abort the outer transaction and surface as a\n947:         # `RELEASE SAVEPOINT` error on the final db.commit().\n948:         try:\n949:             async with db.begin_nested():\n950:                 await db.execute(\n951:                     _BACKFILL_RULE_OUTCOME_SQL,\n952:                     {\n953:                         \"rule_id\": UUID(rule_memory_id),\n954:                         \"outcome_id\": outcome_id,\n955:                         \"tid\": tenant_id,\n956:                     },\n957:                 )\n958:         except Exception:\n959:             logger.exception(\"evolve: failed to backfill source_outcome_id on rule %s\", rule_memory_id)\n960: \n961:     # Commit local DB-session writes (weight UPDATEs + the rule→outcome\n962:     # backfill UPDATE). Split-commit contract: rule/outcome memories were\n963:     # already persisted independently by storage-api over HTTP and are NOT\n964:     # rolled back if this commit fails. On commit failure the outcome and\n965:     # rule remain in storage but weight adjustments are lost and the rule\n966:     # lacks source_outcome_id — log loudly so operators can reconcile.\n967:     try:\n968:         await db.commit()\n969:     except Exception:\n970:         logger.error(\n971:             \"evolve: db.commit() failed after storage-api writes succeeded; \"\n972:             \"rule_memory_id=%s outcome_id=%s — weights and rule→outcome backfill \"\n973:             \"are lost but the memories remain in storage\",\n974:             rule_memory_id,\n975:             outcome_id,\n976:             exc_info=True,\n977:         )\n978:         raise\n979: \n980:     return {\n981:         \"outcome_id\": outcome_id,\n982:         \"outcome_type\": outcome_type,\n983:         \"scope\": scope,\n984:         \"weight_adjustments\": weight_adjustments,\n985:         \"rules_generated\": [\n986:             {\n987:                 \"rule_memory_id\": rule_memory_id,\n988:                 \"condition\": rule_result[\"condition\"],\n989:                 \"action\": rule_result[\"action\"],\n990:                 \"confidence\": rule_result[\"confidence\"],\n991:             }\n992:         ]\n993:         if rule_memory_id and rule_result\n994:         else [],\n995:         # A10 — see ``RULE_SKIP_REASONS`` for the slug taxonomy. None\n996:         # means a rule was generated; a slug names the silent-exit\n997:         # path that fired. Mirrors the always-fire log line emitted\n998:         # alongside.\n999:         \"rule_skipped_reason\": rule_skipped_reason,\n1000:         # A15 — see ``WEIGHT_ADJUSTMENT_SKIP_REASONS``. None when at\n1001:         # least one weight moved; a slug otherwise. Distinguishes the\n1002:         # silent-noop shape A15 reported (200 OK + ``weight_adjustments=[]``\n1003:         # masquerading as success) into a contract callers can inspect.\n1004:         \"weight_adjustment_skipped_reason\": weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n1005:         \"out_of_scope_count\": out_of_scope_count,\n1006:         \"evolve_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n1007:     }\n\n(End of file - total 1007 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"    # Defensive validation — both MCP and REST entry points validate these\n    # before calling in, but the service re-checks so any future caller path\n    # (direct invocation, tests, new routes) can't bypass the contract. All\n    # raises use ValueError so the service layer stays decoupled from\n    # FastAPI; callers translate to the appropriate HTTP status.\n    if outcome_type not in EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES:\n        raise ValueError(\n            f\"Invalid outcome_type '{outcome_type}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES)}\"\n        )\n    if not outcome or not outcome.strip():\n        raise ValueError(\"outcome must be a non-empty description.\")\n    if scope not in VALID_SCOPES:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Invalid scope '{scope}'. Must be: {', '.join(VALID_SCOPES)}.\")\n    if scope == \"fleet\" and not fleet_id:\n        raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n\n    from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n\n    # Phase 0: Filter related_ids by scope. Runs before rule generation so the\n    # LLM prompt never sees memory content the caller shouldn't access (e.g.,","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","text":"    # Defensive validation — both MCP and REST entry points validate these\n    # before calling in, but the service re-checks so any future caller path\n    # (direct invocation, tests, new routes) can't bypass the contract. All\n    # raises use ValueError so the service layer stays decoupled from\n    # FastAPI; callers translate to the appropriate HTTP status.\n    if outcome_type not in EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES:\n        raise ValueError(\n            f\"Invalid outcome_type '{outcome_type}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(EVOLVE_OUTCOME_TYPES)}\"\n        )\n    if not outcome or not outcome.strip():\n        raise ValueError(\"outcome must be a non-empty description.\")\n    if scope not in VALID_SCOPES:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Invalid scope '{scope}'. Must be: {', '.join(VALID_SCOPES)}.\")\n    if scope == \"fleet\" and not fleet_id:\n        raise ValueError(\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\")\n\n    from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n\n    # Phase 0: Filter related_ids by scope. Runs before rule generation so the\n    # LLM prompt never sees memory content the caller shouldn't access (e.g.,\n    # a scope='agent' caller passing another agent's memory IDs). Dropped IDs\n    # are tallied into out_of_scope_count for observability.\n    #\n    # A15: alongside the count, classify why no weights will move when the\n    # filter returns an empty set. The slug is the first thing populated;\n    # downstream paths (``_adjust_weights`` race / DB-failure) may override\n    # it. Mirrors the A10 rule_skipped_reason flow: pre-compute upstream,\n    # let the deeper stage override on a more-specific failure.\n    out_of_scope_count = 0\n    weight_adjustment_skipped_reason: str | None = None\n    if not related_ids:\n        weight_adjustment_skipped_reason = \"no_related_ids\"\n    else:\n        original_count = len(related_ids)\n        related_ids, out_of_scope_count = await _filter_by_scope(\n            db,\n            tenant_id=tenant_id,\n            caller_agent_id=agent_id,\n            fleet_id=fleet_id,\n            scope=scope,\n            related_ids=related_ids,\n        )\n        if not related_ids and out_of_scope_count >= original_count:\n            # Filter dropped everything. Map scope → slug.\n            weight_adjustment_skipped_reason = {\n                \"agent\": \"agent_id_mismatch\",\n                \"fleet\": \"fleet_id_mismatch\",\n                \"all\": \"all_out_of_scope\",\n            }.get(scope, \"all_out_of_scope\")\n            _log_weight_adjustment_skip(\n                weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n                tenant_id,\n                scope,\n                out_of_scope_count=out_of_scope_count,\n                caller_agent_id=agent_id,\n                fleet_id=fleet_id,\n            )\n\n    # Resolve tenant config up front so ``_maybe_generate_rule`` can be\n    # called without any DB dependency. Both REST (here) and MCP\n    # (``memclaw_evolve``) feed config in the same way.\n    config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n\n    # Phase 1: Generate rule BEFORE touching weights. The MCP tool\n    # closes its DB session between this phase and ``_apply_outcome_to_db``\n    # so the LLM round-trip (which can take several seconds) doesn't\n    # pin a pooled connection. REST callers run the whole chain in one\n    # session — same total latency, just no pool relief.\n    rule_result, rule_skipped_reason = await _maybe_generate_rule(\n        tenant_id,\n        outcome,\n        outcome_type,\n        related_ids,\n        config,\n        agent_id,\n        fleet_id,\n    )\n\n    return await _apply_outcome_to_db(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,\n        agent_id=agent_id,\n        fleet_id=fleet_id,\n        outcome=outcome,\n        outcome_type=outcome_type,\n        related_ids=related_ids,\n        rule_result=rule_result,\n        rule_skipped_reason=rule_skipped_reason,\n        scope=scope,\n        out_of_scope_count=out_of_scope_count,\n        weight_adjustment_skipped_reason=weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n        t0=t0,\n    )\n\n\nasync def _maybe_generate_rule(\n    tenant_id: str,\n    outcome: str,\n    outcome_type: str,\n    related_ids: list[str],\n    config,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n) -> tuple[dict | None, str | None]:\n    \"\"\"Decide whether to invoke ``_generate_rule`` and return ``(rule, skip_reason)``.\n\n    Pure compute + LLM call, NO DB access. Callers resolve tenant config\n    first and pass it in. Lets the MCP tool fire this between two\n    independent DB sessions so the multi-second LLM round-trip doesn't\n    pin a pooled connection (audit P3).\n\n    Returns:\n      - ``(rule_dict, None)`` on a successful generation.\n      - ``(None, slug)`` for any silent-exit path; ``slug`` names the\n        reason (one of ``RULE_SKIP_REASONS``).\n    \"\"\"\n    if outcome_type not in (\"failure\", \"partial\"):\n        reason = \"not_failure_or_partial\"\n        _log_rule_skip(reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n        return None, reason\n    if not related_ids:\n        reason = \"no_related_ids\"\n        _log_rule_skip(reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n        return None, reason\n    gen_reason, rule_result = await _generate_rule(\n        tenant_id,\n        outcome,\n        outcome_type,\n        related_ids,\n        config,\n        agent_id,\n        fleet_id,\n    )\n    if gen_reason is not None:\n        _log_rule_skip(gen_reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n        return None, gen_reason\n    return rule_result, None\n\n\nasync def _apply_outcome_to_db(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    *,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n    outcome: str,\n    outcome_type: str,\n    related_ids: list[str],\n    rule_result: dict | None,\n    rule_skipped_reason: str | None,\n    scope: str,\n    out_of_scope_count: int,\n    weight_adjustment_skipped_reason: str | None,\n    t0: float,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Phases 2-5 + commit: the entire DB-bound write side of evolve.\n\n    Audit P3 (evolve): split out of ``report_outcome`` so the MCP tool\n    can call it from a fresh DB session, opened AFTER the LLM rule\n    generation. Atomicity contract is preserved — every local write\n    (weight UPDATEs, backfill UPDATE) commits in this one session;\n    the storage-api writes (rule + outcome memories) commit eagerly\n    via HTTP and are not rolled back if the local commit fails, same\n    as before.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Phase 2: Adjust weights atomically. Row locks are acquired and released\n    # entirely within this block — no long-running work runs while locks are held.\n    processed_ids: list[str] = []\n    weight_adjustments: list[dict] = []\n    if related_ids:\n        adjust_skip_reason, processed_ids, weight_adjustments = await _adjust_weights(\n            db, tenant_id, related_ids, outcome_type, agent_id\n        )\n        # A15: the deeper stage's slug wins. The upstream slug from\n        # ``report_outcome`` only fires when the scope filter dropped\n        # every id; if we got here, the filter passed at least one\n        # but the bulk UPDATE didn't update any (race / parse error).\n        if adjust_skip_reason is not None:\n            weight_adjustment_skipped_reason = adjust_skip_reason\n            _log_weight_adjustment_skip(\n                adjust_skip_reason, tenant_id, scope, related_ids_count=len(related_ids)\n            )\n\n    # Phase 3: Persist rule memory if confidence meets threshold. outcome_id\n    # is not known yet; it is backfilled in Phase 5 after the outcome exists.\n    rule_memory_id: str | None = None\n    if rule_result is not None:\n        confidence = rule_result.get(\"confidence\", 0)\n        if confidence < EVOLVE_RULE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD:\n            rule_skipped_reason = \"below_confidence_threshold\"\n            _log_rule_skip(\n                rule_skipped_reason,\n                tenant_id,\n                outcome_type,\n                confidence=confidence,\n                threshold=EVOLVE_RULE_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD,\n            )\n        else:\n            rule_memory_id = await _persist_rule(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id, rule_result, scope=scope)\n            if rule_memory_id is None:\n                rule_skipped_reason = \"persist_failed\"\n                _log_rule_skip(rule_skipped_reason, tenant_id, outcome_type)\n\n    # Phase 4: Persist outcome memory — records rule_memory_id and the IDs\n    # that actually got their weights updated.\n    outcome_id = await _persist_outcome(\n        db,\n        tenant_id,\n        agent_id,\n        fleet_id,\n        outcome,\n        outcome_type,\n        processed_ids,\n        weight_adjustments,\n        rule_memory_id,\n        scope=scope,\n    )\n\n    # Phase 5: Backfill the rule's source_outcome_id so rules are queryable\n    # back to their originating outcome without scanning every outcome's\n    # related_memory_ids list. Best-effort — a failure here doesn't abort\n    # the whole call since the outcome already references the rule.\n    if rule_memory_id and outcome_id:\n        # Savepoint isolates the backfill: a failure here (e.g. snapshot\n        # visibility race when the rule was committed on a separate connection)\n        # would otherwise abort the outer transaction and surface as a\n        # `RELEASE SAVEPOINT` error on the final db.commit().\n        try:\n            async with db.begin_nested():\n                await db.execute(\n                    _BACKFILL_RULE_OUTCOME_SQL,\n                    {\n                        \"rule_id\": UUID(rule_memory_id),\n                        \"outcome_id\": outcome_id,\n                        \"tid\": tenant_id,\n                    },\n                )\n        except Exception:\n            logger.exception(\"evolve: failed to backfill source_outcome_id on rule %s\", rule_memory_id)\n\n    # Commit local DB-session writes (weight UPDATEs + the rule→outcome\n    # backfill UPDATE). Split-commit contract: rule/outcome memories were\n    # already persisted independently by storage-api over HTTP and are NOT\n    # rolled back if this commit fails. On commit failure the outcome and\n    # rule remain in storage but weight adjustments are lost and the rule\n    # lacks source_outcome_id — log loudly so operators can reconcile.\n    try:\n        await db.commit()\n    except Exception:\n        logger.error(\n            \"evolve: db.commit() failed after storage-api writes succeeded; \"\n            \"rule_memory_id=%s outcome_id=%s — weights and rule→outcome backfill \"\n            \"are lost but the memories remain in storage\",\n            rule_memory_id,\n            outcome_id,\n            exc_info=True,\n        )\n        raise\n\n    return {\n        \"outcome_id\": outcome_id,\n        \"outcome_type\": outcome_type,\n        \"scope\": scope,\n        \"weight_adjustments\": weight_adjustments,\n        \"rules_generated\": [\n            {\n                \"rule_memory_id\": rule_memory_id,\n                \"condition\": rule_result[\"condition\"],\n                \"action\": rule_result[\"action\"],\n                \"confidence\": rule_result[\"confidence\"],\n            }\n        ]\n        if rule_memory_id and rule_result\n        else [],\n        # A10 — see ``RULE_SKIP_REASONS`` for the slug taxonomy. None\n        # means a rule was generated; a slug names the silent-exit\n        # path that fired. Mirrors the always-fire log line emitted\n        # alongside.\n        \"rule_skipped_reason\": rule_skipped_reason,\n        # A15 — see ``WEIGHT_ADJUSTMENT_SKIP_REASONS``. None when at\n        # least one weight moved; a slug otherwise. Distinguishes the\n        # silent-noop shape A15 reported (200 OK + ``weight_adjustments=[]``\n        # masquerading as success) into a contract callers can inspect.\n        \"weight_adjustment_skipped_reason\": weight_adjustment_skipped_reason,\n        \"out_of_scope_count\": out_of_scope_count,\n        \"evolve_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n    }","lineStart":721,"lineEnd":1007,"totalLines":1007,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/evolve_service.py","time":{"start":1780727714238,"end":1780727714258}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09525aa501060ea5016a23bfa207e0819589e9a50919ff8acc"}},"id":"prt_e9ba491740019iKrGNjxXDLBwU","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba46134001IlymZNIpdlKxji"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727714270,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_BntyyJeCghxwOOdsfIEomHJP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","offset":421,"limit":360},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n421:     base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n422: \n423:     # Step 1: entities referenced by multiple agents\n424:     entity_stmt = (\n425:         select(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n426:         .where(\n427:             *base,\n428:             Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n429:             Memory.subject_entity_id.isnot(None),\n430:         )\n431:         .group_by(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n432:         .having(func.count(distinct(Memory.agent_id)) >= 2)\n433:         .limit(10)\n434:     )\n435:     entity_result = await db.execute(entity_stmt)\n436:     entity_ids = [r[0] for r in entity_result.all()]\n437: \n438:     if not entity_ids:\n439:         return []\n440: \n441:     # Step 2: fetch memories for those entities\n442:     mem_stmt = (\n443:         select(Memory)\n444:         .where(\n445:             *base,\n446:             Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n447:             Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n448:             Memory.subject_entity_id.in_(entity_ids),\n449:         )\n450:         .order_by(Memory.subject_entity_id, Memory.agent_id, Memory.created_at.desc())\n451:         .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n452:     )\n453:     result = await db.execute(mem_stmt)\n454:     return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n455: \n456: \n457: async def _query_patterns(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n458:     \"\"\"Fetch recent active memories for trend/pattern analysis.\"\"\"\n459:     base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n460:     stmt = (\n461:         select(Memory)\n462:         .where(\n463:             *base,\n464:             Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n465:             Memory.status == \"active\",\n466:         )\n467:         .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n468:         .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n469:     )\n470:     result = await db.execute(stmt)\n471:     return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n472: \n473: \n474: def _numpy_kmeans(data, k, max_iters=20):\n475:     \"\"\"Simple k-means clustering using only numpy.\"\"\"\n476:     import numpy as np\n477: \n478:     n = data.shape[0]\n479:     # Initialize centroids via random sampling\n480:     rng = np.random.default_rng(42)  # deterministic for reproducibility\n481:     indices = rng.choice(n, size=k, replace=False)\n482:     centroids = data[indices].copy()\n483: \n484:     # Initialize to -1 (sentinel) so the convergence check on the first\n485:     # iteration doesn't false-positive when all points happen to be assigned\n486:     # to cluster 0.\n487:     labels = np.full(n, -1, dtype=np.int32)\n488:     for _ in range(max_iters):\n489:         # Assign each point to nearest centroid (squared-distance, no huge intermediate)\n490:         data_sq = np.sum(data**2, axis=1, keepdims=True)\n491:         cent_sq = np.sum(centroids**2, axis=1)[None, :]\n492:         dists = data_sq + cent_sq - 2.0 * (data @ centroids.T)\n493:         new_labels = np.argmin(dists, axis=1).astype(np.int32)\n494: \n495:         if np.array_equal(labels, new_labels):\n496:             break\n497:         labels = new_labels\n498: \n499:         # Update centroids\n500:         for j in range(k):\n501:             mask = labels == j\n502:             if mask.any():\n503:                 centroids[j] = data[mask].mean(axis=0)\n504:             else:\n505:                 centroids[j] = data[rng.integers(n)]\n506: \n507:     return labels, centroids\n508: \n509: \n510: async def _query_discover(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> _DiscoverResult:\n511:     \"\"\"Sample memories with embeddings and cluster them in vector space.\"\"\"\n512:     base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n513: \n514:     # Sample memories with embeddings\n515:     stmt = (\n516:         select(Memory)\n517:         .where(\n518:             *base,\n519:             Memory.status == \"active\",\n520:             Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n521:             Memory.embedding.isnot(None),\n522:         )\n523:         .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n524:         .limit(INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_SAMPLE_SIZE)\n525:     )\n526:     result = await db.execute(stmt)\n527:     rows = result.scalars().all()\n528: \n529:     if len(rows) < 10:\n530:         # Not enough data for meaningful clustering\n531:         return _DiscoverResult(is_clustered=False, data=_rows_to_dicts(rows))\n532: \n533:     try:\n534:         import numpy as np\n535:     except ImportError:\n536:         logger.warning(\"numpy not available, falling back to patterns mode for discover\")\n537:         return _DiscoverResult(is_clustered=False, data=_rows_to_dicts(rows[:INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES]))\n538: \n539:     # Extract embeddings into numpy array\n540:     embeddings = np.array([r.embedding for r in rows], dtype=np.float32)\n541:     n_clusters = min(INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_CLUSTERS, len(rows) // 5)\n542:     n_clusters = max(2, n_clusters)\n543: \n544:     # Simple numpy k-means (avoids sklearn dependency)\n545:     labels, centroids = _numpy_kmeans(embeddings, n_clusters, max_iters=20)\n546: \n547:     # Build cluster summaries with representative memories\n548:     clusters = []\n549:     for k in range(n_clusters):\n550:         mask = labels == k\n551:         cluster_indices = np.where(mask)[0]\n552:         if len(cluster_indices) == 0:\n553:             continue\n554: \n555:         cluster_embeddings = embeddings[cluster_indices]\n556:         centroid = centroids[k]\n557: \n558:         # Find 3 closest to centroid\n559:         dists = np.linalg.norm(cluster_embeddings - centroid, axis=1)\n560:         closest_idx = np.argsort(dists)[:3]\n561:         representatives = [rows[cluster_indices[i]] for i in closest_idx]\n562: \n563:         # Compute cluster stats\n564:         cluster_rows = [rows[i] for i in cluster_indices]\n565:         weights = [r.weight for r in cluster_rows]\n566:         agents = {r.agent_id for r in cluster_rows}\n567:         types = {}\n568:         for r in cluster_rows:\n569:             types[r.memory_type] = types.get(r.memory_type, 0) + 1\n570: \n571:         clusters.append(\n572:             {\n573:                 \"cluster_id\": k,\n574:                 \"size\": len(cluster_indices),\n575:                 \"weight_mean\": float(np.mean(weights)),\n576:                 \"weight_std\": float(np.std(weights)),\n577:                 \"agent_count\": len(agents),\n578:                 \"agents\": sorted(agents),\n579:                 \"type_distribution\": types,\n580:                 \"representatives\": _rows_to_dicts(representatives),\n581:             }\n582:         )\n583: \n584:     # Return cluster data (will be formatted differently by _format_clusters_for_analysis)\n585:     return _DiscoverResult(is_clustered=True, data=clusters)\n586: \n587: \n588: _QUERY_DISPATCH = {\n589:     \"contradictions\": _query_contradictions,\n590:     \"failures\": _query_failures,\n591:     \"stale\": _query_stale,\n592:     \"divergence\": _query_divergence,\n593:     \"patterns\": _query_patterns,\n594:     \"discover\": _query_discover,\n595: }\n596: \n597: _PROMPT_DISPATCH = {\n598:     \"contradictions\": _PROMPT_CONTRADICTIONS,\n599:     \"failures\": _PROMPT_FAILURES,\n600:     \"stale\": _PROMPT_STALE,\n601:     \"divergence\": _PROMPT_DIVERGENCE,\n602:     \"patterns\": _PROMPT_PATTERNS,\n603:     \"discover\": _PROMPT_DISCOVER,\n604: }\n605: \n606: \n607: # -- Formatting ----------------------------------------------------------------\n608: \n609: \n610: def _format_memories_for_analysis(memories: list[dict]) -> tuple[str, set[str]]:\n611:     \"\"\"Format memory dicts into numbered lines for LLM consumption.\n612: \n613:     Returns (text, shown_ids) so downstream validation of the LLM's\n614:     related_memory_ids stays in sync with what was actually rendered\n615:     into the prompt (even if entries are skipped or truncated here).\n616:     \"\"\"\n617:     lines = []\n618:     shown_ids: set[str] = set()\n619:     for i, m in enumerate(memories, 1):\n620:         meta_parts = []\n621:         if m.get(\"ts_valid_start\"):\n622:             meta_parts.append(f\"[{m['ts_valid_start'][:10]}]\")\n623:         if m.get(\"title\"):\n624:             meta_parts.append(f\"— {_sanitize_content(m['title'], max_len=120)}\")\n625:         if m.get(\"status\") and m[\"status\"] != \"active\":\n626:             meta_parts.append(f\"[status: {m['status']}]\")\n627:         meta_parts.append(f\"[weight: {m.get('weight', 0.5):.2f}]\")\n628:         meta_parts.append(f\"[agent: {_sanitize_content(m.get('agent_id', '?'), max_len=100)}]\")\n629:         if m.get(\"recall_count\", 0) > 0:\n630:             meta_parts.append(f\"[recalls: {m['recall_count']}]\")\n631:         if m.get(\"supersedes_id\"):\n632:             meta_parts.append(f\"[supersedes: {m['supersedes_id']}]\")\n633:         meta = \" \".join(meta_parts)\n634:         content = _sanitize_content(m.get(\"content\", \"\"))\n635:         lines.append(f\"{i}. (id:{m['id']}) [{m.get('memory_type', 'fact')}] {meta}: {content}\")\n636:         if m.get(\"id\"):\n637:             shown_ids.add(str(m[\"id\"]))\n638:     return \"\\n\".join(lines), shown_ids\n639: \n640: \n641: def _format_clusters_for_analysis(clusters: list[dict]) -> tuple[str, set[str]]:\n642:     \"\"\"Format cluster summaries for the discover-mode LLM prompt.\n643: \n644:     Returns (text, shown_ids) — only representative IDs actually rendered\n645:     into the prompt are included, keeping hallucination-filter accurate.\n646:     \"\"\"\n647:     lines = []\n648:     shown_ids: set[str] = set()\n649:     for c in clusters:\n650:         lines.append(f\"--- Cluster {c['cluster_id']} ({c['size']} memories) ---\")\n651:         lines.append(f\"  Weight: mean={c['weight_mean']:.2f}, std={c['weight_std']:.2f}\")\n652:         safe_agents = [_sanitize_content(a, max_len=100) for a in c[\"agents\"]]\n653:         lines.append(f\"  Agents: {', '.join(safe_agents)} ({c['agent_count']} unique)\")\n654:         lines.append(f\"  Types: {c['type_distribution']}\")\n655:         lines.append(\"  Representative memories:\")\n656:         for r in c.get(\"representatives\", []):\n657:             title = _sanitize_content(r.get(\"title\", \"untitled\"), max_len=120)\n658:             content = _sanitize_content(r.get(\"content\", \"\"), max_len=200)\n659:             lines.append(f\"    - (id:{r['id']}) [{r.get('memory_type', 'fact')}] {title}: {content}\")\n660:             if r.get(\"id\"):\n661:                 shown_ids.add(str(r[\"id\"]))\n662:         lines.append(\"\")\n663:     return \"\\n\".join(lines), shown_ids\n664: \n665: \n666: # -- LLM ----------------------------------------------------------------------\n667: \n668: \n669: async def _run_llm_analysis(prompt: str, config) -> dict:\n670:     \"\"\"Send the analysis prompt to the configured LLM provider.\"\"\"\n671:     from core_api.providers._retry import call_with_fallback\n672: \n673:     async def _do_analysis(llm) -> dict:\n674:         return await llm.complete_json(prompt, temperature=INSIGHTS_TEMPERATURE)\n675: \n676:     return await call_with_fallback(\n677:         primary_provider_name=config.enrichment_provider,\n678:         call_fn=_do_analysis,\n679:         fake_fn=lambda: _fake_insights(),\n680:         tenant_config=config,\n681:         service_label=\"insights\",\n682:         model_override=config.enrichment_model,\n683:     )\n684: \n685: \n686: def _fake_insights() -> dict:\n687:     \"\"\"Return placeholder findings for the fake/test provider.\"\"\"\n688:     return {\n689:         \"findings\": [\n690:             {\n691:                 \"type\": \"patterns\",\n692:                 \"title\": \"Fake insight for testing\",\n693:                 \"description\": \"This is a placeholder finding generated by the fake provider.\",\n694:                 \"confidence\": 0.5,\n695:                 \"related_memory_ids\": [],\n696:                 \"recommendation\": \"No action needed (fake provider).\",\n697:             }\n698:         ],\n699:         \"summary\": \"Fake analysis complete.\",\n700:     }\n701: \n702: \n703: # -- Persist -------------------------------------------------------------------\n704: \n705: \n706: async def _persist_findings(\n707:     db: AsyncSession,\n708:     tenant_id: str,\n709:     agent_id: str,\n710:     fleet_id: str | None,\n711:     focus: str,\n712:     scope: str,\n713:     findings: list[dict],\n714: ) -> list[str | None]:\n715:     \"\"\"Create insight-type memories for each finding.\n716: \n717:     Supersedes previous active insights with the same focus+agent by\n718:     transitioning them to 'outdated', preventing duplicate pile-up on re-runs.\n719:     \"\"\"\n720:     # Find existing active insights for this focus to supersede after creation\n721:     from uuid import uuid4\n722: \n723:     from sqlalchemy import select\n724: \n725:     from common.models.memory import Memory\n726:     from core_api.schemas import BulkMemoryCreate, BulkMemoryItem\n727:     from core_api.services.memory_service import create_memories_bulk\n728: \n729:     prior_stmt = (\n730:         select(Memory.id)\n731:         .where(Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id)\n732:         .where(Memory.agent_id == agent_id)\n733:         .where(Memory.memory_type == \"insight\")\n734:         .where(Memory.status == \"active\")\n735:         .where(Memory.deleted_at.is_(None))\n736:         .where(Memory.metadata_[\"insight_focus\"].as_string() == focus)\n737:         .where(Memory.metadata_[\"insight_scope\"].as_string() == scope)\n738:     )\n739:     if fleet_id is not None:\n740:         prior_stmt = prior_stmt.where(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n741:     else:\n742:         prior_stmt = prior_stmt.where(Memory.fleet_id.is_(None))\n743:     prior_rows = (await db.execute(prior_stmt)).scalars().all()\n744:     prior_ids = list(prior_rows)\n745: \n746:     from sqlalchemy import update as sql_update\n747: \n748:     # Transition prior insights for this focus/scope/fleet to \"outdated\" BEFORE\n749:     # creating new ones. This prevents semantic-dedup in create_memory from\n750:     # matching against the prior insight (which has near-identical content\n751:     # template) and failing the new inserts with 409. We skip this step when\n752:     # there are no findings to persist — outdating priors would leave the user\n753:     # with nothing active.\n754:     if findings and prior_ids:\n755:         from sqlalchemy.exc import SQLAlchemyError\n756: \n757:         try:\n758:             async with db.begin_nested():\n759:                 await db.execute(\n760:                     sql_update(Memory)\n761:                     .where(Memory.id.in_(prior_ids))\n762:                     .where(Memory.status == \"active\")\n763:                     .values(status=\"outdated\")\n764:                 )\n765:             logger.info(\n766:                 \"Superseded %d prior %s insights for agent=%s\",\n767:                 len(prior_ids),\n768:                 focus,\n769:                 agent_id,\n770:             )\n771:         except SQLAlchemyError:\n772:             logger.warning(\"Failed to supersede prior insights; skipping persist\", exc_info=True)\n773:             return [None] * len(findings)\n774: \n775:     # Empty-findings short-circuit: ``BulkMemoryCreate.items`` enforces\n776:     # min_length=1, and the prior-supersede block above already returned\n777:     # `[None] * len(findings)` for the failure path. An empty findings\n778:     # list reaches here only when no priors existed either — return\n779:     # straight away without touching the bulk path.\n780:     if not findings:\n\n(Showing lines 421-780 of 1113. Use offset=781 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"    base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n\n    # Step 1: entities referenced by multiple agents\n    entity_stmt = (\n        select(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n            Memory.subject_entity_id.isnot(None),\n        )\n        .group_by(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n        .having(func.count(distinct(Memory.agent_id)) >= 2)\n        .limit(10)\n    )\n    entity_result = await db.execute(entity_stmt)\n    entity_ids = [r[0] for r in entity_result.all()]\n\n    if not entity_ids:\n        return []\n","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","text":"    base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n\n    # Step 1: entities referenced by multiple agents\n    entity_stmt = (\n        select(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n            Memory.subject_entity_id.isnot(None),\n        )\n        .group_by(Memory.subject_entity_id)\n        .having(func.count(distinct(Memory.agent_id)) >= 2)\n        .limit(10)\n    )\n    entity_result = await db.execute(entity_stmt)\n    entity_ids = [r[0] for r in entity_result.all()]\n\n    if not entity_ids:\n        return []\n\n    # Step 2: fetch memories for those entities\n    mem_stmt = (\n        select(Memory)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.status != \"deleted\",\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n            Memory.subject_entity_id.in_(entity_ids),\n        )\n        .order_by(Memory.subject_entity_id, Memory.agent_id, Memory.created_at.desc())\n        .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n    )\n    result = await db.execute(mem_stmt)\n    return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n\n\nasync def _query_patterns(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> list[dict]:\n    \"\"\"Fetch recent active memories for trend/pattern analysis.\"\"\"\n    base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n    stmt = (\n        select(Memory)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n            Memory.status == \"active\",\n        )\n        .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n        .limit(INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES)\n    )\n    result = await db.execute(stmt)\n    return _rows_to_dicts(result.scalars().all())\n\n\ndef _numpy_kmeans(data, k, max_iters=20):\n    \"\"\"Simple k-means clustering using only numpy.\"\"\"\n    import numpy as np\n\n    n = data.shape[0]\n    # Initialize centroids via random sampling\n    rng = np.random.default_rng(42)  # deterministic for reproducibility\n    indices = rng.choice(n, size=k, replace=False)\n    centroids = data[indices].copy()\n\n    # Initialize to -1 (sentinel) so the convergence check on the first\n    # iteration doesn't false-positive when all points happen to be assigned\n    # to cluster 0.\n    labels = np.full(n, -1, dtype=np.int32)\n    for _ in range(max_iters):\n        # Assign each point to nearest centroid (squared-distance, no huge intermediate)\n        data_sq = np.sum(data**2, axis=1, keepdims=True)\n        cent_sq = np.sum(centroids**2, axis=1)[None, :]\n        dists = data_sq + cent_sq - 2.0 * (data @ centroids.T)\n        new_labels = np.argmin(dists, axis=1).astype(np.int32)\n\n        if np.array_equal(labels, new_labels):\n            break\n        labels = new_labels\n\n        # Update centroids\n        for j in range(k):\n            mask = labels == j\n            if mask.any():\n                centroids[j] = data[mask].mean(axis=0)\n            else:\n                centroids[j] = data[rng.integers(n)]\n\n    return labels, centroids\n\n\nasync def _query_discover(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope) -> _DiscoverResult:\n    \"\"\"Sample memories with embeddings and cluster them in vector space.\"\"\"\n    base = _scope_filters(tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n\n    # Sample memories with embeddings\n    stmt = (\n        select(Memory)\n        .where(\n            *base,\n            Memory.status == \"active\",\n            Memory.memory_type != \"insight\",\n            Memory.embedding.isnot(None),\n        )\n        .order_by(Memory.created_at.desc())\n        .limit(INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_SAMPLE_SIZE)\n    )\n    result = await db.execute(stmt)\n    rows = result.scalars().all()\n\n    if len(rows) < 10:\n        # Not enough data for meaningful clustering\n        return _DiscoverResult(is_clustered=False, data=_rows_to_dicts(rows))\n\n    try:\n        import numpy as np\n    except ImportError:\n        logger.warning(\"numpy not available, falling back to patterns mode for discover\")\n        return _DiscoverResult(is_clustered=False, data=_rows_to_dicts(rows[:INSIGHTS_MAX_MEMORIES]))\n\n    # Extract embeddings into numpy array\n    embeddings = np.array([r.embedding for r in rows], dtype=np.float32)\n    n_clusters = min(INSIGHTS_DISCOVER_CLUSTERS, len(rows) // 5)\n    n_clusters = max(2, n_clusters)\n\n    # Simple numpy k-means (avoids sklearn dependency)\n    labels, centroids = _numpy_kmeans(embeddings, n_clusters, max_iters=20)\n\n    # Build cluster summaries with representative memories\n    clusters = []\n    for k in range(n_clusters):\n        mask = labels == k\n        cluster_indices = np.where(mask)[0]\n        if len(cluster_indices) == 0:\n            continue\n\n        cluster_embeddings = embeddings[cluster_indices]\n        centroid = centroids[k]\n\n        # Find 3 closest to centroid\n        dists = np.linalg.norm(cluster_embeddings - centroid, axis=1)\n        closest_idx = np.argsort(dists)[:3]\n        representatives = [rows[cluster_indices[i]] for i in closest_idx]\n\n        # Compute cluster stats\n        cluster_rows = [rows[i] for i in cluster_indices]\n        weights = [r.weight for r in cluster_rows]\n        agents = {r.agent_id for r in cluster_rows}\n        types = {}\n        for r in cluster_rows:\n            types[r.memory_type] = types.get(r.memory_type, 0) + 1\n\n        clusters.append(\n            {\n                \"cluster_id\": k,\n                \"size\": len(cluster_indices),\n                \"weight_mean\": float(np.mean(weights)),\n                \"weight_std\": float(np.std(weights)),\n                \"agent_count\": len(agents),\n                \"agents\": sorted(agents),\n                \"type_distribution\": types,\n                \"representatives\": _rows_to_dicts(representatives),\n            }\n        )\n\n    # Return cluster data (will be formatted differently by _format_clusters_for_analysis)\n    return _DiscoverResult(is_clustered=True, data=clusters)\n\n\n_QUERY_DISPATCH = {\n    \"contradictions\": _query_contradictions,\n    \"failures\": _query_failures,\n    \"stale\": _query_stale,\n    \"divergence\": _query_divergence,\n    \"patterns\": _query_patterns,\n    \"discover\": _query_discover,\n}\n\n_PROMPT_DISPATCH = {\n    \"contradictions\": _PROMPT_CONTRADICTIONS,\n    \"failures\": _PROMPT_FAILURES,\n    \"stale\": _PROMPT_STALE,\n    \"divergence\": _PROMPT_DIVERGENCE,\n    \"patterns\": _PROMPT_PATTERNS,\n    \"discover\": _PROMPT_DISCOVER,\n}\n\n\n# -- Formatting ----------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\ndef _format_memories_for_analysis(memories: list[dict]) -> tuple[str, set[str]]:\n    \"\"\"Format memory dicts into numbered lines for LLM consumption.\n\n    Returns (text, shown_ids) so downstream validation of the LLM's\n    related_memory_ids stays in sync with what was actually rendered\n    into the prompt (even if entries are skipped or truncated here).\n    \"\"\"\n    lines = []\n    shown_ids: set[str] = set()\n    for i, m in enumerate(memories, 1):\n        meta_parts = []\n        if m.get(\"ts_valid_start\"):\n            meta_parts.append(f\"[{m['ts_valid_start'][:10]}]\")\n        if m.get(\"title\"):\n            meta_parts.append(f\"— {_sanitize_content(m['title'], max_len=120)}\")\n        if m.get(\"status\") and m[\"status\"] != \"active\":\n            meta_parts.append(f\"[status: {m['status']}]\")\n        meta_parts.append(f\"[weight: {m.get('weight', 0.5):.2f}]\")\n        meta_parts.append(f\"[agent: {_sanitize_content(m.get('agent_id', '?'), max_len=100)}]\")\n        if m.get(\"recall_count\", 0) > 0:\n            meta_parts.append(f\"[recalls: {m['recall_count']}]\")\n        if m.get(\"supersedes_id\"):\n            meta_parts.append(f\"[supersedes: {m['supersedes_id']}]\")\n        meta = \" \".join(meta_parts)\n        content = _sanitize_content(m.get(\"content\", \"\"))\n        lines.append(f\"{i}. (id:{m['id']}) [{m.get('memory_type', 'fact')}] {meta}: {content}\")\n        if m.get(\"id\"):\n            shown_ids.add(str(m[\"id\"]))\n    return \"\\n\".join(lines), shown_ids\n\n\ndef _format_clusters_for_analysis(clusters: list[dict]) -> tuple[str, set[str]]:\n    \"\"\"Format cluster summaries for the discover-mode LLM prompt.\n\n    Returns (text, shown_ids) — only representative IDs actually rendered\n    into the prompt are included, keeping hallucination-filter accurate.\n    \"\"\"\n    lines = []\n    shown_ids: set[str] = set()\n    for c in clusters:\n        lines.append(f\"--- Cluster {c['cluster_id']} ({c['size']} memories) ---\")\n        lines.append(f\"  Weight: mean={c['weight_mean']:.2f}, std={c['weight_std']:.2f}\")\n        safe_agents = [_sanitize_content(a, max_len=100) for a in c[\"agents\"]]\n        lines.append(f\"  Agents: {', '.join(safe_agents)} ({c['agent_count']} unique)\")\n        lines.append(f\"  Types: {c['type_distribution']}\")\n        lines.append(\"  Representative memories:\")\n        for r in c.get(\"representatives\", []):\n            title = _sanitize_content(r.get(\"title\", \"untitled\"), max_len=120)\n            content = _sanitize_content(r.get(\"content\", \"\"), max_len=200)\n            lines.append(f\"    - (id:{r['id']}) [{r.get('memory_type', 'fact')}] {title}: {content}\")\n            if r.get(\"id\"):\n                shown_ids.add(str(r[\"id\"]))\n        lines.append(\"\")\n    return \"\\n\".join(lines), shown_ids\n\n\n# -- LLM ----------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nasync def _run_llm_analysis(prompt: str, config) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Send the analysis prompt to the configured LLM provider.\"\"\"\n    from core_api.providers._retry import call_with_fallback\n\n    async def _do_analysis(llm) -> dict:\n        return await llm.complete_json(prompt, temperature=INSIGHTS_TEMPERATURE)\n\n    return await call_with_fallback(\n        primary_provider_name=config.enrichment_provider,\n        call_fn=_do_analysis,\n        fake_fn=lambda: _fake_insights(),\n        tenant_config=config,\n        service_label=\"insights\",\n        model_override=config.enrichment_model,\n    )\n\n\ndef _fake_insights() -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Return placeholder findings for the fake/test provider.\"\"\"\n    return {\n        \"findings\": [\n            {\n                \"type\": \"patterns\",\n                \"title\": \"Fake insight for testing\",\n                \"description\": \"This is a placeholder finding generated by the fake provider.\",\n                \"confidence\": 0.5,\n                \"related_memory_ids\": [],\n                \"recommendation\": \"No action needed (fake provider).\",\n            }\n        ],\n        \"summary\": \"Fake analysis complete.\",\n    }\n\n\n# -- Persist -------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nasync def _persist_findings(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n    focus: str,\n    scope: str,\n    findings: list[dict],\n) -> list[str | None]:\n    \"\"\"Create insight-type memories for each finding.\n\n    Supersedes previous active insights with the same focus+agent by\n    transitioning them to 'outdated', preventing duplicate pile-up on re-runs.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Find existing active insights for this focus to supersede after creation\n    from uuid import uuid4\n\n    from sqlalchemy import select\n\n    from common.models.memory import Memory\n    from core_api.schemas import BulkMemoryCreate, BulkMemoryItem\n    from core_api.services.memory_service import create_memories_bulk\n\n    prior_stmt = (\n        select(Memory.id)\n        .where(Memory.tenant_id == tenant_id)\n        .where(Memory.agent_id == agent_id)\n        .where(Memory.memory_type == \"insight\")\n        .where(Memory.status == \"active\")\n        .where(Memory.deleted_at.is_(None))\n        .where(Memory.metadata_[\"insight_focus\"].as_string() == focus)\n        .where(Memory.metadata_[\"insight_scope\"].as_string() == scope)\n    )\n    if fleet_id is not None:\n        prior_stmt = prior_stmt.where(Memory.fleet_id == fleet_id)\n    else:\n        prior_stmt = prior_stmt.where(Memory.fleet_id.is_(None))\n    prior_rows = (await db.execute(prior_stmt)).scalars().all()\n    prior_ids = list(prior_rows)\n\n    from sqlalchemy import update as sql_update\n\n    # Transition prior insights for this focus/scope/fleet to \"outdated\" BEFORE\n    # creating new ones. This prevents semantic-dedup in create_memory from\n    # matching against the prior insight (which has near-identical content\n    # template) and failing the new inserts with 409. We skip this step when\n    # there are no findings to persist — outdating priors would leave the user\n    # with nothing active.\n    if findings and prior_ids:\n        from sqlalchemy.exc import SQLAlchemyError\n\n        try:\n            async with db.begin_nested():\n                await db.execute(\n                    sql_update(Memory)\n                    .where(Memory.id.in_(prior_ids))\n                    .where(Memory.status == \"active\")\n                    .values(status=\"outdated\")\n                )\n            logger.info(\n                \"Superseded %d prior %s insights for agent=%s\",\n                len(prior_ids),\n                focus,\n                agent_id,\n            )\n        except SQLAlchemyError:\n            logger.warning(\"Failed to supersede prior insights; skipping persist\", exc_info=True)\n            return [None] * len(findings)\n\n    # Empty-findings short-circuit: ``BulkMemoryCreate.items`` enforces\n    # min_length=1, and the prior-supersede block above already returned\n    # `[None] * len(findings)` for the failure path. An empty findings\n    # list reaches here only when no priors existed either — return\n    # straight away without touching the bulk path.\n    if not findings:","lineStart":421,"lineEnd":780,"totalLines":1113,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","time":{"start":1780727714240,"end":1780727714265}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09525aa501060ea5016a23bfa207e481959b5fb645c7598ea2"}},"id":"prt_e9ba491bf001K66VG6PqiKdj5B","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba46134001IlymZNIpdlKxji"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727714273,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_M9O141i1rymeiYrtIJkAbGdO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","offset":781,"limit":360},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n781:         return []\n782: \n783:     # Build one ``BulkMemoryItem`` per finding so the persist runs as a\n784:     # single ``create_memories_bulk`` call rather than N serial\n785:     # ``create_memory`` round-trips each in their own savepoint (audit\n786:     # finding #29). Per-item error isolation is preserved by the bulk\n787:     # contract — failed rows surface as ``BulkItemResult(status=\"error\")``\n788:     # and become ``None`` in the returned ``insight_ids`` (same shape as\n789:     # the prior per-savepoint exception path).\n790:     #\n791:     # write_mode behaviour change vs the pre-#29 path\n792:     # -----------------------------------------------\n793:     # The previous serial path passed ``write_mode=\"strong\"`` on every\n794:     # ``MemoryCreate``. ``BulkMemoryItem`` carries no ``write_mode``\n795:     # field, and ``create_memories_bulk`` doesn't pick the strong vs fast\n796:     # pipeline per item — so the bulk path effectively drops the strong\n797:     # mode override. The only behavioural delta between the strong and\n798:     # fast pipelines is the inline ``CheckSemanticDuplicate`` step (see\n799:     # ``core_api/pipeline/compositions/write.py``); everything else\n800:     # (embed, enrich, exact-dedup, write, schedule background tasks) is\n801:     # identical. The post-write fire-and-forget tasks — entity extraction,\n802:     # async contradiction detection, deferred enrichment — are still\n803:     # scheduled per memory by the bulk path's ``ScheduleBackgroundTasks``-\n804:     # equivalent loop, so contradiction detection coverage is intact.\n805:     #\n806:     # Why dropping inline semantic dedup is acceptable for insights\n807:     # specifically: the supersede-priors block above ALREADY transitions\n808:     # any prior active insight for this ``insight_focus`` + ``scope`` +\n809:     # ``agent_id`` to ``outdated`` before this persist runs. That handles\n810:     # the cross-run \"same insight regenerated\" dedup case at the\n811:     # type-aware level that matters for insights. Inline semantic dedup\n812:     # would compare each finding against EVERY memory in the tenant\n813:     # (not just insights), which risks blocking a genuinely-novel\n814:     # insight whose content happens to look semantically similar to an\n815:     # unrelated fact. Net: cheaper persist AND fewer false-positive\n816:     # rejections.\n817:     titles: list[str] = []\n818:     items: list[BulkMemoryItem] = []\n819:     for finding in findings:\n820:         title = str(finding.get(\"title\", \"Untitled insight\"))[:80]\n821:         titles.append(title)\n822:         description = str(finding.get(\"description\", \"\"))[:1000]\n823:         recommendation = str(finding.get(\"recommendation\", \"\"))[:500]\n824:         confidence = max(0.0, min(1.0, float(finding.get(\"confidence\", 0.5))))\n825:         related_ids = finding.get(\"related_memory_ids\", [])\n826: \n827:         content = f\"[Insight/{finding.get('type', focus)}] {title}: {description}\"\n828:         if recommendation:\n829:             content += f\" Recommendation: {recommendation}\"\n830: \n831:         # ``BulkMemoryItem`` has no ``title`` field — the title is encoded\n832:         # in ``content`` as \"[Insight/{type}] {title}: {description}\".\n833:         items.append(\n834:             BulkMemoryItem(\n835:                 memory_type=\"insight\",\n836:                 content=content,\n837:                 weight=confidence,\n838:                 metadata={\n839:                     \"insight_focus\": focus,\n840:                     \"insight_scope\": scope,\n841:                     \"insight_type\": finding.get(\"type\", focus),\n842:                     \"related_memory_ids\": [str(rid) for rid in related_ids],\n843:                     \"recommendation\": recommendation,\n844:                     \"confidence\": confidence,\n845:                 },\n846:             )\n847:         )\n848: \n849:     bulk_data = BulkMemoryCreate(\n850:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n851:         fleet_id=fleet_id,\n852:         agent_id=agent_id,\n853:         items=items,\n854:         visibility=_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY.get(scope, \"scope_team\"),\n855:     )\n856:     # Per-attempt id is required by the bulk contract for idempotent\n857:     # retries; insights persist is called from one place per\n858:     # generate_insights invocation, so a fresh uuid4 here is the right\n859:     # granularity (a retry would be a fresh generate_insights call with\n860:     # a new attempt id anyway).\n861:     bulk_attempt_id = f\"insights:{uuid4()}\"\n862: \n863:     insight_ids: list[str | None] = []\n864:     try:\n865:         response = await create_memories_bulk(db, bulk_data, bulk_attempt_id=bulk_attempt_id)\n866:     except Exception:\n867:         logger.exception(\"Bulk persist of insight findings failed entirely\")\n868:         insight_ids = [None] * len(findings)\n869:     else:\n870:         # Bulk contract: ``results`` is aligned to input order, one\n871:         # entry per item. ``id`` is set for ``created`` /\n872:         # ``duplicate_attempt`` / ``duplicate_content``; absent for\n873:         # ``error``.\n874:         by_index = {r.index: r for r in response.results}\n875:         for i, finding_title in enumerate(titles):\n876:             r = by_index.get(i)\n877:             if r is None or r.id is None:\n878:                 if r is not None and r.error:\n879:                     logger.warning(\n880:                         \"Failed to persist insight finding %s: %s\",\n881:                         finding_title,\n882:                         r.error,\n883:                     )\n884:                 else:\n885:                     logger.warning(\n886:                         \"Insight finding %s missing from bulk response\",\n887:                         finding_title,\n888:                     )\n889:                 insight_ids.append(None)\n890:             else:\n891:                 insight_ids.append(str(r.id))\n892: \n893:     # Safety net: if every finding failed to persist, restore the priors we\n894:     # pre-emptively outdated so the user isn't left with nothing active.\n895:     if prior_ids and insight_ids and all(iid is None for iid in insight_ids):\n896:         try:\n897:             async with db.begin_nested():\n898:                 result = await db.execute(\n899:                     sql_update(Memory)\n900:                     .where(Memory.id.in_(prior_ids))\n901:                     .where(Memory.status == \"outdated\")\n902:                     .values(status=\"active\")\n903:                 )\n904:             restored = result.rowcount\n905:             logger.warning(\n906:                 \"All %d insight findings failed to persist; restored %d prior insights to active\",\n907:                 len(findings),\n908:                 restored,\n909:             )\n910:         except Exception:\n911:             logger.warning(\"Failed to restore prior insights after total failure\", exc_info=True)\n912: \n913:     return insight_ids\n914: \n915: \n916: def _to_float(val, default: float = 0.5) -> float:\n917:     try:\n918:         return float(val)\n919:     except (TypeError, ValueError):\n920:         return default\n921: \n922: \n923: # -- Public API ----------------------------------------------------------------\n924: \n925: \n926: async def synthesize_insights(\n927:     memories_or_clusters: list,\n928:     is_clustered: bool,\n929:     config,\n930:     *,\n931:     focus: str,\n932:     scope: str,\n933: ) -> dict:\n934:     \"\"\"LLM-only analysis step. No DB access.\n935: \n936:     Audit finding P3: ``memclaw_insights`` previously held its\n937:     ``_mcp_session()`` open across the multi-second ``_run_llm_analysis``\n938:     round-trip, pinning a pooled DB connection. This helper takes the\n939:     already-queried memories + resolved tenant config and produces the\n940:     same intermediate shape the legacy ``generate_insights`` body\n941:     produced in steps 3-5, so the MCP tool can exit the session block\n942:     before invoking it.\n943: \n944:     Returns\n945:     -------\n946:     dict with:\n947:       - ``findings``: list of sanitized finding dicts\n948:       - ``summary``: LLM-emitted overall summary string\n949:       - ``memories_analyzed``: count of memories that fed the prompt\n950:     \"\"\"\n951:     prompt_template = _PROMPT_DISPATCH[focus]\n952:     if is_clustered:\n953:         memories_text, shown_ids = _format_clusters_for_analysis(memories_or_clusters)\n954:         count = sum(c.get(\"size\", 0) for c in memories_or_clusters)\n955:     else:\n956:         memories_text, shown_ids = _format_memories_for_analysis(memories_or_clusters)\n957:         count = len(memories_or_clusters)\n958:         if focus == \"discover\":\n959:             prompt_template = _PROMPT_DISPATCH[\"patterns\"]\n960: \n961:     # Escape literal braces in memories_text before .format(). Cluster mode\n962:     # always includes Python dict reprs (type_distribution); content mode can\n963:     # include user-controlled `{...}` strings. Without escaping, str.format\n964:     # raises KeyError on any stray `{word}`.\n965:     safe_memories = memories_text.replace(\"{\", \"{{\").replace(\"}\", \"}}\")\n966:     prompt = prompt_template.format(memories=safe_memories, count=count)\n967: \n968:     analysis = await _run_llm_analysis(prompt, config)\n969: \n970:     findings = analysis.get(\"findings\", [])\n971:     if not isinstance(findings, list):\n972:         findings = []\n973:     sanitized = []\n974:     total_dropped = 0\n975:     findings_with_drops = 0\n976:     for f in findings:\n977:         if not isinstance(f, dict):\n978:             continue\n979:         raw_related = [str(rid) for rid in f.get(\"related_memory_ids\", []) if rid]\n980:         kept_related = [rid for rid in raw_related if rid in shown_ids]\n981:         dropped = len(raw_related) - len(kept_related)\n982:         if dropped > 0:\n983:             total_dropped += dropped\n984:             findings_with_drops += 1\n985:         sanitized.append(\n986:             {\n987:                 \"type\": str(f.get(\"type\", focus))[:50],\n988:                 \"title\": str(f.get(\"title\", \"Untitled\"))[:80],\n989:                 \"description\": str(f.get(\"description\", \"\")),\n990:                 \"confidence\": max(0.0, min(1.0, _to_float(f.get(\"confidence\", 0.5)))),\n991:                 \"related_memory_ids\": kept_related,\n992:                 \"recommendation\": str(f.get(\"recommendation\", \"\")),\n993:             }\n994:         )\n995:     if total_dropped > 0:\n996:         logger.info(\n997:             \"insights: dropped %d hallucinated related_memory_ids across %d findings (focus=%s, scope=%s)\",\n998:             total_dropped,\n999:             findings_with_drops,\n1000:             focus,\n1001:             scope,\n1002:         )\n1003: \n1004:     return {\n1005:         \"findings\": sanitized,\n1006:         \"summary\": analysis.get(\"summary\", \"\"),\n1007:         \"memories_analyzed\": count,\n1008:     }\n1009: \n1010: \n1011: async def generate_insights(\n1012:     db: AsyncSession,\n1013:     tenant_id: str,\n1014:     focus: str,\n1015:     scope: str = \"agent\",\n1016:     fleet_id: str | None = None,\n1017:     agent_id: str = \"mcp-agent\",\n1018: ) -> dict:\n1019:     \"\"\"Run an LLM reasoning pass over a targeted memory subset and persist findings.\n1020: \n1021:     Parameters\n1022:     ----------\n1023:     db : AsyncSession\n1024:         Database session.\n1025:     tenant_id : str\n1026:         Tenant identifier.\n1027:     focus : str\n1028:         One of INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES: contradictions, failures, stale,\n1029:         divergence, patterns, discover.\n1030:     scope : str\n1031:         \"agent\", \"fleet\", or \"all\".\n1032:     fleet_id : str | None\n1033:         Required when scope is \"fleet\".\n1034:     agent_id : str\n1035:         Agent identifier, defaults to \"mcp-agent\".\n1036: \n1037:     Returns\n1038:     -------\n1039:     dict\n1040:         Analysis results including findings, summary, persisted insight IDs,\n1041:         and timing information.\n1042:     \"\"\"\n1043:     t0 = time.perf_counter()\n1044: \n1045:     if focus not in INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES:\n1046:         raise HTTPException(\n1047:             status_code=422,\n1048:             detail=f\"Invalid focus '{focus}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES)}\",\n1049:         )\n1050:     if scope not in (\"agent\", \"fleet\", \"all\"):\n1051:         raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=f\"Invalid scope '{scope}'. Must be: agent, fleet, all\")\n1052:     if scope == \"fleet\" and not fleet_id:\n1053:         raise HTTPException(\n1054:             status_code=422,\n1055:             detail=\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\",\n1056:         )\n1057:     if focus == \"divergence\" and scope == \"agent\":\n1058:         raise HTTPException(\n1059:             status_code=422,\n1060:             detail=\"Focus 'divergence' requires scope='fleet' or scope='all' to compare across agents.\",\n1061:         )\n1062: \n1063:     # 1. Query memories based on focus\n1064:     query_fn = _QUERY_DISPATCH[focus]\n1065:     memories_or_clusters = await query_fn(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n1066: \n1067:     if focus == \"discover\" and isinstance(memories_or_clusters, _DiscoverResult):\n1068:         is_clustered = memories_or_clusters.is_clustered\n1069:         memories_or_clusters = memories_or_clusters.data\n1070:     else:\n1071:         is_clustered = False\n1072: \n1073:     if not memories_or_clusters:\n1074:         return {\n1075:             \"focus\": focus,\n1076:             \"scope\": scope,\n1077:             \"memories_analyzed\": 0,\n1078:             \"findings\": [],\n1079:             \"summary\": \"No relevant memories found for this analysis.\",\n1080:             \"insight_memory_ids\": [],\n1081:             \"insights_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n1082:         }\n1083: \n1084:     # 2. Resolve tenant config for LLM provider\n1085:     from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n1086: \n1087:     config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n1088: \n1089:     # 3-5. LLM analysis (no DB). Delegated to ``synthesize_insights`` so\n1090:     # MCP callers that want to release their session before the LLM\n1091:     # round-trip can do so independently (see ``memclaw_insights``).\n1092:     synth = await synthesize_insights(\n1093:         memories_or_clusters,\n1094:         is_clustered,\n1095:         config,\n1096:         focus=focus,\n1097:         scope=scope,\n1098:     )\n1099:     findings = synth[\"findings\"]\n1100: \n1101:     # 6. Persist findings as insight memories\n1102:     insight_ids = await _persist_findings(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id, focus, scope, findings)\n1103:     await db.commit()\n1104: \n1105:     return {\n1106:         \"focus\": focus,\n1107:         \"scope\": scope,\n1108:         \"memories_analyzed\": synth[\"memories_analyzed\"],\n1109:         \"findings\": [{**f, \"insight_memory_id\": mid} for f, mid in zip(findings, insight_ids)],\n1110:         \"summary\": synth[\"summary\"],\n1111:         \"insight_memory_ids\": [mid for mid in insight_ids if mid],\n1112:         \"insights_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n1113:     }\n\n(End of file - total 1113 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"        return []\n\n    # Build one ``BulkMemoryItem`` per finding so the persist runs as a\n    # single ``create_memories_bulk`` call rather than N serial\n    # ``create_memory`` round-trips each in their own savepoint (audit\n    # finding #29). Per-item error isolation is preserved by the bulk\n    # contract — failed rows surface as ``BulkItemResult(status=\"error\")``\n    # and become ``None`` in the returned ``insight_ids`` (same shape as\n    # the prior per-savepoint exception path).\n    #\n    # write_mode behaviour change vs the pre-#29 path\n    # -----------------------------------------------\n    # The previous serial path passed ``write_mode=\"strong\"`` on every\n    # ``MemoryCreate``. ``BulkMemoryItem`` carries no ``write_mode``\n    # field, and ``create_memories_bulk`` doesn't pick the strong vs fast\n    # pipeline per item — so the bulk path effectively drops the strong\n    # mode override. The only behavioural delta between the strong and\n    # fast pipelines is the inline ``CheckSemanticDuplicate`` step (see\n    # ``core_api/pipeline/compositions/write.py``); everything else\n    # (embed, enrich, exact-dedup, write, schedule background tasks) is","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","text":"        return []\n\n    # Build one ``BulkMemoryItem`` per finding so the persist runs as a\n    # single ``create_memories_bulk`` call rather than N serial\n    # ``create_memory`` round-trips each in their own savepoint (audit\n    # finding #29). Per-item error isolation is preserved by the bulk\n    # contract — failed rows surface as ``BulkItemResult(status=\"error\")``\n    # and become ``None`` in the returned ``insight_ids`` (same shape as\n    # the prior per-savepoint exception path).\n    #\n    # write_mode behaviour change vs the pre-#29 path\n    # -----------------------------------------------\n    # The previous serial path passed ``write_mode=\"strong\"`` on every\n    # ``MemoryCreate``. ``BulkMemoryItem`` carries no ``write_mode``\n    # field, and ``create_memories_bulk`` doesn't pick the strong vs fast\n    # pipeline per item — so the bulk path effectively drops the strong\n    # mode override. The only behavioural delta between the strong and\n    # fast pipelines is the inline ``CheckSemanticDuplicate`` step (see\n    # ``core_api/pipeline/compositions/write.py``); everything else\n    # (embed, enrich, exact-dedup, write, schedule background tasks) is\n    # identical. The post-write fire-and-forget tasks — entity extraction,\n    # async contradiction detection, deferred enrichment — are still\n    # scheduled per memory by the bulk path's ``ScheduleBackgroundTasks``-\n    # equivalent loop, so contradiction detection coverage is intact.\n    #\n    # Why dropping inline semantic dedup is acceptable for insights\n    # specifically: the supersede-priors block above ALREADY transitions\n    # any prior active insight for this ``insight_focus`` + ``scope`` +\n    # ``agent_id`` to ``outdated`` before this persist runs. That handles\n    # the cross-run \"same insight regenerated\" dedup case at the\n    # type-aware level that matters for insights. Inline semantic dedup\n    # would compare each finding against EVERY memory in the tenant\n    # (not just insights), which risks blocking a genuinely-novel\n    # insight whose content happens to look semantically similar to an\n    # unrelated fact. Net: cheaper persist AND fewer false-positive\n    # rejections.\n    titles: list[str] = []\n    items: list[BulkMemoryItem] = []\n    for finding in findings:\n        title = str(finding.get(\"title\", \"Untitled insight\"))[:80]\n        titles.append(title)\n        description = str(finding.get(\"description\", \"\"))[:1000]\n        recommendation = str(finding.get(\"recommendation\", \"\"))[:500]\n        confidence = max(0.0, min(1.0, float(finding.get(\"confidence\", 0.5))))\n        related_ids = finding.get(\"related_memory_ids\", [])\n\n        content = f\"[Insight/{finding.get('type', focus)}] {title}: {description}\"\n        if recommendation:\n            content += f\" Recommendation: {recommendation}\"\n\n        # ``BulkMemoryItem`` has no ``title`` field — the title is encoded\n        # in ``content`` as \"[Insight/{type}] {title}: {description}\".\n        items.append(\n            BulkMemoryItem(\n                memory_type=\"insight\",\n                content=content,\n                weight=confidence,\n                metadata={\n                    \"insight_focus\": focus,\n                    \"insight_scope\": scope,\n                    \"insight_type\": finding.get(\"type\", focus),\n                    \"related_memory_ids\": [str(rid) for rid in related_ids],\n                    \"recommendation\": recommendation,\n                    \"confidence\": confidence,\n                },\n            )\n        )\n\n    bulk_data = BulkMemoryCreate(\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,\n        fleet_id=fleet_id,\n        agent_id=agent_id,\n        items=items,\n        visibility=_SCOPE_TO_VISIBILITY.get(scope, \"scope_team\"),\n    )\n    # Per-attempt id is required by the bulk contract for idempotent\n    # retries; insights persist is called from one place per\n    # generate_insights invocation, so a fresh uuid4 here is the right\n    # granularity (a retry would be a fresh generate_insights call with\n    # a new attempt id anyway).\n    bulk_attempt_id = f\"insights:{uuid4()}\"\n\n    insight_ids: list[str | None] = []\n    try:\n        response = await create_memories_bulk(db, bulk_data, bulk_attempt_id=bulk_attempt_id)\n    except Exception:\n        logger.exception(\"Bulk persist of insight findings failed entirely\")\n        insight_ids = [None] * len(findings)\n    else:\n        # Bulk contract: ``results`` is aligned to input order, one\n        # entry per item. ``id`` is set for ``created`` /\n        # ``duplicate_attempt`` / ``duplicate_content``; absent for\n        # ``error``.\n        by_index = {r.index: r for r in response.results}\n        for i, finding_title in enumerate(titles):\n            r = by_index.get(i)\n            if r is None or r.id is None:\n                if r is not None and r.error:\n                    logger.warning(\n                        \"Failed to persist insight finding %s: %s\",\n                        finding_title,\n                        r.error,\n                    )\n                else:\n                    logger.warning(\n                        \"Insight finding %s missing from bulk response\",\n                        finding_title,\n                    )\n                insight_ids.append(None)\n            else:\n                insight_ids.append(str(r.id))\n\n    # Safety net: if every finding failed to persist, restore the priors we\n    # pre-emptively outdated so the user isn't left with nothing active.\n    if prior_ids and insight_ids and all(iid is None for iid in insight_ids):\n        try:\n            async with db.begin_nested():\n                result = await db.execute(\n                    sql_update(Memory)\n                    .where(Memory.id.in_(prior_ids))\n                    .where(Memory.status == \"outdated\")\n                    .values(status=\"active\")\n                )\n            restored = result.rowcount\n            logger.warning(\n                \"All %d insight findings failed to persist; restored %d prior insights to active\",\n                len(findings),\n                restored,\n            )\n        except Exception:\n            logger.warning(\"Failed to restore prior insights after total failure\", exc_info=True)\n\n    return insight_ids\n\n\ndef _to_float(val, default: float = 0.5) -> float:\n    try:\n        return float(val)\n    except (TypeError, ValueError):\n        return default\n\n\n# -- Public API ----------------------------------------------------------------\n\n\nasync def synthesize_insights(\n    memories_or_clusters: list,\n    is_clustered: bool,\n    config,\n    *,\n    focus: str,\n    scope: str,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"LLM-only analysis step. No DB access.\n\n    Audit finding P3: ``memclaw_insights`` previously held its\n    ``_mcp_session()`` open across the multi-second ``_run_llm_analysis``\n    round-trip, pinning a pooled DB connection. This helper takes the\n    already-queried memories + resolved tenant config and produces the\n    same intermediate shape the legacy ``generate_insights`` body\n    produced in steps 3-5, so the MCP tool can exit the session block\n    before invoking it.\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    dict with:\n      - ``findings``: list of sanitized finding dicts\n      - ``summary``: LLM-emitted overall summary string\n      - ``memories_analyzed``: count of memories that fed the prompt\n    \"\"\"\n    prompt_template = _PROMPT_DISPATCH[focus]\n    if is_clustered:\n        memories_text, shown_ids = _format_clusters_for_analysis(memories_or_clusters)\n        count = sum(c.get(\"size\", 0) for c in memories_or_clusters)\n    else:\n        memories_text, shown_ids = _format_memories_for_analysis(memories_or_clusters)\n        count = len(memories_or_clusters)\n        if focus == \"discover\":\n            prompt_template = _PROMPT_DISPATCH[\"patterns\"]\n\n    # Escape literal braces in memories_text before .format(). Cluster mode\n    # always includes Python dict reprs (type_distribution); content mode can\n    # include user-controlled `{...}` strings. Without escaping, str.format\n    # raises KeyError on any stray `{word}`.\n    safe_memories = memories_text.replace(\"{\", \"{{\").replace(\"}\", \"}}\")\n    prompt = prompt_template.format(memories=safe_memories, count=count)\n\n    analysis = await _run_llm_analysis(prompt, config)\n\n    findings = analysis.get(\"findings\", [])\n    if not isinstance(findings, list):\n        findings = []\n    sanitized = []\n    total_dropped = 0\n    findings_with_drops = 0\n    for f in findings:\n        if not isinstance(f, dict):\n            continue\n        raw_related = [str(rid) for rid in f.get(\"related_memory_ids\", []) if rid]\n        kept_related = [rid for rid in raw_related if rid in shown_ids]\n        dropped = len(raw_related) - len(kept_related)\n        if dropped > 0:\n            total_dropped += dropped\n            findings_with_drops += 1\n        sanitized.append(\n            {\n                \"type\": str(f.get(\"type\", focus))[:50],\n                \"title\": str(f.get(\"title\", \"Untitled\"))[:80],\n                \"description\": str(f.get(\"description\", \"\")),\n                \"confidence\": max(0.0, min(1.0, _to_float(f.get(\"confidence\", 0.5)))),\n                \"related_memory_ids\": kept_related,\n                \"recommendation\": str(f.get(\"recommendation\", \"\")),\n            }\n        )\n    if total_dropped > 0:\n        logger.info(\n            \"insights: dropped %d hallucinated related_memory_ids across %d findings (focus=%s, scope=%s)\",\n            total_dropped,\n            findings_with_drops,\n            focus,\n            scope,\n        )\n\n    return {\n        \"findings\": sanitized,\n        \"summary\": analysis.get(\"summary\", \"\"),\n        \"memories_analyzed\": count,\n    }\n\n\nasync def generate_insights(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    focus: str,\n    scope: str = \"agent\",\n    fleet_id: str | None = None,\n    agent_id: str = \"mcp-agent\",\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Run an LLM reasoning pass over a targeted memory subset and persist findings.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    db : AsyncSession\n        Database session.\n    tenant_id : str\n        Tenant identifier.\n    focus : str\n        One of INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES: contradictions, failures, stale,\n        divergence, patterns, discover.\n    scope : str\n        \"agent\", \"fleet\", or \"all\".\n    fleet_id : str | None\n        Required when scope is \"fleet\".\n    agent_id : str\n        Agent identifier, defaults to \"mcp-agent\".\n\n    Returns\n    -------\n    dict\n        Analysis results including findings, summary, persisted insight IDs,\n        and timing information.\n    \"\"\"\n    t0 = time.perf_counter()\n\n    if focus not in INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=f\"Invalid focus '{focus}'. Must be one of: {', '.join(INSIGHTS_FOCUS_MODES)}\",\n        )\n    if scope not in (\"agent\", \"fleet\", \"all\"):\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=422, detail=f\"Invalid scope '{scope}'. Must be: agent, fleet, all\")\n    if scope == \"fleet\" and not fleet_id:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=\"fleet_id is required when scope is 'fleet'.\",\n        )\n    if focus == \"divergence\" and scope == \"agent\":\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=422,\n            detail=\"Focus 'divergence' requires scope='fleet' or scope='all' to compare across agents.\",\n        )\n\n    # 1. Query memories based on focus\n    query_fn = _QUERY_DISPATCH[focus]\n    memories_or_clusters = await query_fn(db, tenant_id, fleet_id, agent_id, scope)\n\n    if focus == \"discover\" and isinstance(memories_or_clusters, _DiscoverResult):\n        is_clustered = memories_or_clusters.is_clustered\n        memories_or_clusters = memories_or_clusters.data\n    else:\n        is_clustered = False\n\n    if not memories_or_clusters:\n        return {\n            \"focus\": focus,\n            \"scope\": scope,\n            \"memories_analyzed\": 0,\n            \"findings\": [],\n            \"summary\": \"No relevant memories found for this analysis.\",\n            \"insight_memory_ids\": [],\n            \"insights_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n        }\n\n    # 2. Resolve tenant config for LLM provider\n    from core_api.services.organization_settings import resolve_config\n\n    config = await resolve_config(db, tenant_id)\n\n    # 3-5. LLM analysis (no DB). Delegated to ``synthesize_insights`` so\n    # MCP callers that want to release their session before the LLM\n    # round-trip can do so independently (see ``memclaw_insights``).\n    synth = await synthesize_insights(\n        memories_or_clusters,\n        is_clustered,\n        config,\n        focus=focus,\n        scope=scope,\n    )\n    findings = synth[\"findings\"]\n\n    # 6. Persist findings as insight memories\n    insight_ids = await _persist_findings(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id, focus, scope, findings)\n    await db.commit()\n\n    return {\n        \"focus\": focus,\n        \"scope\": scope,\n        \"memories_analyzed\": synth[\"memories_analyzed\"],\n        \"findings\": [{**f, \"insight_memory_id\": mid} for f, mid in zip(findings, insight_ids)],\n        \"summary\": synth[\"summary\"],\n        \"insight_memory_ids\": [mid for mid in insight_ids if mid],\n        \"insights_ms\": int((time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000),\n    }","lineStart":781,"lineEnd":1113,"totalLines":1113,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/insights_service.py","time":{"start":1780727714242,"end":1780727714271}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_09525aa501060ea5016a23bfa207ec8195986fb3ffb2068329"}},"id":"prt_e9ba491c1001O4t9q7ubDSM4C4","sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","messageID":"msg_e9ba46134001IlymZNIpdlKxji"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780727714288,"sessionID":"ses_1645cad34ffe2dSeSw3HI64S6Y","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_RFnTb78IYkHROYv1SsgevCS5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"weight|recall_count|last_recalled_at|composite|importance|freshness|graph boost|ORDER BY|similarity","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api","include":"*.py"},"output":"Found 508 matches (showing first 100)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:\n  Line 591:     weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"0-1 (single only).\")] = None,\n\n  Line 649:                         weight=weight,\n\n  Line 745:     weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"op=update; 0-1.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 951:                             \"weight\": memory.weight,\n\n  Line 957:                             \"last_recalled_at\": (\n\n  Line 958:                                 memory.last_recalled_at.isoformat()\n\n  Line 959:                                 if getattr(memory, \"last_recalled_at\", None)\n\n  Line 962:                             \"recall_count\": getattr(memory, \"recall_count\", 0),\n\n  Line 1024:                 if weight is not None:\n\n  Line 1025:                     fields[\"weight\"] = weight\n\n  Line 1097:     min_similarity: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"0.1-0.9.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 1098:     fts_weight: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"0=semantic, 1=keyword.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 1099:     freshness_floor: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"0-1.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 1100:     freshness_decay_days: Annotated[int | None, Field(description=\"7-730.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 1104:     similarity_blend: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"0-1.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 1121:             min_similarity=min_similarity,\n\n  Line 1122:             fts_weight=fts_weight,\n\n  Line 1123:             freshness_floor=freshness_floor,\n\n  Line 1124:             freshness_decay_days=freshness_decay_days,\n\n  Line 1128:             similarity_blend=similarity_blend,\n\n  Line 1444:                         \"similarity\": round(sim, 4),\n\n  Line 1511:     weight_min: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"Min weight 0-1.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 1512:     weight_max: Annotated[float | None, Field(description=\"Max weight 0-1.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 1515:     sort: Annotated[str, Field(description=\"created_at|weight|recall_count.\")] = \"created_at\",\n\n  Line 1548:     if sort not in {\"created_at\", \"weight\", \"recall_count\"}:\n\n  Line 1552:                 f\"Invalid sort '{sort}'. Must be one of: created_at, weight, recall_count.\",\n\n  Line 1644:             weight_min=weight_min,\n\n  Line 1645:             weight_max=weight_max,\n\n  Line 1954:     action: adjust weights, generate preventive rules on failure. Closes the\n\n  Line 2002:     #   3. session 2 — _apply_outcome_to_db (weights + persist + backfill + commit)\n\n  Line 2118:     Includes tenant + fleet + agent-scope rules ordered by weight.\n\n  Line 2169:     weight: Annotated[str | None, Field(description=\"op=set: low|med|high.\")] = None,\n\n  Line 2260:                     \"weight\": weight,\n\n  Line 2366:                 # Storage owns scope/weight/fleet/agent shape validation;\n\n  Line 2382:                     \"weight\": weight,  # type: ignore[typeddict-item]\n\n  Line 2403:                         \"weight\": weight,\n\n  Line 2500:             # storage-side 422 (bad scope/weight) raises this — surface\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api